{"type":"tool_execution_end","toolCallId":"functions.mcp:0","toolName":"mcp","result":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 29\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630022841\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nremaining_ms: 887016\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"after_version\":29,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630022841\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C5\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the dispute is not whether the May 2026 Russia-Ukraine war ended, whether the May 9-11 pause was perfectly honored, or whether every later market-platform statement was correct. The proposition asks a narrower question: by the May 31 deadline, had the parties officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that was general in character rather than merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or a future framework? On this record, the answer should be yes.\\n\\nThe case-packet evidence gives the governing lens. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d, states that an official ceasefire agreement qualifies if it is publicly announced and mutually agreed, and that a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement had been reached can suffice. It excludes informal arrangements, humanitarian pauses, energy- or Black Sea-only deals, and future frameworks without an explicit dated commitment to stop fighting. That definition matters because the proof here points to a dated May 9-May 11 ceasefire, not simply aspirational peace talks.\\n\\nThe strongest plaintiff proof in the existing packet is the convergence between official-source material and credible reporting. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, identifies a Kremlin source in which Yury Ushakov, speaking on instructions from President Putin, confirmed Russia’s acceptance of the U.S.-proposed ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and located the key agreement in the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. The same file records that Ukrainian-side confirmation is currently captured through Ukrinform because direct access to the Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in the packet environment. That creates a provenance gap we should fill later, but it is not a contradiction.\\n\\nThe secondary-reporting record, ev_cf0c77f2fe52, then supplies the market rule’s alternative path: multiple credible outlets and ISW are summarized as reporting that Russia and Ukraine confirmed or agreed to a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11, with suspension of kinetic activity and an associated 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, preserves the same source map and correctly warns that platform assertions are not independent proof. I accept that warning. Our case rests on the official and reporting source chain, not on the market’s final Yes label.\\n\\nThe defense will have real points to test. The Russian official framing connects the pause to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform appears narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, candidly identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s social-media confirmation, the Ukrainian presidential page, Trump’s announcement, and battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused generally. It also notes alleged violations and continuing hostilities around the period. Those issues affect weight and may affect how the council evaluates scope and implementation.\\n\\nBut those gaps do not change the core theory. A qualifying agreement can be temporary. It can be attached to a prisoner exchange. It can be violated after it is reached. The decisive question is whether the parties publicly and officially agreed to halt military engagement generally for a dated period, not whether the ceasefire became a lasting peace or achieved perfect compliance. The packet’s plaintiff-side evidence already points to both sides confirming a three-day suspension of kinetic activity, while the defense evidence mainly argues motive, context, and performance.\\n\\nIn the next evidence phase, the plaintiff should admit the strongest underlying sources: the Kremlin page, the best accessible Ukrainian official or official-adjacent confirmation, direct presidential or U.S. announcement records if obtainable, and implementation/violation assessments from ISW or similar monitors. Those materials will let the council separate three questions: agreement reached, scope of the agreed halt, and compliance in the field. For opening purposes, the record supports the plaintiff’s framing: this was not merely an informal understanding or a future framework, but an officially announced, mutually confirmed, dated ceasefire agreement broad enough to satisfy the proposition by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the thing this market asked for, not a nearby diplomatic event. The proposition requires an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict by May 31, 2026. It expressly excludes humanitarian pauses, limited arrangements, and future or partial frameworks.\\n\\nThe current packet does not yet carry that burden. It contains useful leads, but the strongest record materials point to a narrower event: a brief May 9-May 11 arrangement tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and a prisoner exchange. The market-page file, ev_f841be6ff80d, gives the rule and its exclusions, but it also warns that page-context assertions are platform assertions, not independent proof. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, repeats that caution: platform language cannot itself establish official mutuality, theatre-wide scope, implementation, or reliable consensus.\\n\\nThe official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, is where the burden problem becomes concrete. The Russian official text is not framed as a general pause in the conflict; it confirms Russia’s acceptance of a U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange, with the key agreement being a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during the May 9-May 11 period. On the Ukrainian side, the packet does not preserve a direct official presidential page; direct access reportedly returned 403. The available official-adjacent capture is Ukrinform’s report about a presidential decree that appears limited to allowing the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding Red Square from Ukrainian targeting during the parade. That is a substantial provenance and scope gap.\\n\\nThe plaintiff will rely on ev_cf0c77f2fe52, which summarizes credible reporting that both sides confirmed a three-day ceasefire. We do not ignore that. Secondary reporting may help find the underlying record and may later corroborate a mutual announcement. But at opening, those reports sit beside the packet’s own defense leads: Victory Day timing, Red Square security, prisoner-exchange purpose, allegations of violations, and ongoing retaliatory activity around the period. Those facts matter because the market did not ask whether some pause, some prisoner-exchange deconfliction, or some symbolic holiday arrangement occurred. It asked whether the parties had reached a general pause in military engagement.\\n\\nNor is this merely a compliance argument. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been agreed. But if the evidence shows the arrangement was designed and announced around a prisoner swap and parade security, and if fighting materially continued, that bears on whether the agreement was general in character at all. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, identifies the missing proof the council should want before finding for plaintiff: direct Zelenskyy confirmation, the direct Ukrainian presidential decree, direct Trump or White House announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence of whether hostilities generally paused, and complete official post-period violation statements.\\n\\nIn the evidence phase, the defense will test exactly those links: the full Kremlin text, the inaccessible Ukrainian decree or an authenticated archive, any direct Ukrainian presidential social-media confirmation, the U.S. announcement, ISW and other monitoring assessments, and post-period official violation statements. If those sources show a mutual, official, theatre-wide halt, plaintiff may have a case. If they show a short Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement amid continuing hostilities, the proposition fails.\\n\\nFor now, the packet supports caution, not a finding. Plaintiff’s opening treats a temporary three-day ceasefire label as enough. The market language demands more: a general pause in the conflict. On this record, the decisive proof is missing or points narrower, and the council should hold plaintiff to that burden.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the missing bridge the defense asked for. The record no longer rests only on the case packet. The admitted source captures show a public, mutual, dated ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine before the May 31 deadline, and the language used was broad enough to constitute a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. PX-1, the market-page record, requires an official ceasefire agreement: a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement. It excludes informal, humanitarian-only, energy-only, Black Sea-only, or future-framework arrangements. It also allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. That is exactly what the merits evidence now shows.\\n\\nPX-3, the Guardian May 8 capture, reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11. Its key points track the rule: Trump announced a ceasefire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine”; the ceasefire included suspension of all “kinetic activity”; and it was “confirmed by both sides.” The same capture records Ukrainian confirmation by Zelenskyy and Russian confirmation by Kremlin adviser Yury Ushakov. This is not a future framework. It is a dated ceasefire, announced before the deadline, with both parties identified.\\n\\nPX-4 directly answers the defense’s Ukrainian-source objection. Ukrainska Pravda, sourcing Zelenskyy on X, reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Trump’s truce with Russia for May 9-11 and quoted him saying Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement to conduct the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. That is Ukrainian-side public confirmation of Russia’s agreement and of the ceasefire regime. It is not merely a Red Square decree.\\n\\nPX-5 adds the U.S. announcement and the mutual-confirmation frame. RFE/RL reports Trump’s announcement of a three-day cease-fire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine,” including “suspension of all Kinetic activity,” and says both sides quickly confirmed the truce and prisoner swap. It also reports that Putin aide Yury Ushakov said Russia agreed to the three-day cease-fire and prisoner exchange. PX-2, the case-packet official-source record, independently preserves the Kremlin source path and confirms the Russian official framing.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is context: Victory Day, Red Square, and prisoner exchange. But context is not the same as limitation. A ceasefire can have an occasion and still be general in scope. A prisoner exchange can be conducted during a general ceasefire; it does not convert the ceasefire into a humanitarian-only pause when the announced term is suspension of all kinetic activity in the war between the two states. Likewise, the Red Square decree may be narrow by itself, but PX-4 and PX-5 show broader Ukrainian confirmation alongside that narrow parade-security action.\\n\\nThe defense also points to violations and continued activity. That matters for compliance, not formation. The proposition asks whether the parties had officially reached the public mutual halt by May 31. It does not require that no shot was later fired. PX-5 candidly includes adverse context: reports of earlier violations, strikes, and retaliatory claims around the period. Those facts show why compliance was contested, but they do not erase the public mutual agreement reported and confirmed on May 8.\\n\\nProvenance and custody: the five case-packet files are juror-visible case-packet evidence. PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5 were submitted in this merits phase as text captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and descriptions; AAR accepted each and assigned evidence IDs. Direct X pages and some official pages were hard to capture in this environment, but the accepted evidence faithfully preserves the relevant source-chain content and is corroborated across independent outlets and the existing official-source packet.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, plaintiff need not prove a lasting peace or flawless battlefield silence. The better reading of the admitted evidence is that by May 8, before the May 31 deadline, Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire in the war, including suspension of kinetic activity. That satisfies the proposition.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has improved the record, but not enough to satisfy the proposition. The record now supports that a three-day truce was publicly discussed and confirmed around May 8. The remaining question is whether that truce constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange arrangement. On this record, the better answer remains no.\\n\\nStart with the rule. DX-1, the market-page record, requires more than any official ceasefire label. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited agreements and requires a general pause in the conflict. That scope requirement does real work here.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own proof shows why. PX-4 says Zelenskyy framed the arrangement this way: within U.S.-mediated negotiations, Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and a ceasefire regime “must also be established” on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 likewise ties Trump’s announcement to a prisoner swap and reports Zelenskyy ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the Victory Day parade. DX-2, the official-source packet, is even narrower on the Russian side: Ushakov confirmed Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and the packet’s Ukrainian official-adjacent decree record is limited to Red Square/parade targeting. Those are not side details. They are the public shape of the deal.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat “suspension of all kinetic activity” as dispositive. But the source chain remains mostly media-captured, with direct X, Truth Social, and official Ukrainian decree captures still missing. More importantly, an announced aspiration to suspend kinetic activity does not resolve whether the parties actually reached a general conflict pause, as opposed to a brief operational deconfliction attached to POW exchange and parade security. The burden is plaintiff’s, and ambiguity on scope counts against them.\\n\\nThe implementation evidence confirms that ambiguity. DX-4, the NV/ISW capture, reports Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It says intensity decreased but did not stop, Ukraine reported 51 combat engagements, Russian forces continued strikes in Kharkiv and Kherson Oblasts, and Russia claimed thousands of Ukrainian violations. It also reports ISW’s assessment that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions and that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square, which Kyiv upheld. That is powerful evidence that the practical, defined commitment was narrow.\\n\\nDX-5, CBS/AP’s May 10 report, shows the same pattern during the supposed pause. Both sides accused each other of breaking the ceasefire; Zelenskyy said Russia was not observing the truce and that there was no calm in frontline areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks; Russia accused Ukraine of more than 1,000 violations and said it responded in kind. CBS/AP also noted the three-day pause’s timeline was somewhat unclear. This is not offered to impose a perfect-compliance requirement. It is offered because widespread continued operations, undefined conditions, and mutual “response in kind” claims are probative of what kind of arrangement was actually reached.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s best legal point is that an agreement can be violated and still be an agreement. Correct. But the proposition is not “was there an agreement called a ceasefire?” It asks whether there was a general pause in military engagement. Formation and scope are intertwined: if the only clearly defined official condition was Red Square non-targeting, if Russia’s official acceptance described a prisoner-exchange purpose, if the exchange did not even occur as the announced 1,000-for-1,000 event during the truce period on this record, and if operations continued across the theater, then plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause by a preponderance.\\n\\nProvenance matters too. Plaintiff’s new exhibits are accepted text captures from reputable outlets, but they remain secondary captures of hard-to-access primary statements. The case-packet itself, DX-3, flags the same gaps: missing direct Zelenskyy social-media confirmation, missing direct Ukrainian presidential decree, missing direct Trump/White House record, and missing battlefield/monitoring evidence. Defendant filled part of that last gap with DX-4 and DX-5, and the result undercuts plaintiff’s scope theory.\\n\\nSearch and capture ledger: I checked targeted May 9-11 ceasefire-violation and ISW queries after reading plaintiff’s exhibits. ISW May 9-11 assessments appeared as the strongest implementation target; accessible captures were preserved through NV’s ISW summary and CBS/AP’s contemporaneous violation report. A Guardian May 9 Red Square/frontline article was opened but not submitted because DX-4 and DX-5 more directly address implementation and scope.\\n\\nThe council can find that a short truce was announced. It should not find that plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition. The admitted evidence shows a fragile, underdefined, prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with continued frontline operations, not a publicly agreed general pause in the Russia-Ukraine conflict.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s new evidence proves the wrong point. DX-4 and DX-5 are evidence of poor compliance, weak monitoring, and violation accusations. They are not evidence that the May 8 agreement was merely Red Square-only or that no official public mutual ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nThat distinction matters because the proposition and PX-1 focus on whether the parties had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt by May 31. The market rule even says a qualifying agreement can resolve Yes if officially reached before the resolution date regardless of later start mechanics. Defendant’s evidence is mostly about what happened after the agreement was announced.\\n\\nDX-4, the NV/ISW capture, says fighting intensity decreased but did not stop completely. It reports continued operations and weak ceasefire mechanisms. But it also states President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 exchange. DX-5, the CBS/AP capture, likewise reports accusations of violations, but it also states Trump announced Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire and that both sides appeared to agree. These are concessions on formation.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn noncompliance into narrow scope. That does not follow. A general ceasefire with poor monitoring can be violated. A general ceasefire can be attached to a prisoner exchange. A general ceasefire can coincide with Victory Day. None of those facts converts broad language like “ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine” and “suspension of all kinetic activity” into a Red Square-only arrangement.\\n\\nThe best scope evidence remains PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5. PX-3 says both sides confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire and suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-4 gives the Ukrainian-side confirmation: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement and a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 gives the U.S. announcement and both-side confirmation: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides.\\n\\nThe Red Square material is narrower, but it is not the whole agreement. It is an additional operational commitment about parade targeting. The prisoner exchange is likewise not disqualifying. The market excludes humanitarian pauses, but this record does not show a prisoner-exchange-only corridor or a local evacuation window. It shows a ceasefire in the war, with all kinetic activity suspended, plus a prisoner swap during that pause.\\n\\nDefendant also leans on missing primary captures. Those gaps affect weight, and plaintiff disclosed them. But the rule expressly permits wide credible media consensus, and the accepted captures are mutually reinforcing: Guardian, Ukrainska Pravda, RFE/RL, and the case-packet official-source record all converge on public mutual confirmation. Defendant’s own exhibits do not break that chain; they accept the announcement and agreement, then dispute implementation.\\n\\nSo the actual evidentiary balance is this: plaintiff has multiple accepted sources proving official public mutual agreement to a dated ceasefire with broad kinetic-activity language. Defendant has sources proving the ceasefire was fragile and violated. Under a preponderance standard, the former satisfies the proposition; the latter does not rewrite it.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal is right about one thing but draws the wrong conclusion. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been reached. If the record showed a clearly defined general pause followed by isolated breaches, defendant would lose that point.\\n\\nBut DX-4 and DX-5 are not just breach evidence. They are scope and character evidence. DX-4 reports that, on the first day of the supposed May 9-11 general pause, Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline; combat declined but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and ISW assessed that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most importantly, DX-4 says the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade. That does not look like a defined, general halt in military engagement. It looks like a fragile holiday/prisoner-exchange deconfliction with one concrete parade-security condition.\\n\\nDX-5 is similar. Plaintiff stresses that CBS/AP says both sides appeared to agree. But the same exhibit says the timeline was somewhat unclear, both sides accused each other of breaking the truce, Zelenskyy said there was no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and Russia claimed it responded in kind. Again, defendant is not saying every violation voids formation. Defendant is saying the record as a whole does not show the qualifying thing: a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nThat distinction is why plaintiff’s “formation not compliance” framing is too narrow. The proposition contains a scope element. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. The official-source packet says Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange. Plaintiff’s Ukrainian-side evidence likewise puts the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange at the center, and the direct Ukrainian decree remains missing while the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square-specific. Plaintiff’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase is powerful, but it is mostly preserved through media captures, not through the unavailable primary posts, and it must be weighed against the operational evidence that no defined general pause actually existed.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat announcement language as enough and implementation as irrelevant. The market does not permit that shortcut. It asks whether the parties reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. Where the public official detail is prisoner exchange and Red Square, the conditions are undefined, and fighting continued across the theater from the first day, plaintiff has not carried that stricter burden by a preponderance.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record resolves this case on a preponderance standard.\\n\\nThe proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It does not ask whether the war ended, whether the ceasefire was durable, or whether neither side later accused the other of violations.\\n\\nThe decisive record is straightforward. PX-1 defines the qualifying event as an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and permits a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. PX-3 reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, that Trump announced it as a ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, that it included suspension of all kinetic activity, and that it was confirmed by both sides. PX-4 supplies Ukrainian-side confirmation: Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 truce with Russia, said Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement, and said a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 supplies the U.S. announcement and the same mutual-confirmation frame: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides, including Russian agreement through Ushakov. PX-2 independently preserves the Russian official-source path.\\n\\nThat evidence satisfies the elements: official/public, mutual, dated before the deadline, and general in the only sense the market required: a halt in military engagement in the war, not a sector-only Black Sea or energy arrangement, not a mere informal understanding, and not a future framework.\\n\\nThe defense’s contrary evidence is important, but it points mainly to performance. DX-4 and DX-5 show continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. We should not ignore that. But both exhibits also preserve the formation facts: Trump announced the ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. A breached ceasefire is still a ceasefire agreement. The proposition turns on whether the agreement was reached, not whether it was perfectly obeyed.\\n\\nThe defense says the prisoner exchange and Victory Day context make the pause non-general. The better reading is that they explain why the parties accepted a temporary general pause. A prisoner exchange can occur during a broad ceasefire; it does not make the ceasefire humanitarian-only when the announced scope is suspension of all kinetic activity. Red Square non-targeting was an additional concrete operational condition, not the whole agreement. The record contains separate broader language: ceasefire in the war, ceasefire regime on May 9-11, suspension of kinetic activity, and both sides confirmed.\\n\\nThere are source-chain gaps: direct X, Truth Social, and some official pages were hard to capture. But the market rule expressly allows credible media consensus, and here the accepted sources converge with the case-packet official-source record. The defense’s own evidence does not break that convergence; it disputes execution.\\n\\nOn balance, plaintiff’s evidence proves more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed May 9-11 halt in military engagement before May 31. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case is not about whether something happened on May 8. Something did. The record supports that a short May 9-11 truce was announced and that both sides were reported as accepting it. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition: an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause, limited arrangement, or future framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. The market-page record requires a general pause and excludes humanitarian and limited agreements. That means the council cannot stop at the word “ceasefire” or at the fact of a public announcement. It must ask what kind of ceasefire the record proves.\\n\\nThe official-source packet supplies the best answer. Russia’s official source, through Ushakov, accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.” The key agreement described there was a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during May 9-11. On the Ukrainian official side, the direct presidential decree was not captured; the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square and parade-specific. Those facts do not prove a theatre-wide general pause. They prove a prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with a concrete parade-security component.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own merits exhibits do not eliminate that limitation. PX-4 quotes Zelenskyy in the context of the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and says a ceasefire regime must also be established. PX-5 reports the Trump announcement but also says Zelenskyy ordered no attack on Red Square and preserves the same prisoner-swap frame. Yes, those sources use broad language such as “suspension of all kinetic activity.” But broad media language must be weighed against the actual official-source detail, the missing primary captures, and what the parties did when the supposed general pause began.\\n\\nThat implementation evidence is decisive because it goes to character and scope, not merely breach. DX-4 reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day; combat intensity decreased but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most tellingly, DX-4 reports that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square. DX-5 reports no calm in front line areas, mutual violation accusations, an unclear timeline, and Russian “response in kind.”\\n\\nPlaintiff says violations are only compliance. If this were a clearly defined general ceasefire followed by isolated breaches, that would be right. But the record shows something different: undefined conditions, the one clearly public operational term being Red Square, a prisoner-exchange purpose, and continued operations across the theater from day one. That is evidence that the arrangement never rose to the general pause required by the proposition.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce caution. Direct X or Telegram, direct Truth Social or White House, and the direct Ukrainian decree remain absent. The rule allows credible media consensus, but consensus reporting does not override ambiguity in the official-source record and battlefield evidence. At most, plaintiff proved a fragile, short, U.S.-brokered truce label attached to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The market required more.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, if the evidence is equally consistent with a limited prisoner-exchange/parade-security pause and a qualifying general pause, plaintiff loses. Here the limiting evidence is stronger than equal. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and resolution criteria\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Official-source case-packet record\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Guardian both-sides confirmation report\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Ukrainian-side Zelensky confirmation report\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 RFE/RL Trump announcement and both-sides confirmation\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule requiring general pause and excluding limited/humanitarian pauses\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Official-source packet: Russian prisoner-exchange framing and narrow Ukrainian decree capture\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Unresolved record gaps and known tension on scope/violations\\n# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 NV/ISW: continued offensive operations and undefined ceasefire conditions\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 CBS/AP: mutual violation accusations and no calm on front lines\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-4/DX-6 Zelenskyy report tying ceasefire regime to prisoner exchange\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-5/DX-7 RFE/RL report with Red Square and adverse violation context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Guardian broad ceasefire confirmation\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Zelenskyy confirmation of ceasefire regime\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 RFE/RL both-side confirmation and adverse context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R4 Defendant NV/ISW exhibit showing compliance dispute, not no agreement\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R5 Defendant CBS/AP exhibit showing both sides appeared to agree\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 NV/ISW: continued operations and unclear conditions as scope evidence\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 CBS/AP: mutual violations, unclear timeline, no calm on front line\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Official-source packet: prisoner-exchange and Red Square framing\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S4 Market rule requiring a general pause, not limited/humanitarian arrangements\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 8 2026 report: Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire (ev_236dce43c3d8_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-236dce43c3d8)\\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\\nSHA-256: `236dce43c3d8f0a768feb3c9aa5e4214f9afb219b3cc647e8679b1179e916c6c`\\nBytes: 1583\\nRelevance: Credible media report that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, suspension of kinetic activity, and prisoner swap; directly addresses public mutual agreement and scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026: Zelenskyy confirms truce with Russia on May 9-11 (ev_2c8cd49d9b00_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-2c8cd49d9b00)\\nSource: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033888/\\nSHA-256: `2c8cd49d9b0040da3a58b04496b028fae6de5fb2b66b02d1f9b68b7bb84bbcac`\\nBytes: 1248\\nRelevance: Ukrainian media report based on Zelenskyy on X/Twitter confirming Russia's agreement and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11; addresses Ukrainian-side public confirmation.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] RFE/RL May 8 2026: Trump announces three-day cease-fire; both sides confirm (ev_5d2cebff6f4b_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2cebff6f4b)\\nSource: https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-russia-victory-day-cease-fire-drone-attacks/33752482.html\\nSHA-256: `5d2cebff6f4b0f521cbfa77b06da6f8548e1352caa5fc5983a21cf59c675b46a`\\nBytes: 1405\\nRelevance: Report preserving Trump announcement, confirmation by both sides, suspension of kinetic activity, prisoner swap, and adverse context of earlier violations; addresses official public agreement and scope/compliance distinction.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] NV May 10 2026 report on ISW assessment: fighting continued during first day of ceasefire (ev_52a3277a9302_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-52a3277a9302)\\nSource: https://english.nv.ua/russian-war/isw-says-fighting-continued-despite-may-9-11-ceasefire-50606640.html\\nSHA-256: `52a3277a93024fbf92cdd1f34c2ebf0ee4a62600c40ffa7809cd520718baba32`\\nBytes: 1823\\nRelevance: Shows adverse implementation and scope evidence: offensive operations continued across the frontline, combat declined but did not stop, ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, only known condition was Red Square non-targeting, and Russian forces allegedly used the period to reinforce positions.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] CBS/AP May 10 2026: Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating ceasefire (ev_d5ef4e09892f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-d5ef4e09892f)\\nSource: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/russia-ukraine-accuse-each-other-ceasefire-violations/\\nSHA-256: `d5ef4e09892f541e4806e0e6d705f5472ab9890cf4567bf47bf3a56b73f03dd8`\\nBytes: 1606\\nRelevance: Shows contemporaneous post-agreement evidence that both sides accused each other of violations, Zelenskyy said there was no calm on front lines despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and the ceasefire timing was unclear; bears on whether the arrangement was a general pause rather than fragile/limited truce.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and capture ledger\\nPlaintiff searched official and source-specific paths for the May 8-11 ceasefire record. Successful captures submitted as evidence: Guardian May 8 report, Ukrainska Pravda May 8 Zelenskyy confirmation report, and RFE/RL May 8 Trump/both-sides confirmation report. Existing case-packet evidence supplies market criteria and a Kremlin official-source summary. Capture limits: direct X pages for Zelenskyy and WhiteHouse rendered no text in web open; PBS returned 403; Ukrinform opened without readable lines; ISW May 8/May 11 direct pages returned 403; earlier curl to the Kremlin page timed out. These failures leave some primary-source gaps, but the accepted captures preserve the material source-chain content and include adverse context on alleged violations.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nAt merits, defendant inspected the new plaintiff evidence and searched targeted terms for May 9-11 ceasefire scope, violations, and ISW assessments. Source targets included ISW May 9-11 assessments, accessible media captures of those assessments, and contemporaneous violation reports. Defendant submitted accepted captures from NV/ISW and CBS/AP. Direct primary social/official sources remain incompletely captured in the record, including direct Zelenskyy X/Telegram, Trump Truth Social/White House, and president.gov.ua decree text; those gaps affect weight because plaintiff relies heavily on secondary captures for scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff rebuttal evidence audit\\nPlaintiff inspected the two new defendant exhibits by stat/read_evidence_range. Both primarily address implementation: continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. Both also preserve or concede agreement facts: Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. No additional outside source was needed for this targeted rebuttal.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:22.654219585Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887016,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":13},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":18,\"version\":29}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 29\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630022841\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nremaining_ms: 887016\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"after_version\":29,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630022841\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C5\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the dispute is not whether the May 2026 Russia-Ukraine war ended, whether the May 9-11 pause was perfectly honored, or whether every later market-platform statement was correct. The proposition asks a narrower question: by the May 31 deadline, had the parties officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that was general in character rather than merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or a future framework? On this record, the answer should be yes.\\n\\nThe case-packet evidence gives the governing lens. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d, states that an official ceasefire agreement qualifies if it is publicly announced and mutually agreed, and that a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement had been reached can suffice. It excludes informal arrangements, humanitarian pauses, energy- or Black Sea-only deals, and future frameworks without an explicit dated commitment to stop fighting. That definition matters because the proof here points to a dated May 9-May 11 ceasefire, not simply aspirational peace talks.\\n\\nThe strongest plaintiff proof in the existing packet is the convergence between official-source material and credible reporting. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, identifies a Kremlin source in which Yury Ushakov, speaking on instructions from President Putin, confirmed Russia’s acceptance of the U.S.-proposed ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and located the key agreement in the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. The same file records that Ukrainian-side confirmation is currently captured through Ukrinform because direct access to the Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in the packet environment. That creates a provenance gap we should fill later, but it is not a contradiction.\\n\\nThe secondary-reporting record, ev_cf0c77f2fe52, then supplies the market rule’s alternative path: multiple credible outlets and ISW are summarized as reporting that Russia and Ukraine confirmed or agreed to a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11, with suspension of kinetic activity and an associated 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, preserves the same source map and correctly warns that platform assertions are not independent proof. I accept that warning. Our case rests on the official and reporting source chain, not on the market’s final Yes label.\\n\\nThe defense will have real points to test. The Russian official framing connects the pause to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform appears narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, candidly identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s social-media confirmation, the Ukrainian presidential page, Trump’s announcement, and battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused generally. It also notes alleged violations and continuing hostilities around the period. Those issues affect weight and may affect how the council evaluates scope and implementation.\\n\\nBut those gaps do not change the core theory. A qualifying agreement can be temporary. It can be attached to a prisoner exchange. It can be violated after it is reached. The decisive question is whether the parties publicly and officially agreed to halt military engagement generally for a dated period, not whether the ceasefire became a lasting peace or achieved perfect compliance. The packet’s plaintiff-side evidence already points to both sides confirming a three-day suspension of kinetic activity, while the defense evidence mainly argues motive, context, and performance.\\n\\nIn the next evidence phase, the plaintiff should admit the strongest underlying sources: the Kremlin page, the best accessible Ukrainian official or official-adjacent confirmation, direct presidential or U.S. announcement records if obtainable, and implementation/violation assessments from ISW or similar monitors. Those materials will let the council separate three questions: agreement reached, scope of the agreed halt, and compliance in the field. For opening purposes, the record supports the plaintiff’s framing: this was not merely an informal understanding or a future framework, but an officially announced, mutually confirmed, dated ceasefire agreement broad enough to satisfy the proposition by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the thing this market asked for, not a nearby diplomatic event. The proposition requires an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict by May 31, 2026. It expressly excludes humanitarian pauses, limited arrangements, and future or partial frameworks.\\n\\nThe current packet does not yet carry that burden. It contains useful leads, but the strongest record materials point to a narrower event: a brief May 9-May 11 arrangement tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and a prisoner exchange. The market-page file, ev_f841be6ff80d, gives the rule and its exclusions, but it also warns that page-context assertions are platform assertions, not independent proof. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, repeats that caution: platform language cannot itself establish official mutuality, theatre-wide scope, implementation, or reliable consensus.\\n\\nThe official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, is where the burden problem becomes concrete. The Russian official text is not framed as a general pause in the conflict; it confirms Russia’s acceptance of a U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange, with the key agreement being a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during the May 9-May 11 period. On the Ukrainian side, the packet does not preserve a direct official presidential page; direct access reportedly returned 403. The available official-adjacent capture is Ukrinform’s report about a presidential decree that appears limited to allowing the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding Red Square from Ukrainian targeting during the parade. That is a substantial provenance and scope gap.\\n\\nThe plaintiff will rely on ev_cf0c77f2fe52, which summarizes credible reporting that both sides confirmed a three-day ceasefire. We do not ignore that. Secondary reporting may help find the underlying record and may later corroborate a mutual announcement. But at opening, those reports sit beside the packet’s own defense leads: Victory Day timing, Red Square security, prisoner-exchange purpose, allegations of violations, and ongoing retaliatory activity around the period. Those facts matter because the market did not ask whether some pause, some prisoner-exchange deconfliction, or some symbolic holiday arrangement occurred. It asked whether the parties had reached a general pause in military engagement.\\n\\nNor is this merely a compliance argument. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been agreed. But if the evidence shows the arrangement was designed and announced around a prisoner swap and parade security, and if fighting materially continued, that bears on whether the agreement was general in character at all. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, identifies the missing proof the council should want before finding for plaintiff: direct Zelenskyy confirmation, the direct Ukrainian presidential decree, direct Trump or White House announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence of whether hostilities generally paused, and complete official post-period violation statements.\\n\\nIn the evidence phase, the defense will test exactly those links: the full Kremlin text, the inaccessible Ukrainian decree or an authenticated archive, any direct Ukrainian presidential social-media confirmation, the U.S. announcement, ISW and other monitoring assessments, and post-period official violation statements. If those sources show a mutual, official, theatre-wide halt, plaintiff may have a case. If they show a short Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement amid continuing hostilities, the proposition fails.\\n\\nFor now, the packet supports caution, not a finding. Plaintiff’s opening treats a temporary three-day ceasefire label as enough. The market language demands more: a general pause in the conflict. On this record, the decisive proof is missing or points narrower, and the council should hold plaintiff to that burden.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the missing bridge the defense asked for. The record no longer rests only on the case packet. The admitted source captures show a public, mutual, dated ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine before the May 31 deadline, and the language used was broad enough to constitute a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. PX-1, the market-page record, requires an official ceasefire agreement: a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement. It excludes informal, humanitarian-only, energy-only, Black Sea-only, or future-framework arrangements. It also allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. That is exactly what the merits evidence now shows.\\n\\nPX-3, the Guardian May 8 capture, reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11. Its key points track the rule: Trump announced a ceasefire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine”; the ceasefire included suspension of all “kinetic activity”; and it was “confirmed by both sides.” The same capture records Ukrainian confirmation by Zelenskyy and Russian confirmation by Kremlin adviser Yury Ushakov. This is not a future framework. It is a dated ceasefire, announced before the deadline, with both parties identified.\\n\\nPX-4 directly answers the defense’s Ukrainian-source objection. Ukrainska Pravda, sourcing Zelenskyy on X, reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Trump’s truce with Russia for May 9-11 and quoted him saying Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement to conduct the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. That is Ukrainian-side public confirmation of Russia’s agreement and of the ceasefire regime. It is not merely a Red Square decree.\\n\\nPX-5 adds the U.S. announcement and the mutual-confirmation frame. RFE/RL reports Trump’s announcement of a three-day cease-fire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine,” including “suspension of all Kinetic activity,” and says both sides quickly confirmed the truce and prisoner swap. It also reports that Putin aide Yury Ushakov said Russia agreed to the three-day cease-fire and prisoner exchange. PX-2, the case-packet official-source record, independently preserves the Kremlin source path and confirms the Russian official framing.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is context: Victory Day, Red Square, and prisoner exchange. But context is not the same as limitation. A ceasefire can have an occasion and still be general in scope. A prisoner exchange can be conducted during a general ceasefire; it does not convert the ceasefire into a humanitarian-only pause when the announced term is suspension of all kinetic activity in the war between the two states. Likewise, the Red Square decree may be narrow by itself, but PX-4 and PX-5 show broader Ukrainian confirmation alongside that narrow parade-security action.\\n\\nThe defense also points to violations and continued activity. That matters for compliance, not formation. The proposition asks whether the parties had officially reached the public mutual halt by May 31. It does not require that no shot was later fired. PX-5 candidly includes adverse context: reports of earlier violations, strikes, and retaliatory claims around the period. Those facts show why compliance was contested, but they do not erase the public mutual agreement reported and confirmed on May 8.\\n\\nProvenance and custody: the five case-packet files are juror-visible case-packet evidence. PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5 were submitted in this merits phase as text captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and descriptions; AAR accepted each and assigned evidence IDs. Direct X pages and some official pages were hard to capture in this environment, but the accepted evidence faithfully preserves the relevant source-chain content and is corroborated across independent outlets and the existing official-source packet.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, plaintiff need not prove a lasting peace or flawless battlefield silence. The better reading of the admitted evidence is that by May 8, before the May 31 deadline, Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire in the war, including suspension of kinetic activity. That satisfies the proposition.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has improved the record, but not enough to satisfy the proposition. The record now supports that a three-day truce was publicly discussed and confirmed around May 8. The remaining question is whether that truce constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange arrangement. On this record, the better answer remains no.\\n\\nStart with the rule. DX-1, the market-page record, requires more than any official ceasefire label. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited agreements and requires a general pause in the conflict. That scope requirement does real work here.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own proof shows why. PX-4 says Zelenskyy framed the arrangement this way: within U.S.-mediated negotiations, Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and a ceasefire regime “must also be established” on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 likewise ties Trump’s announcement to a prisoner swap and reports Zelenskyy ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the Victory Day parade. DX-2, the official-source packet, is even narrower on the Russian side: Ushakov confirmed Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and the packet’s Ukrainian official-adjacent decree record is limited to Red Square/parade targeting. Those are not side details. They are the public shape of the deal.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat “suspension of all kinetic activity” as dispositive. But the source chain remains mostly media-captured, with direct X, Truth Social, and official Ukrainian decree captures still missing. More importantly, an announced aspiration to suspend kinetic activity does not resolve whether the parties actually reached a general conflict pause, as opposed to a brief operational deconfliction attached to POW exchange and parade security. The burden is plaintiff’s, and ambiguity on scope counts against them.\\n\\nThe implementation evidence confirms that ambiguity. DX-4, the NV/ISW capture, reports Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It says intensity decreased but did not stop, Ukraine reported 51 combat engagements, Russian forces continued strikes in Kharkiv and Kherson Oblasts, and Russia claimed thousands of Ukrainian violations. It also reports ISW’s assessment that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions and that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square, which Kyiv upheld. That is powerful evidence that the practical, defined commitment was narrow.\\n\\nDX-5, CBS/AP’s May 10 report, shows the same pattern during the supposed pause. Both sides accused each other of breaking the ceasefire; Zelenskyy said Russia was not observing the truce and that there was no calm in frontline areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks; Russia accused Ukraine of more than 1,000 violations and said it responded in kind. CBS/AP also noted the three-day pause’s timeline was somewhat unclear. This is not offered to impose a perfect-compliance requirement. It is offered because widespread continued operations, undefined conditions, and mutual “response in kind” claims are probative of what kind of arrangement was actually reached.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s best legal point is that an agreement can be violated and still be an agreement. Correct. But the proposition is not “was there an agreement called a ceasefire?” It asks whether there was a general pause in military engagement. Formation and scope are intertwined: if the only clearly defined official condition was Red Square non-targeting, if Russia’s official acceptance described a prisoner-exchange purpose, if the exchange did not even occur as the announced 1,000-for-1,000 event during the truce period on this record, and if operations continued across the theater, then plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause by a preponderance.\\n\\nProvenance matters too. Plaintiff’s new exhibits are accepted text captures from reputable outlets, but they remain secondary captures of hard-to-access primary statements. The case-packet itself, DX-3, flags the same gaps: missing direct Zelenskyy social-media confirmation, missing direct Ukrainian presidential decree, missing direct Trump/White House record, and missing battlefield/monitoring evidence. Defendant filled part of that last gap with DX-4 and DX-5, and the result undercuts plaintiff’s scope theory.\\n\\nSearch and capture ledger: I checked targeted May 9-11 ceasefire-violation and ISW queries after reading plaintiff’s exhibits. ISW May 9-11 assessments appeared as the strongest implementation target; accessible captures were preserved through NV’s ISW summary and CBS/AP’s contemporaneous violation report. A Guardian May 9 Red Square/frontline article was opened but not submitted because DX-4 and DX-5 more directly address implementation and scope.\\n\\nThe council can find that a short truce was announced. It should not find that plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition. The admitted evidence shows a fragile, underdefined, prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with continued frontline operations, not a publicly agreed general pause in the Russia-Ukraine conflict.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s new evidence proves the wrong point. DX-4 and DX-5 are evidence of poor compliance, weak monitoring, and violation accusations. They are not evidence that the May 8 agreement was merely Red Square-only or that no official public mutual ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nThat distinction matters because the proposition and PX-1 focus on whether the parties had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt by May 31. The market rule even says a qualifying agreement can resolve Yes if officially reached before the resolution date regardless of later start mechanics. Defendant’s evidence is mostly about what happened after the agreement was announced.\\n\\nDX-4, the NV/ISW capture, says fighting intensity decreased but did not stop completely. It reports continued operations and weak ceasefire mechanisms. But it also states President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 exchange. DX-5, the CBS/AP capture, likewise reports accusations of violations, but it also states Trump announced Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire and that both sides appeared to agree. These are concessions on formation.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn noncompliance into narrow scope. That does not follow. A general ceasefire with poor monitoring can be violated. A general ceasefire can be attached to a prisoner exchange. A general ceasefire can coincide with Victory Day. None of those facts converts broad language like “ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine” and “suspension of all kinetic activity” into a Red Square-only arrangement.\\n\\nThe best scope evidence remains PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5. PX-3 says both sides confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire and suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-4 gives the Ukrainian-side confirmation: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement and a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 gives the U.S. announcement and both-side confirmation: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides.\\n\\nThe Red Square material is narrower, but it is not the whole agreement. It is an additional operational commitment about parade targeting. The prisoner exchange is likewise not disqualifying. The market excludes humanitarian pauses, but this record does not show a prisoner-exchange-only corridor or a local evacuation window. It shows a ceasefire in the war, with all kinetic activity suspended, plus a prisoner swap during that pause.\\n\\nDefendant also leans on missing primary captures. Those gaps affect weight, and plaintiff disclosed them. But the rule expressly permits wide credible media consensus, and the accepted captures are mutually reinforcing: Guardian, Ukrainska Pravda, RFE/RL, and the case-packet official-source record all converge on public mutual confirmation. Defendant’s own exhibits do not break that chain; they accept the announcement and agreement, then dispute implementation.\\n\\nSo the actual evidentiary balance is this: plaintiff has multiple accepted sources proving official public mutual agreement to a dated ceasefire with broad kinetic-activity language. Defendant has sources proving the ceasefire was fragile and violated. Under a preponderance standard, the former satisfies the proposition; the latter does not rewrite it.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal is right about one thing but draws the wrong conclusion. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been reached. If the record showed a clearly defined general pause followed by isolated breaches, defendant would lose that point.\\n\\nBut DX-4 and DX-5 are not just breach evidence. They are scope and character evidence. DX-4 reports that, on the first day of the supposed May 9-11 general pause, Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline; combat declined but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and ISW assessed that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most importantly, DX-4 says the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade. That does not look like a defined, general halt in military engagement. It looks like a fragile holiday/prisoner-exchange deconfliction with one concrete parade-security condition.\\n\\nDX-5 is similar. Plaintiff stresses that CBS/AP says both sides appeared to agree. But the same exhibit says the timeline was somewhat unclear, both sides accused each other of breaking the truce, Zelenskyy said there was no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and Russia claimed it responded in kind. Again, defendant is not saying every violation voids formation. Defendant is saying the record as a whole does not show the qualifying thing: a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nThat distinction is why plaintiff’s “formation not compliance” framing is too narrow. The proposition contains a scope element. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. The official-source packet says Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange. Plaintiff’s Ukrainian-side evidence likewise puts the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange at the center, and the direct Ukrainian decree remains missing while the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square-specific. Plaintiff’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase is powerful, but it is mostly preserved through media captures, not through the unavailable primary posts, and it must be weighed against the operational evidence that no defined general pause actually existed.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat announcement language as enough and implementation as irrelevant. The market does not permit that shortcut. It asks whether the parties reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. Where the public official detail is prisoner exchange and Red Square, the conditions are undefined, and fighting continued across the theater from the first day, plaintiff has not carried that stricter burden by a preponderance.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record resolves this case on a preponderance standard.\\n\\nThe proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It does not ask whether the war ended, whether the ceasefire was durable, or whether neither side later accused the other of violations.\\n\\nThe decisive record is straightforward. PX-1 defines the qualifying event as an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and permits a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. PX-3 reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, that Trump announced it as a ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, that it included suspension of all kinetic activity, and that it was confirmed by both sides. PX-4 supplies Ukrainian-side confirmation: Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 truce with Russia, said Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement, and said a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 supplies the U.S. announcement and the same mutual-confirmation frame: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides, including Russian agreement through Ushakov. PX-2 independently preserves the Russian official-source path.\\n\\nThat evidence satisfies the elements: official/public, mutual, dated before the deadline, and general in the only sense the market required: a halt in military engagement in the war, not a sector-only Black Sea or energy arrangement, not a mere informal understanding, and not a future framework.\\n\\nThe defense’s contrary evidence is important, but it points mainly to performance. DX-4 and DX-5 show continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. We should not ignore that. But both exhibits also preserve the formation facts: Trump announced the ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. A breached ceasefire is still a ceasefire agreement. The proposition turns on whether the agreement was reached, not whether it was perfectly obeyed.\\n\\nThe defense says the prisoner exchange and Victory Day context make the pause non-general. The better reading is that they explain why the parties accepted a temporary general pause. A prisoner exchange can occur during a broad ceasefire; it does not make the ceasefire humanitarian-only when the announced scope is suspension of all kinetic activity. Red Square non-targeting was an additional concrete operational condition, not the whole agreement. The record contains separate broader language: ceasefire in the war, ceasefire regime on May 9-11, suspension of kinetic activity, and both sides confirmed.\\n\\nThere are source-chain gaps: direct X, Truth Social, and some official pages were hard to capture. But the market rule expressly allows credible media consensus, and here the accepted sources converge with the case-packet official-source record. The defense’s own evidence does not break that convergence; it disputes execution.\\n\\nOn balance, plaintiff’s evidence proves more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed May 9-11 halt in military engagement before May 31. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case is not about whether something happened on May 8. Something did. The record supports that a short May 9-11 truce was announced and that both sides were reported as accepting it. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition: an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause, limited arrangement, or future framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. The market-page record requires a general pause and excludes humanitarian and limited agreements. That means the council cannot stop at the word “ceasefire” or at the fact of a public announcement. It must ask what kind of ceasefire the record proves.\\n\\nThe official-source packet supplies the best answer. Russia’s official source, through Ushakov, accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.” The key agreement described there was a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during May 9-11. On the Ukrainian official side, the direct presidential decree was not captured; the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square and parade-specific. Those facts do not prove a theatre-wide general pause. They prove a prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with a concrete parade-security component.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own merits exhibits do not eliminate that limitation. PX-4 quotes Zelenskyy in the context of the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and says a ceasefire regime must also be established. PX-5 reports the Trump announcement but also says Zelenskyy ordered no attack on Red Square and preserves the same prisoner-swap frame. Yes, those sources use broad language such as “suspension of all kinetic activity.” But broad media language must be weighed against the actual official-source detail, the missing primary captures, and what the parties did when the supposed general pause began.\\n\\nThat implementation evidence is decisive because it goes to character and scope, not merely breach. DX-4 reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day; combat intensity decreased but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most tellingly, DX-4 reports that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square. DX-5 reports no calm in front line areas, mutual violation accusations, an unclear timeline, and Russian “response in kind.”\\n\\nPlaintiff says violations are only compliance. If this were a clearly defined general ceasefire followed by isolated breaches, that would be right. But the record shows something different: undefined conditions, the one clearly public operational term being Red Square, a prisoner-exchange purpose, and continued operations across the theater from day one. That is evidence that the arrangement never rose to the general pause required by the proposition.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce caution. Direct X or Telegram, direct Truth Social or White House, and the direct Ukrainian decree remain absent. The rule allows credible media consensus, but consensus reporting does not override ambiguity in the official-source record and battlefield evidence. At most, plaintiff proved a fragile, short, U.S.-brokered truce label attached to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The market required more.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, if the evidence is equally consistent with a limited prisoner-exchange/parade-security pause and a qualifying general pause, plaintiff loses. Here the limiting evidence is stronger than equal. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and resolution criteria\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Official-source case-packet record\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Guardian both-sides confirmation report\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Ukrainian-side Zelensky confirmation report\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 RFE/RL Trump announcement and both-sides confirmation\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule requiring general pause and excluding limited/humanitarian pauses\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Official-source packet: Russian prisoner-exchange framing and narrow Ukrainian decree capture\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Unresolved record gaps and known tension on scope/violations\\n# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 NV/ISW: continued offensive operations and undefined ceasefire conditions\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 CBS/AP: mutual violation accusations and no calm on front lines\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-4/DX-6 Zelenskyy report tying ceasefire regime to prisoner exchange\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-5/DX-7 RFE/RL report with Red Square and adverse violation context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Guardian broad ceasefire confirmation\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Zelenskyy confirmation of ceasefire regime\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 RFE/RL both-side confirmation and adverse context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R4 Defendant NV/ISW exhibit showing compliance dispute, not no agreement\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R5 Defendant CBS/AP exhibit showing both sides appeared to agree\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 NV/ISW: continued operations and unclear conditions as scope evidence\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 CBS/AP: mutual violations, unclear timeline, no calm on front line\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Official-source packet: prisoner-exchange and Red Square framing\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S4 Market rule requiring a general pause, not limited/humanitarian arrangements\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 8 2026 report: Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire (ev_236dce43c3d8_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-236dce43c3d8)\\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\\nSHA-256: `236dce43c3d8f0a768feb3c9aa5e4214f9afb219b3cc647e8679b1179e916c6c`\\nBytes: 1583\\nRelevance: Credible media report that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, suspension of kinetic activity, and prisoner swap; directly addresses public mutual agreement and scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026: Zelenskyy confirms truce with Russia on May 9-11 (ev_2c8cd49d9b00_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-2c8cd49d9b00)\\nSource: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033888/\\nSHA-256: `2c8cd49d9b0040da3a58b04496b028fae6de5fb2b66b02d1f9b68b7bb84bbcac`\\nBytes: 1248\\nRelevance: Ukrainian media report based on Zelenskyy on X/Twitter confirming Russia's agreement and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11; addresses Ukrainian-side public confirmation.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] RFE/RL May 8 2026: Trump announces three-day cease-fire; both sides confirm (ev_5d2cebff6f4b_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2cebff6f4b)\\nSource: https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-russia-victory-day-cease-fire-drone-attacks/33752482.html\\nSHA-256: `5d2cebff6f4b0f521cbfa77b06da6f8548e1352caa5fc5983a21cf59c675b46a`\\nBytes: 1405\\nRelevance: Report preserving Trump announcement, confirmation by both sides, suspension of kinetic activity, prisoner swap, and adverse context of earlier violations; addresses official public agreement and scope/compliance distinction.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] NV May 10 2026 report on ISW assessment: fighting continued during first day of ceasefire (ev_52a3277a9302_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-52a3277a9302)\\nSource: https://english.nv.ua/russian-war/isw-says-fighting-continued-despite-may-9-11-ceasefire-50606640.html\\nSHA-256: `52a3277a93024fbf92cdd1f34c2ebf0ee4a62600c40ffa7809cd520718baba32`\\nBytes: 1823\\nRelevance: Shows adverse implementation and scope evidence: offensive operations continued across the frontline, combat declined but did not stop, ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, only known condition was Red Square non-targeting, and Russian forces allegedly used the period to reinforce positions.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] CBS/AP May 10 2026: Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating ceasefire (ev_d5ef4e09892f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-d5ef4e09892f)\\nSource: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/russia-ukraine-accuse-each-other-ceasefire-violations/\\nSHA-256: `d5ef4e09892f541e4806e0e6d705f5472ab9890cf4567bf47bf3a56b73f03dd8`\\nBytes: 1606\\nRelevance: Shows contemporaneous post-agreement evidence that both sides accused each other of violations, Zelenskyy said there was no calm on front lines despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and the ceasefire timing was unclear; bears on whether the arrangement was a general pause rather than fragile/limited truce.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and capture ledger\\nPlaintiff searched official and source-specific paths for the May 8-11 ceasefire record. Successful captures submitted as evidence: Guardian May 8 report, Ukrainska Pravda May 8 Zelenskyy confirmation report, and RFE/RL May 8 Trump/both-sides confirmation report. Existing case-packet evidence supplies market criteria and a Kremlin official-source summary. Capture limits: direct X pages for Zelenskyy and WhiteHouse rendered no text in web open; PBS returned 403; Ukrinform opened without readable lines; ISW May 8/May 11 direct pages returned 403; earlier curl to the Kremlin page timed out. These failures leave some primary-source gaps, but the accepted captures preserve the material source-chain content and include adverse context on alleged violations.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nAt merits, defendant inspected the new plaintiff evidence and searched targeted terms for May 9-11 ceasefire scope, violations, and ISW assessments. Source targets included ISW May 9-11 assessments, accessible media captures of those assessments, and contemporaneous violation reports. Defendant submitted accepted captures from NV/ISW and CBS/AP. Direct primary social/official sources remain incompletely captured in the record, including direct Zelenskyy X/Telegram, Trump Truth Social/White House, and president.gov.ua decree text; those gaps affect weight because plaintiff relies heavily on secondary captures for scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff rebuttal evidence audit\\nPlaintiff inspected the two new defendant exhibits by stat/read_evidence_range. Both primarily address implementation: continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. Both also preserve or concede agreement facts: Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. No additional outside source was needed for this targeted rebuttal.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:22.654219585Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887016,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":13},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":18,\"version\":29}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C5","after_version":29,"case_id":"arb-ex07-20260630022841","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C5","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C5\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the dispute is not whether the May 2026 Russia-Ukraine war ended, whether the May 9-11 pause was perfectly honored, or whether every later market-platform statement was correct. The proposition asks a narrower question: by the May 31 deadline, had the parties officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that was general in character rather than merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or a future framework? On this record, the answer should be yes.\n\nThe case-packet evidence gives the governing lens. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d, states that an official ceasefire agreement qualifies if it is publicly announced and mutually agreed, and that a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement had been reached can suffice. It excludes informal arrangements, humanitarian pauses, energy- or Black Sea-only deals, and future frameworks without an explicit dated commitment to stop fighting. That definition matters because the proof here points to a dated May 9-May 11 ceasefire, not simply aspirational peace talks.\n\nThe strongest plaintiff proof in the existing packet is the convergence between official-source material and credible reporting. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, identifies a Kremlin source in which Yury Ushakov, speaking on instructions from President Putin, confirmed Russia’s acceptance of the U.S.-proposed ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and located the key agreement in the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. The same file records that Ukrainian-side confirmation is currently captured through Ukrinform because direct access to the Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in the packet environment. That creates a provenance gap we should fill later, but it is not a contradiction.\n\nThe secondary-reporting record, ev_cf0c77f2fe52, then supplies the market rule’s alternative path: multiple credible outlets and ISW are summarized as reporting that Russia and Ukraine confirmed or agreed to a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11, with suspension of kinetic activity and an associated 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, preserves the same source map and correctly warns that platform assertions are not independent proof. I accept that warning. Our case rests on the official and reporting source chain, not on the market’s final Yes label.\n\nThe defense will have real points to test. The Russian official framing connects the pause to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform appears narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, candidly identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s social-media confirmation, the Ukrainian presidential page, Trump’s announcement, and battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused generally. It also notes alleged violations and continuing hostilities around the period. Those issues affect weight and may affect how the council evaluates scope and implementation.\n\nBut those gaps do not change the core theory. A qualifying agreement can be temporary. It can be attached to a prisoner exchange. It can be violated after it is reached. The decisive question is whether the parties publicly and officially agreed to halt military engagement generally for a dated period, not whether the ceasefire became a lasting peace or achieved perfect compliance. The packet’s plaintiff-side evidence already points to both sides confirming a three-day suspension of kinetic activity, while the defense evidence mainly argues motive, context, and performance.\n\nIn the next evidence phase, the plaintiff should admit the strongest underlying sources: the Kremlin page, the best accessible Ukrainian official or official-adjacent confirmation, direct presidential or U.S. announcement records if obtainable, and implementation/violation assessments from ISW or similar monitors. Those materials will let the council separate three questions: agreement reached, scope of the agreed halt, and compliance in the field. For opening purposes, the record supports the plaintiff’s framing: this was not merely an informal understanding or a future framework, but an officially announced, mutually confirmed, dated ceasefire agreement broad enough to satisfy the proposition by a preponderance of the evidence.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the thing this market asked for, not a nearby diplomatic event. The proposition requires an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict by May 31, 2026. It expressly excludes humanitarian pauses, limited arrangements, and future or partial frameworks.\n\nThe current packet does not yet carry that burden. It contains useful leads, but the strongest record materials point to a narrower event: a brief May 9-May 11 arrangement tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and a prisoner exchange. The market-page file, ev_f841be6ff80d, gives the rule and its exclusions, but it also warns that page-context assertions are platform assertions, not independent proof. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, repeats that caution: platform language cannot itself establish official mutuality, theatre-wide scope, implementation, or reliable consensus.\n\nThe official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, is where the burden problem becomes concrete. The Russian official text is not framed as a general pause in the conflict; it confirms Russia’s acceptance of a U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange, with the key agreement being a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during the May 9-May 11 period. On the Ukrainian side, the packet does not preserve a direct official presidential page; direct access reportedly returned 403. The available official-adjacent capture is Ukrinform’s report about a presidential decree that appears limited to allowing the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding Red Square from Ukrainian targeting during the parade. That is a substantial provenance and scope gap.\n\nThe plaintiff will rely on ev_cf0c77f2fe52, which summarizes credible reporting that both sides confirmed a three-day ceasefire. We do not ignore that. Secondary reporting may help find the underlying record and may later corroborate a mutual announcement. But at opening, those reports sit beside the packet’s own defense leads: Victory Day timing, Red Square security, prisoner-exchange purpose, allegations of violations, and ongoing retaliatory activity around the period. Those facts matter because the market did not ask whether some pause, some prisoner-exchange deconfliction, or some symbolic holiday arrangement occurred. It asked whether the parties had reached a general pause in military engagement.\n\nNor is this merely a compliance argument. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been agreed. But if the evidence shows the arrangement was designed and announced around a prisoner swap and parade security, and if fighting materially continued, that bears on whether the agreement was general in character at all. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, identifies the missing proof the council should want before finding for plaintiff: direct Zelenskyy confirmation, the direct Ukrainian presidential decree, direct Trump or White House announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence of whether hostilities generally paused, and complete official post-period violation statements.\n\nIn the evidence phase, the defense will test exactly those links: the full Kremlin text, the inaccessible Ukrainian decree or an authenticated archive, any direct Ukrainian presidential social-media confirmation, the U.S. announcement, ISW and other monitoring assessments, and post-period official violation statements. If those sources show a mutual, official, theatre-wide halt, plaintiff may have a case. If they show a short Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement amid continuing hostilities, the proposition fails.\n\nFor now, the packet supports caution, not a finding. Plaintiff’s opening treats a temporary three-day ceasefire label as enough. The market language demands more: a general pause in the conflict. On this record, the decisive proof is missing or points narrower, and the council should hold plaintiff to that burden.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the missing bridge the defense asked for. The record no longer rests only on the case packet. The admitted source captures show a public, mutual, dated ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine before the May 31 deadline, and the language used was broad enough to constitute a general halt in military engagement.\n\nStart with the governing rule. PX-1, the market-page record, requires an official ceasefire agreement: a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement. It excludes informal, humanitarian-only, energy-only, Black Sea-only, or future-framework arrangements. It also allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. That is exactly what the merits evidence now shows.\n\nPX-3, the Guardian May 8 capture, reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11. Its key points track the rule: Trump announced a ceasefire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine”; the ceasefire included suspension of all “kinetic activity”; and it was “confirmed by both sides.” The same capture records Ukrainian confirmation by Zelenskyy and Russian confirmation by Kremlin adviser Yury Ushakov. This is not a future framework. It is a dated ceasefire, announced before the deadline, with both parties identified.\n\nPX-4 directly answers the defense’s Ukrainian-source objection. Ukrainska Pravda, sourcing Zelenskyy on X, reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Trump’s truce with Russia for May 9-11 and quoted him saying Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement to conduct the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. That is Ukrainian-side public confirmation of Russia’s agreement and of the ceasefire regime. It is not merely a Red Square decree.\n\nPX-5 adds the U.S. announcement and the mutual-confirmation frame. RFE/RL reports Trump’s announcement of a three-day cease-fire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine,” including “suspension of all Kinetic activity,” and says both sides quickly confirmed the truce and prisoner swap. It also reports that Putin aide Yury Ushakov said Russia agreed to the three-day cease-fire and prisoner exchange. PX-2, the case-packet official-source record, independently preserves the Kremlin source path and confirms the Russian official framing.\n\nThe defense’s best point is context: Victory Day, Red Square, and prisoner exchange. But context is not the same as limitation. A ceasefire can have an occasion and still be general in scope. A prisoner exchange can be conducted during a general ceasefire; it does not convert the ceasefire into a humanitarian-only pause when the announced term is suspension of all kinetic activity in the war between the two states. Likewise, the Red Square decree may be narrow by itself, but PX-4 and PX-5 show broader Ukrainian confirmation alongside that narrow parade-security action.\n\nThe defense also points to violations and continued activity. That matters for compliance, not formation. The proposition asks whether the parties had officially reached the public mutual halt by May 31. It does not require that no shot was later fired. PX-5 candidly includes adverse context: reports of earlier violations, strikes, and retaliatory claims around the period. Those facts show why compliance was contested, but they do not erase the public mutual agreement reported and confirmed on May 8.\n\nProvenance and custody: the five case-packet files are juror-visible case-packet evidence. PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5 were submitted in this merits phase as text captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and descriptions; AAR accepted each and assigned evidence IDs. Direct X pages and some official pages were hard to capture in this environment, but the accepted evidence faithfully preserves the relevant source-chain content and is corroborated across independent outlets and the existing official-source packet.\n\nOn a preponderance standard, plaintiff need not prove a lasting peace or flawless battlefield silence. The better reading of the admitted evidence is that by May 8, before the May 31 deadline, Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire in the war, including suspension of kinetic activity. That satisfies the proposition.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has improved the record, but not enough to satisfy the proposition. The record now supports that a three-day truce was publicly discussed and confirmed around May 8. The remaining question is whether that truce constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange arrangement. On this record, the better answer remains no.\n\nStart with the rule. DX-1, the market-page record, requires more than any official ceasefire label. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited agreements and requires a general pause in the conflict. That scope requirement does real work here.\n\nPlaintiff’s own proof shows why. PX-4 says Zelenskyy framed the arrangement this way: within U.S.-mediated negotiations, Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and a ceasefire regime “must also be established” on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 likewise ties Trump’s announcement to a prisoner swap and reports Zelenskyy ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the Victory Day parade. DX-2, the official-source packet, is even narrower on the Russian side: Ushakov confirmed Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and the packet’s Ukrainian official-adjacent decree record is limited to Red Square/parade targeting. Those are not side details. They are the public shape of the deal.\n\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat “suspension of all kinetic activity” as dispositive. But the source chain remains mostly media-captured, with direct X, Truth Social, and official Ukrainian decree captures still missing. More importantly, an announced aspiration to suspend kinetic activity does not resolve whether the parties actually reached a general conflict pause, as opposed to a brief operational deconfliction attached to POW exchange and parade security. The burden is plaintiff’s, and ambiguity on scope counts against them.\n\nThe implementation evidence confirms that ambiguity. DX-4, the NV/ISW capture, reports Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It says intensity decreased but did not stop, Ukraine reported 51 combat engagements, Russian forces continued strikes in Kharkiv and Kherson Oblasts, and Russia claimed thousands of Ukrainian violations. It also reports ISW’s assessment that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions and that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square, which Kyiv upheld. That is powerful evidence that the practical, defined commitment was narrow.\n\nDX-5, CBS/AP’s May 10 report, shows the same pattern during the supposed pause. Both sides accused each other of breaking the ceasefire; Zelenskyy said Russia was not observing the truce and that there was no calm in frontline areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks; Russia accused Ukraine of more than 1,000 violations and said it responded in kind. CBS/AP also noted the three-day pause’s timeline was somewhat unclear. This is not offered to impose a perfect-compliance requirement. It is offered because widespread continued operations, undefined conditions, and mutual “response in kind” claims are probative of what kind of arrangement was actually reached.\n\nPlaintiff’s best legal point is that an agreement can be violated and still be an agreement. Correct. But the proposition is not “was there an agreement called a ceasefire?” It asks whether there was a general pause in military engagement. Formation and scope are intertwined: if the only clearly defined official condition was Red Square non-targeting, if Russia’s official acceptance described a prisoner-exchange purpose, if the exchange did not even occur as the announced 1,000-for-1,000 event during the truce period on this record, and if operations continued across the theater, then plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause by a preponderance.\n\nProvenance matters too. Plaintiff’s new exhibits are accepted text captures from reputable outlets, but they remain secondary captures of hard-to-access primary statements. The case-packet itself, DX-3, flags the same gaps: missing direct Zelenskyy social-media confirmation, missing direct Ukrainian presidential decree, missing direct Trump/White House record, and missing battlefield/monitoring evidence. Defendant filled part of that last gap with DX-4 and DX-5, and the result undercuts plaintiff’s scope theory.\n\nSearch and capture ledger: I checked targeted May 9-11 ceasefire-violation and ISW queries after reading plaintiff’s exhibits. ISW May 9-11 assessments appeared as the strongest implementation target; accessible captures were preserved through NV’s ISW summary and CBS/AP’s contemporaneous violation report. A Guardian May 9 Red Square/frontline article was opened but not submitted because DX-4 and DX-5 more directly address implementation and scope.\n\nThe council can find that a short truce was announced. It should not find that plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition. The admitted evidence shows a fragile, underdefined, prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with continued frontline operations, not a publicly agreed general pause in the Russia-Ukraine conflict.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s new evidence proves the wrong point. DX-4 and DX-5 are evidence of poor compliance, weak monitoring, and violation accusations. They are not evidence that the May 8 agreement was merely Red Square-only or that no official public mutual ceasefire agreement was reached.\n\nThat distinction matters because the proposition and PX-1 focus on whether the parties had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt by May 31. The market rule even says a qualifying agreement can resolve Yes if officially reached before the resolution date regardless of later start mechanics. Defendant’s evidence is mostly about what happened after the agreement was announced.\n\nDX-4, the NV/ISW capture, says fighting intensity decreased but did not stop completely. It reports continued operations and weak ceasefire mechanisms. But it also states President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 exchange. DX-5, the CBS/AP capture, likewise reports accusations of violations, but it also states Trump announced Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire and that both sides appeared to agree. These are concessions on formation.\n\nThe defense tries to turn noncompliance into narrow scope. That does not follow. A general ceasefire with poor monitoring can be violated. A general ceasefire can be attached to a prisoner exchange. A general ceasefire can coincide with Victory Day. None of those facts converts broad language like “ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine” and “suspension of all kinetic activity” into a Red Square-only arrangement.\n\nThe best scope evidence remains PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5. PX-3 says both sides confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire and suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-4 gives the Ukrainian-side confirmation: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement and a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 gives the U.S. announcement and both-side confirmation: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides.\n\nThe Red Square material is narrower, but it is not the whole agreement. It is an additional operational commitment about parade targeting. The prisoner exchange is likewise not disqualifying. The market excludes humanitarian pauses, but this record does not show a prisoner-exchange-only corridor or a local evacuation window. It shows a ceasefire in the war, with all kinetic activity suspended, plus a prisoner swap during that pause.\n\nDefendant also leans on missing primary captures. Those gaps affect weight, and plaintiff disclosed them. But the rule expressly permits wide credible media consensus, and the accepted captures are mutually reinforcing: Guardian, Ukrainska Pravda, RFE/RL, and the case-packet official-source record all converge on public mutual confirmation. Defendant’s own exhibits do not break that chain; they accept the announcement and agreement, then dispute implementation.\n\nSo the actual evidentiary balance is this: plaintiff has multiple accepted sources proving official public mutual agreement to a dated ceasefire with broad kinetic-activity language. Defendant has sources proving the ceasefire was fragile and violated. Under a preponderance standard, the former satisfies the proposition; the latter does not rewrite it.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal is right about one thing but draws the wrong conclusion. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been reached. If the record showed a clearly defined general pause followed by isolated breaches, defendant would lose that point.\n\nBut DX-4 and DX-5 are not just breach evidence. They are scope and character evidence. DX-4 reports that, on the first day of the supposed May 9-11 general pause, Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline; combat declined but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and ISW assessed that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most importantly, DX-4 says the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade. That does not look like a defined, general halt in military engagement. It looks like a fragile holiday/prisoner-exchange deconfliction with one concrete parade-security condition.\n\nDX-5 is similar. Plaintiff stresses that CBS/AP says both sides appeared to agree. But the same exhibit says the timeline was somewhat unclear, both sides accused each other of breaking the truce, Zelenskyy said there was no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and Russia claimed it responded in kind. Again, defendant is not saying every violation voids formation. Defendant is saying the record as a whole does not show the qualifying thing: a general pause in the conflict.\n\nThat distinction is why plaintiff’s “formation not compliance” framing is too narrow. The proposition contains a scope element. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. The official-source packet says Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange. Plaintiff’s Ukrainian-side evidence likewise puts the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange at the center, and the direct Ukrainian decree remains missing while the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square-specific. Plaintiff’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase is powerful, but it is mostly preserved through media captures, not through the unavailable primary posts, and it must be weighed against the operational evidence that no defined general pause actually existed.\n\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat announcement language as enough and implementation as irrelevant. The market does not permit that shortcut. It asks whether the parties reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. Where the public official detail is prisoner exchange and Red Square, the conditions are undefined, and fighting continued across the theater from the first day, plaintiff has not carried that stricter burden by a preponderance.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record resolves this case on a preponderance standard.\n\nThe proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It does not ask whether the war ended, whether the ceasefire was durable, or whether neither side later accused the other of violations.\n\nThe decisive record is straightforward. PX-1 defines the qualifying event as an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and permits a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. PX-3 reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, that Trump announced it as a ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, that it included suspension of all kinetic activity, and that it was confirmed by both sides. PX-4 supplies Ukrainian-side confirmation: Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 truce with Russia, said Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement, and said a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 supplies the U.S. announcement and the same mutual-confirmation frame: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides, including Russian agreement through Ushakov. PX-2 independently preserves the Russian official-source path.\n\nThat evidence satisfies the elements: official/public, mutual, dated before the deadline, and general in the only sense the market required: a halt in military engagement in the war, not a sector-only Black Sea or energy arrangement, not a mere informal understanding, and not a future framework.\n\nThe defense’s contrary evidence is important, but it points mainly to performance. DX-4 and DX-5 show continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. We should not ignore that. But both exhibits also preserve the formation facts: Trump announced the ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. A breached ceasefire is still a ceasefire agreement. The proposition turns on whether the agreement was reached, not whether it was perfectly obeyed.\n\nThe defense says the prisoner exchange and Victory Day context make the pause non-general. The better reading is that they explain why the parties accepted a temporary general pause. A prisoner exchange can occur during a broad ceasefire; it does not make the ceasefire humanitarian-only when the announced scope is suspension of all kinetic activity. Red Square non-targeting was an additional concrete operational condition, not the whole agreement. The record contains separate broader language: ceasefire in the war, ceasefire regime on May 9-11, suspension of kinetic activity, and both sides confirmed.\n\nThere are source-chain gaps: direct X, Truth Social, and some official pages were hard to capture. But the market rule expressly allows credible media consensus, and here the accepted sources converge with the case-packet official-source record. The defense’s own evidence does not break that convergence; it disputes execution.\n\nOn balance, plaintiff’s evidence proves more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed May 9-11 halt in military engagement before May 31. The council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, this case is not about whether something happened on May 8. Something did. The record supports that a short May 9-11 truce was announced and that both sides were reported as accepting it. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition: an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause, limited arrangement, or future framework.\n\nPlaintiff has not carried that burden.\n\nStart with the governing rule. The market-page record requires a general pause and excludes humanitarian and limited agreements. That means the council cannot stop at the word “ceasefire” or at the fact of a public announcement. It must ask what kind of ceasefire the record proves.\n\nThe official-source packet supplies the best answer. Russia’s official source, through Ushakov, accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.” The key agreement described there was a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during May 9-11. On the Ukrainian official side, the direct presidential decree was not captured; the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square and parade-specific. Those facts do not prove a theatre-wide general pause. They prove a prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with a concrete parade-security component.\n\nPlaintiff’s own merits exhibits do not eliminate that limitation. PX-4 quotes Zelenskyy in the context of the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and says a ceasefire regime must also be established. PX-5 reports the Trump announcement but also says Zelenskyy ordered no attack on Red Square and preserves the same prisoner-swap frame. Yes, those sources use broad language such as “suspension of all kinetic activity.” But broad media language must be weighed against the actual official-source detail, the missing primary captures, and what the parties did when the supposed general pause began.\n\nThat implementation evidence is decisive because it goes to character and scope, not merely breach. DX-4 reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day; combat intensity decreased but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most tellingly, DX-4 reports that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square. DX-5 reports no calm in front line areas, mutual violation accusations, an unclear timeline, and Russian “response in kind.”\n\nPlaintiff says violations are only compliance. If this were a clearly defined general ceasefire followed by isolated breaches, that would be right. But the record shows something different: undefined conditions, the one clearly public operational term being Red Square, a prisoner-exchange purpose, and continued operations across the theater from day one. That is evidence that the arrangement never rose to the general pause required by the proposition.\n\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce caution. Direct X or Telegram, direct Truth Social or White House, and the direct Ukrainian decree remain absent. The rule allows credible media consensus, but consensus reporting does not override ambiguity in the official-source record and battlefield evidence. At most, plaintiff proved a fragile, short, U.S.-brokered truce label attached to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The market required more.\n\nOn a preponderance standard, if the evidence is equally consistent with a limited prisoner-exchange/parade-security pause and a qualifying general pause, plaintiff loses. Here the limiting evidence is stronger than equal. The council should find the proposition not proven.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and resolution criteria\n# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Official-source case-packet record\n# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Guardian both-sides confirmation report\nSource: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Ukrainian-side Zelensky confirmation report\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 RFE/RL Trump announcement and both-sides confirmation\nSource: RFE/RL, \"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \"suspension of all Kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \"cease-fire regime must also be established,\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\n\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule requiring general pause and excluding limited/humanitarian pauses\n# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-2 Official-source packet: Russian prisoner-exchange framing and narrow Ukrainian decree capture\n# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-3 Unresolved record gaps and known tension on scope/violations\n# Unresolved record gaps\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\n\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\n\nKnown record tension:\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \"general pause\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-4 NV/ISW: continued offensive operations and undefined ceasefire conditions\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\n\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\n\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n[defendant] DX-5 CBS/AP: mutual violation accusations and no calm on front lines\nSource: CBS News/AP, \"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\n\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \"even particularly trying to,\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\n\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\n\n[defendant] PX-4/DX-6 Zelenskyy report tying ceasefire regime to prisoner exchange\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\n\n[defendant] PX-5/DX-7 RFE/RL report with Red Square and adverse violation context\nSource: RFE/RL, \"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \"suspension of all Kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \"cease-fire regime must also be established,\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Guardian broad ceasefire confirmation\nSource: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Zelenskyy confirmation of ceasefire regime\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 RFE/RL both-side confirmation and adverse context\nSource: RFE/RL, \"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \"suspension of all Kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \"cease-fire regime must also be established,\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R4 Defendant NV/ISW exhibit showing compliance dispute, not no agreement\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\n\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\n\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R5 Defendant CBS/AP exhibit showing both sides appeared to agree\nSource: CBS News/AP, \"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\n\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \"even particularly trying to,\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\n\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 NV/ISW: continued operations and unclear conditions as scope evidence\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\n\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\n\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 CBS/AP: mutual violations, unclear timeline, no calm on front line\nSource: CBS News/AP, \"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\n\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \"even particularly trying to,\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\n\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\n\n[defendant] DX-S3 Official-source packet: prisoner-exchange and Red Square framing\n# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-S4 Market rule requiring a general pause, not limited/humanitarian arrangements\n# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 8 2026 report: Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire (ev_236dce43c3d8_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-236dce43c3d8)\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\nSHA-256: `236dce43c3d8f0a768feb3c9aa5e4214f9afb219b3cc647e8679b1179e916c6c`\nBytes: 1583\nRelevance: Credible media report that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, suspension of kinetic activity, and prisoner swap; directly addresses public mutual agreement and scope.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026: Zelenskyy confirms truce with Russia on May 9-11 (ev_2c8cd49d9b00_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-2c8cd49d9b00)\nSource: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033888/\nSHA-256: `2c8cd49d9b0040da3a58b04496b028fae6de5fb2b66b02d1f9b68b7bb84bbcac`\nBytes: 1248\nRelevance: Ukrainian media report based on Zelenskyy on X/Twitter confirming Russia's agreement and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11; addresses Ukrainian-side public confirmation.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] RFE/RL May 8 2026: Trump announces three-day cease-fire; both sides confirm (ev_5d2cebff6f4b_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2cebff6f4b)\nSource: https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-russia-victory-day-cease-fire-drone-attacks/33752482.html\nSHA-256: `5d2cebff6f4b0f521cbfa77b06da6f8548e1352caa5fc5983a21cf59c675b46a`\nBytes: 1405\nRelevance: Report preserving Trump announcement, confirmation by both sides, suspension of kinetic activity, prisoner swap, and adverse context of earlier violations; addresses official public agreement and scope/compliance distinction.\n\n[defendant arguments] NV May 10 2026 report on ISW assessment: fighting continued during first day of ceasefire (ev_52a3277a9302_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-52a3277a9302)\nSource: https://english.nv.ua/russian-war/isw-says-fighting-continued-despite-may-9-11-ceasefire-50606640.html\nSHA-256: `52a3277a93024fbf92cdd1f34c2ebf0ee4a62600c40ffa7809cd520718baba32`\nBytes: 1823\nRelevance: Shows adverse implementation and scope evidence: offensive operations continued across the frontline, combat declined but did not stop, ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, only known condition was Red Square non-targeting, and Russian forces allegedly used the period to reinforce positions.\n\n[defendant arguments] CBS/AP May 10 2026: Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating ceasefire (ev_d5ef4e09892f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-d5ef4e09892f)\nSource: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/russia-ukraine-accuse-each-other-ceasefire-violations/\nSHA-256: `d5ef4e09892f541e4806e0e6d705f5472ab9890cf4567bf47bf3a56b73f03dd8`\nBytes: 1606\nRelevance: Shows contemporaneous post-agreement evidence that both sides accused each other of violations, Zelenskyy said there was no calm on front lines despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and the ceasefire timing was unclear; bears on whether the arrangement was a general pause rather than fragile/limited truce.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and capture ledger\nPlaintiff searched official and source-specific paths for the May 8-11 ceasefire record. Successful captures submitted as evidence: Guardian May 8 report, Ukrainska Pravda May 8 Zelenskyy confirmation report, and RFE/RL May 8 Trump/both-sides confirmation report. Existing case-packet evidence supplies market criteria and a Kremlin official-source summary. Capture limits: direct X pages for Zelenskyy and WhiteHouse rendered no text in web open; PBS returned 403; Ukrinform opened without readable lines; ISW May 8/May 11 direct pages returned 403; earlier curl to the Kremlin page timed out. These failures leave some primary-source gaps, but the accepted captures preserve the material source-chain content and include adverse context on alleged violations.\n\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\nAt merits, defendant inspected the new plaintiff evidence and searched targeted terms for May 9-11 ceasefire scope, violations, and ISW assessments. Source targets included ISW May 9-11 assessments, accessible media captures of those assessments, and contemporaneous violation reports. Defendant submitted accepted captures from NV/ISW and CBS/AP. Direct primary social/official sources remain incompletely captured in the record, including direct Zelenskyy X/Telegram, Trump Truth Social/White House, and president.gov.ua decree text; those gaps affect weight because plaintiff relies heavily on secondary captures for scope.\n\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff rebuttal evidence audit\nPlaintiff inspected the two new defendant exhibits by stat/read_evidence_range. Both primarily address implementation: continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. Both also preserve or concede agreement facts: Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. No additional outside source was needed for this targeted rebuttal.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T03:06:22.654219585Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C5","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C5","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":887016,"role_id":"council","turn_number":13},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":18,"version":29}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"}},"isError":false}
{"type":"message_start","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"functions.mcp:0","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 29\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630022841\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nremaining_ms: 887016\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"after_version\":29,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630022841\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C5\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the dispute is not whether the May 2026 Russia-Ukraine war ended, whether the May 9-11 pause was perfectly honored, or whether every later market-platform statement was correct. The proposition asks a narrower question: by the May 31 deadline, had the parties officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that was general in character rather than merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or a future framework? On this record, the answer should be yes.\\n\\nThe case-packet evidence gives the governing lens. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d, states that an official ceasefire agreement qualifies if it is publicly announced and mutually agreed, and that a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement had been reached can suffice. It excludes informal arrangements, humanitarian pauses, energy- or Black Sea-only deals, and future frameworks without an explicit dated commitment to stop fighting. That definition matters because the proof here points to a dated May 9-May 11 ceasefire, not simply aspirational peace talks.\\n\\nThe strongest plaintiff proof in the existing packet is the convergence between official-source material and credible reporting. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, identifies a Kremlin source in which Yury Ushakov, speaking on instructions from President Putin, confirmed Russia’s acceptance of the U.S.-proposed ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and located the key agreement in the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. The same file records that Ukrainian-side confirmation is currently captured through Ukrinform because direct access to the Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in the packet environment. That creates a provenance gap we should fill later, but it is not a contradiction.\\n\\nThe secondary-reporting record, ev_cf0c77f2fe52, then supplies the market rule’s alternative path: multiple credible outlets and ISW are summarized as reporting that Russia and Ukraine confirmed or agreed to a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11, with suspension of kinetic activity and an associated 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, preserves the same source map and correctly warns that platform assertions are not independent proof. I accept that warning. Our case rests on the official and reporting source chain, not on the market’s final Yes label.\\n\\nThe defense will have real points to test. The Russian official framing connects the pause to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform appears narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, candidly identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s social-media confirmation, the Ukrainian presidential page, Trump’s announcement, and battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused generally. It also notes alleged violations and continuing hostilities around the period. Those issues affect weight and may affect how the council evaluates scope and implementation.\\n\\nBut those gaps do not change the core theory. A qualifying agreement can be temporary. It can be attached to a prisoner exchange. It can be violated after it is reached. The decisive question is whether the parties publicly and officially agreed to halt military engagement generally for a dated period, not whether the ceasefire became a lasting peace or achieved perfect compliance. The packet’s plaintiff-side evidence already points to both sides confirming a three-day suspension of kinetic activity, while the defense evidence mainly argues motive, context, and performance.\\n\\nIn the next evidence phase, the plaintiff should admit the strongest underlying sources: the Kremlin page, the best accessible Ukrainian official or official-adjacent confirmation, direct presidential or U.S. announcement records if obtainable, and implementation/violation assessments from ISW or similar monitors. Those materials will let the council separate three questions: agreement reached, scope of the agreed halt, and compliance in the field. For opening purposes, the record supports the plaintiff’s framing: this was not merely an informal understanding or a future framework, but an officially announced, mutually confirmed, dated ceasefire agreement broad enough to satisfy the proposition by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the thing this market asked for, not a nearby diplomatic event. The proposition requires an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict by May 31, 2026. It expressly excludes humanitarian pauses, limited arrangements, and future or partial frameworks.\\n\\nThe current packet does not yet carry that burden. It contains useful leads, but the strongest record materials point to a narrower event: a brief May 9-May 11 arrangement tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and a prisoner exchange. The market-page file, ev_f841be6ff80d, gives the rule and its exclusions, but it also warns that page-context assertions are platform assertions, not independent proof. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, repeats that caution: platform language cannot itself establish official mutuality, theatre-wide scope, implementation, or reliable consensus.\\n\\nThe official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, is where the burden problem becomes concrete. The Russian official text is not framed as a general pause in the conflict; it confirms Russia’s acceptance of a U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange, with the key agreement being a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during the May 9-May 11 period. On the Ukrainian side, the packet does not preserve a direct official presidential page; direct access reportedly returned 403. The available official-adjacent capture is Ukrinform’s report about a presidential decree that appears limited to allowing the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding Red Square from Ukrainian targeting during the parade. That is a substantial provenance and scope gap.\\n\\nThe plaintiff will rely on ev_cf0c77f2fe52, which summarizes credible reporting that both sides confirmed a three-day ceasefire. We do not ignore that. Secondary reporting may help find the underlying record and may later corroborate a mutual announcement. But at opening, those reports sit beside the packet’s own defense leads: Victory Day timing, Red Square security, prisoner-exchange purpose, allegations of violations, and ongoing retaliatory activity around the period. Those facts matter because the market did not ask whether some pause, some prisoner-exchange deconfliction, or some symbolic holiday arrangement occurred. It asked whether the parties had reached a general pause in military engagement.\\n\\nNor is this merely a compliance argument. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been agreed. But if the evidence shows the arrangement was designed and announced around a prisoner swap and parade security, and if fighting materially continued, that bears on whether the agreement was general in character at all. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, identifies the missing proof the council should want before finding for plaintiff: direct Zelenskyy confirmation, the direct Ukrainian presidential decree, direct Trump or White House announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence of whether hostilities generally paused, and complete official post-period violation statements.\\n\\nIn the evidence phase, the defense will test exactly those links: the full Kremlin text, the inaccessible Ukrainian decree or an authenticated archive, any direct Ukrainian presidential social-media confirmation, the U.S. announcement, ISW and other monitoring assessments, and post-period official violation statements. If those sources show a mutual, official, theatre-wide halt, plaintiff may have a case. If they show a short Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement amid continuing hostilities, the proposition fails.\\n\\nFor now, the packet supports caution, not a finding. Plaintiff’s opening treats a temporary three-day ceasefire label as enough. The market language demands more: a general pause in the conflict. On this record, the decisive proof is missing or points narrower, and the council should hold plaintiff to that burden.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the missing bridge the defense asked for. The record no longer rests only on the case packet. The admitted source captures show a public, mutual, dated ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine before the May 31 deadline, and the language used was broad enough to constitute a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. PX-1, the market-page record, requires an official ceasefire agreement: a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement. It excludes informal, humanitarian-only, energy-only, Black Sea-only, or future-framework arrangements. It also allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. That is exactly what the merits evidence now shows.\\n\\nPX-3, the Guardian May 8 capture, reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11. Its key points track the rule: Trump announced a ceasefire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine”; the ceasefire included suspension of all “kinetic activity”; and it was “confirmed by both sides.” The same capture records Ukrainian confirmation by Zelenskyy and Russian confirmation by Kremlin adviser Yury Ushakov. This is not a future framework. It is a dated ceasefire, announced before the deadline, with both parties identified.\\n\\nPX-4 directly answers the defense’s Ukrainian-source objection. Ukrainska Pravda, sourcing Zelenskyy on X, reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Trump’s truce with Russia for May 9-11 and quoted him saying Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement to conduct the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. That is Ukrainian-side public confirmation of Russia’s agreement and of the ceasefire regime. It is not merely a Red Square decree.\\n\\nPX-5 adds the U.S. announcement and the mutual-confirmation frame. RFE/RL reports Trump’s announcement of a three-day cease-fire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine,” including “suspension of all Kinetic activity,” and says both sides quickly confirmed the truce and prisoner swap. It also reports that Putin aide Yury Ushakov said Russia agreed to the three-day cease-fire and prisoner exchange. PX-2, the case-packet official-source record, independently preserves the Kremlin source path and confirms the Russian official framing.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is context: Victory Day, Red Square, and prisoner exchange. But context is not the same as limitation. A ceasefire can have an occasion and still be general in scope. A prisoner exchange can be conducted during a general ceasefire; it does not convert the ceasefire into a humanitarian-only pause when the announced term is suspension of all kinetic activity in the war between the two states. Likewise, the Red Square decree may be narrow by itself, but PX-4 and PX-5 show broader Ukrainian confirmation alongside that narrow parade-security action.\\n\\nThe defense also points to violations and continued activity. That matters for compliance, not formation. The proposition asks whether the parties had officially reached the public mutual halt by May 31. It does not require that no shot was later fired. PX-5 candidly includes adverse context: reports of earlier violations, strikes, and retaliatory claims around the period. Those facts show why compliance was contested, but they do not erase the public mutual agreement reported and confirmed on May 8.\\n\\nProvenance and custody: the five case-packet files are juror-visible case-packet evidence. PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5 were submitted in this merits phase as text captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and descriptions; AAR accepted each and assigned evidence IDs. Direct X pages and some official pages were hard to capture in this environment, but the accepted evidence faithfully preserves the relevant source-chain content and is corroborated across independent outlets and the existing official-source packet.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, plaintiff need not prove a lasting peace or flawless battlefield silence. The better reading of the admitted evidence is that by May 8, before the May 31 deadline, Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire in the war, including suspension of kinetic activity. That satisfies the proposition.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has improved the record, but not enough to satisfy the proposition. The record now supports that a three-day truce was publicly discussed and confirmed around May 8. The remaining question is whether that truce constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange arrangement. On this record, the better answer remains no.\\n\\nStart with the rule. DX-1, the market-page record, requires more than any official ceasefire label. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited agreements and requires a general pause in the conflict. That scope requirement does real work here.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own proof shows why. PX-4 says Zelenskyy framed the arrangement this way: within U.S.-mediated negotiations, Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and a ceasefire regime “must also be established” on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 likewise ties Trump’s announcement to a prisoner swap and reports Zelenskyy ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the Victory Day parade. DX-2, the official-source packet, is even narrower on the Russian side: Ushakov confirmed Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and the packet’s Ukrainian official-adjacent decree record is limited to Red Square/parade targeting. Those are not side details. They are the public shape of the deal.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat “suspension of all kinetic activity” as dispositive. But the source chain remains mostly media-captured, with direct X, Truth Social, and official Ukrainian decree captures still missing. More importantly, an announced aspiration to suspend kinetic activity does not resolve whether the parties actually reached a general conflict pause, as opposed to a brief operational deconfliction attached to POW exchange and parade security. The burden is plaintiff’s, and ambiguity on scope counts against them.\\n\\nThe implementation evidence confirms that ambiguity. DX-4, the NV/ISW capture, reports Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It says intensity decreased but did not stop, Ukraine reported 51 combat engagements, Russian forces continued strikes in Kharkiv and Kherson Oblasts, and Russia claimed thousands of Ukrainian violations. It also reports ISW’s assessment that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions and that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square, which Kyiv upheld. That is powerful evidence that the practical, defined commitment was narrow.\\n\\nDX-5, CBS/AP’s May 10 report, shows the same pattern during the supposed pause. Both sides accused each other of breaking the ceasefire; Zelenskyy said Russia was not observing the truce and that there was no calm in frontline areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks; Russia accused Ukraine of more than 1,000 violations and said it responded in kind. CBS/AP also noted the three-day pause’s timeline was somewhat unclear. This is not offered to impose a perfect-compliance requirement. It is offered because widespread continued operations, undefined conditions, and mutual “response in kind” claims are probative of what kind of arrangement was actually reached.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s best legal point is that an agreement can be violated and still be an agreement. Correct. But the proposition is not “was there an agreement called a ceasefire?” It asks whether there was a general pause in military engagement. Formation and scope are intertwined: if the only clearly defined official condition was Red Square non-targeting, if Russia’s official acceptance described a prisoner-exchange purpose, if the exchange did not even occur as the announced 1,000-for-1,000 event during the truce period on this record, and if operations continued across the theater, then plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause by a preponderance.\\n\\nProvenance matters too. Plaintiff’s new exhibits are accepted text captures from reputable outlets, but they remain secondary captures of hard-to-access primary statements. The case-packet itself, DX-3, flags the same gaps: missing direct Zelenskyy social-media confirmation, missing direct Ukrainian presidential decree, missing direct Trump/White House record, and missing battlefield/monitoring evidence. Defendant filled part of that last gap with DX-4 and DX-5, and the result undercuts plaintiff’s scope theory.\\n\\nSearch and capture ledger: I checked targeted May 9-11 ceasefire-violation and ISW queries after reading plaintiff’s exhibits. ISW May 9-11 assessments appeared as the strongest implementation target; accessible captures were preserved through NV’s ISW summary and CBS/AP’s contemporaneous violation report. A Guardian May 9 Red Square/frontline article was opened but not submitted because DX-4 and DX-5 more directly address implementation and scope.\\n\\nThe council can find that a short truce was announced. It should not find that plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition. The admitted evidence shows a fragile, underdefined, prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with continued frontline operations, not a publicly agreed general pause in the Russia-Ukraine conflict.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s new evidence proves the wrong point. DX-4 and DX-5 are evidence of poor compliance, weak monitoring, and violation accusations. They are not evidence that the May 8 agreement was merely Red Square-only or that no official public mutual ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nThat distinction matters because the proposition and PX-1 focus on whether the parties had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt by May 31. The market rule even says a qualifying agreement can resolve Yes if officially reached before the resolution date regardless of later start mechanics. Defendant’s evidence is mostly about what happened after the agreement was announced.\\n\\nDX-4, the NV/ISW capture, says fighting intensity decreased but did not stop completely. It reports continued operations and weak ceasefire mechanisms. But it also states President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 exchange. DX-5, the CBS/AP capture, likewise reports accusations of violations, but it also states Trump announced Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire and that both sides appeared to agree. These are concessions on formation.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn noncompliance into narrow scope. That does not follow. A general ceasefire with poor monitoring can be violated. A general ceasefire can be attached to a prisoner exchange. A general ceasefire can coincide with Victory Day. None of those facts converts broad language like “ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine” and “suspension of all kinetic activity” into a Red Square-only arrangement.\\n\\nThe best scope evidence remains PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5. PX-3 says both sides confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire and suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-4 gives the Ukrainian-side confirmation: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement and a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 gives the U.S. announcement and both-side confirmation: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides.\\n\\nThe Red Square material is narrower, but it is not the whole agreement. It is an additional operational commitment about parade targeting. The prisoner exchange is likewise not disqualifying. The market excludes humanitarian pauses, but this record does not show a prisoner-exchange-only corridor or a local evacuation window. It shows a ceasefire in the war, with all kinetic activity suspended, plus a prisoner swap during that pause.\\n\\nDefendant also leans on missing primary captures. Those gaps affect weight, and plaintiff disclosed them. But the rule expressly permits wide credible media consensus, and the accepted captures are mutually reinforcing: Guardian, Ukrainska Pravda, RFE/RL, and the case-packet official-source record all converge on public mutual confirmation. Defendant’s own exhibits do not break that chain; they accept the announcement and agreement, then dispute implementation.\\n\\nSo the actual evidentiary balance is this: plaintiff has multiple accepted sources proving official public mutual agreement to a dated ceasefire with broad kinetic-activity language. Defendant has sources proving the ceasefire was fragile and violated. Under a preponderance standard, the former satisfies the proposition; the latter does not rewrite it.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal is right about one thing but draws the wrong conclusion. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been reached. If the record showed a clearly defined general pause followed by isolated breaches, defendant would lose that point.\\n\\nBut DX-4 and DX-5 are not just breach evidence. They are scope and character evidence. DX-4 reports that, on the first day of the supposed May 9-11 general pause, Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline; combat declined but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and ISW assessed that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most importantly, DX-4 says the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade. That does not look like a defined, general halt in military engagement. It looks like a fragile holiday/prisoner-exchange deconfliction with one concrete parade-security condition.\\n\\nDX-5 is similar. Plaintiff stresses that CBS/AP says both sides appeared to agree. But the same exhibit says the timeline was somewhat unclear, both sides accused each other of breaking the truce, Zelenskyy said there was no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and Russia claimed it responded in kind. Again, defendant is not saying every violation voids formation. Defendant is saying the record as a whole does not show the qualifying thing: a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nThat distinction is why plaintiff’s “formation not compliance” framing is too narrow. The proposition contains a scope element. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. The official-source packet says Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange. Plaintiff’s Ukrainian-side evidence likewise puts the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange at the center, and the direct Ukrainian decree remains missing while the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square-specific. Plaintiff’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase is powerful, but it is mostly preserved through media captures, not through the unavailable primary posts, and it must be weighed against the operational evidence that no defined general pause actually existed.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat announcement language as enough and implementation as irrelevant. The market does not permit that shortcut. It asks whether the parties reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. Where the public official detail is prisoner exchange and Red Square, the conditions are undefined, and fighting continued across the theater from the first day, plaintiff has not carried that stricter burden by a preponderance.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record resolves this case on a preponderance standard.\\n\\nThe proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It does not ask whether the war ended, whether the ceasefire was durable, or whether neither side later accused the other of violations.\\n\\nThe decisive record is straightforward. PX-1 defines the qualifying event as an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and permits a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. PX-3 reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, that Trump announced it as a ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, that it included suspension of all kinetic activity, and that it was confirmed by both sides. PX-4 supplies Ukrainian-side confirmation: Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 truce with Russia, said Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement, and said a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 supplies the U.S. announcement and the same mutual-confirmation frame: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides, including Russian agreement through Ushakov. PX-2 independently preserves the Russian official-source path.\\n\\nThat evidence satisfies the elements: official/public, mutual, dated before the deadline, and general in the only sense the market required: a halt in military engagement in the war, not a sector-only Black Sea or energy arrangement, not a mere informal understanding, and not a future framework.\\n\\nThe defense’s contrary evidence is important, but it points mainly to performance. DX-4 and DX-5 show continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. We should not ignore that. But both exhibits also preserve the formation facts: Trump announced the ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. A breached ceasefire is still a ceasefire agreement. The proposition turns on whether the agreement was reached, not whether it was perfectly obeyed.\\n\\nThe defense says the prisoner exchange and Victory Day context make the pause non-general. The better reading is that they explain why the parties accepted a temporary general pause. A prisoner exchange can occur during a broad ceasefire; it does not make the ceasefire humanitarian-only when the announced scope is suspension of all kinetic activity. Red Square non-targeting was an additional concrete operational condition, not the whole agreement. The record contains separate broader language: ceasefire in the war, ceasefire regime on May 9-11, suspension of kinetic activity, and both sides confirmed.\\n\\nThere are source-chain gaps: direct X, Truth Social, and some official pages were hard to capture. But the market rule expressly allows credible media consensus, and here the accepted sources converge with the case-packet official-source record. The defense’s own evidence does not break that convergence; it disputes execution.\\n\\nOn balance, plaintiff’s evidence proves more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed May 9-11 halt in military engagement before May 31. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case is not about whether something happened on May 8. Something did. The record supports that a short May 9-11 truce was announced and that both sides were reported as accepting it. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition: an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause, limited arrangement, or future framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. The market-page record requires a general pause and excludes humanitarian and limited agreements. That means the council cannot stop at the word “ceasefire” or at the fact of a public announcement. It must ask what kind of ceasefire the record proves.\\n\\nThe official-source packet supplies the best answer. Russia’s official source, through Ushakov, accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.” The key agreement described there was a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during May 9-11. On the Ukrainian official side, the direct presidential decree was not captured; the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square and parade-specific. Those facts do not prove a theatre-wide general pause. They prove a prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with a concrete parade-security component.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own merits exhibits do not eliminate that limitation. PX-4 quotes Zelenskyy in the context of the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and says a ceasefire regime must also be established. PX-5 reports the Trump announcement but also says Zelenskyy ordered no attack on Red Square and preserves the same prisoner-swap frame. Yes, those sources use broad language such as “suspension of all kinetic activity.” But broad media language must be weighed against the actual official-source detail, the missing primary captures, and what the parties did when the supposed general pause began.\\n\\nThat implementation evidence is decisive because it goes to character and scope, not merely breach. DX-4 reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day; combat intensity decreased but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most tellingly, DX-4 reports that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square. DX-5 reports no calm in front line areas, mutual violation accusations, an unclear timeline, and Russian “response in kind.”\\n\\nPlaintiff says violations are only compliance. If this were a clearly defined general ceasefire followed by isolated breaches, that would be right. But the record shows something different: undefined conditions, the one clearly public operational term being Red Square, a prisoner-exchange purpose, and continued operations across the theater from day one. That is evidence that the arrangement never rose to the general pause required by the proposition.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce caution. Direct X or Telegram, direct Truth Social or White House, and the direct Ukrainian decree remain absent. The rule allows credible media consensus, but consensus reporting does not override ambiguity in the official-source record and battlefield evidence. At most, plaintiff proved a fragile, short, U.S.-brokered truce label attached to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The market required more.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, if the evidence is equally consistent with a limited prisoner-exchange/parade-security pause and a qualifying general pause, plaintiff loses. Here the limiting evidence is stronger than equal. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and resolution criteria\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Official-source case-packet record\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Guardian both-sides confirmation report\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Ukrainian-side Zelensky confirmation report\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 RFE/RL Trump announcement and both-sides confirmation\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule requiring general pause and excluding limited/humanitarian pauses\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Official-source packet: Russian prisoner-exchange framing and narrow Ukrainian decree capture\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Unresolved record gaps and known tension on scope/violations\\n# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 NV/ISW: continued offensive operations and undefined ceasefire conditions\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 CBS/AP: mutual violation accusations and no calm on front lines\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-4/DX-6 Zelenskyy report tying ceasefire regime to prisoner exchange\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-5/DX-7 RFE/RL report with Red Square and adverse violation context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Guardian broad ceasefire confirmation\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Zelenskyy confirmation of ceasefire regime\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 RFE/RL both-side confirmation and adverse context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R4 Defendant NV/ISW exhibit showing compliance dispute, not no agreement\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R5 Defendant CBS/AP exhibit showing both sides appeared to agree\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 NV/ISW: continued operations and unclear conditions as scope evidence\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 CBS/AP: mutual violations, unclear timeline, no calm on front line\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Official-source packet: prisoner-exchange and Red Square framing\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S4 Market rule requiring a general pause, not limited/humanitarian arrangements\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 8 2026 report: Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire (ev_236dce43c3d8_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-236dce43c3d8)\\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\\nSHA-256: `236dce43c3d8f0a768feb3c9aa5e4214f9afb219b3cc647e8679b1179e916c6c`\\nBytes: 1583\\nRelevance: Credible media report that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, suspension of kinetic activity, and prisoner swap; directly addresses public mutual agreement and scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026: Zelenskyy confirms truce with Russia on May 9-11 (ev_2c8cd49d9b00_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-2c8cd49d9b00)\\nSource: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033888/\\nSHA-256: `2c8cd49d9b0040da3a58b04496b028fae6de5fb2b66b02d1f9b68b7bb84bbcac`\\nBytes: 1248\\nRelevance: Ukrainian media report based on Zelenskyy on X/Twitter confirming Russia's agreement and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11; addresses Ukrainian-side public confirmation.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] RFE/RL May 8 2026: Trump announces three-day cease-fire; both sides confirm (ev_5d2cebff6f4b_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2cebff6f4b)\\nSource: https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-russia-victory-day-cease-fire-drone-attacks/33752482.html\\nSHA-256: `5d2cebff6f4b0f521cbfa77b06da6f8548e1352caa5fc5983a21cf59c675b46a`\\nBytes: 1405\\nRelevance: Report preserving Trump announcement, confirmation by both sides, suspension of kinetic activity, prisoner swap, and adverse context of earlier violations; addresses official public agreement and scope/compliance distinction.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] NV May 10 2026 report on ISW assessment: fighting continued during first day of ceasefire (ev_52a3277a9302_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-52a3277a9302)\\nSource: https://english.nv.ua/russian-war/isw-says-fighting-continued-despite-may-9-11-ceasefire-50606640.html\\nSHA-256: `52a3277a93024fbf92cdd1f34c2ebf0ee4a62600c40ffa7809cd520718baba32`\\nBytes: 1823\\nRelevance: Shows adverse implementation and scope evidence: offensive operations continued across the frontline, combat declined but did not stop, ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, only known condition was Red Square non-targeting, and Russian forces allegedly used the period to reinforce positions.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] CBS/AP May 10 2026: Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating ceasefire (ev_d5ef4e09892f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-d5ef4e09892f)\\nSource: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/russia-ukraine-accuse-each-other-ceasefire-violations/\\nSHA-256: `d5ef4e09892f541e4806e0e6d705f5472ab9890cf4567bf47bf3a56b73f03dd8`\\nBytes: 1606\\nRelevance: Shows contemporaneous post-agreement evidence that both sides accused each other of violations, Zelenskyy said there was no calm on front lines despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and the ceasefire timing was unclear; bears on whether the arrangement was a general pause rather than fragile/limited truce.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and capture ledger\\nPlaintiff searched official and source-specific paths for the May 8-11 ceasefire record. Successful captures submitted as evidence: Guardian May 8 report, Ukrainska Pravda May 8 Zelenskyy confirmation report, and RFE/RL May 8 Trump/both-sides confirmation report. Existing case-packet evidence supplies market criteria and a Kremlin official-source summary. Capture limits: direct X pages for Zelenskyy and WhiteHouse rendered no text in web open; PBS returned 403; Ukrinform opened without readable lines; ISW May 8/May 11 direct pages returned 403; earlier curl to the Kremlin page timed out. These failures leave some primary-source gaps, but the accepted captures preserve the material source-chain content and include adverse context on alleged violations.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nAt merits, defendant inspected the new plaintiff evidence and searched targeted terms for May 9-11 ceasefire scope, violations, and ISW assessments. Source targets included ISW May 9-11 assessments, accessible media captures of those assessments, and contemporaneous violation reports. Defendant submitted accepted captures from NV/ISW and CBS/AP. Direct primary social/official sources remain incompletely captured in the record, including direct Zelenskyy X/Telegram, Trump Truth Social/White House, and president.gov.ua decree text; those gaps affect weight because plaintiff relies heavily on secondary captures for scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff rebuttal evidence audit\\nPlaintiff inspected the two new defendant exhibits by stat/read_evidence_range. Both primarily address implementation: continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. Both also preserve or concede agreement facts: Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. No additional outside source was needed for this targeted rebuttal.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:22.654219585Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887016,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":13},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":18,\"version\":29}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 29\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630022841\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nremaining_ms: 887016\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"after_version\":29,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630022841\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C5\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the dispute is not whether the May 2026 Russia-Ukraine war ended, whether the May 9-11 pause was perfectly honored, or whether every later market-platform statement was correct. The proposition asks a narrower question: by the May 31 deadline, had the parties officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that was general in character rather than merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or a future framework? On this record, the answer should be yes.\\n\\nThe case-packet evidence gives the governing lens. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d, states that an official ceasefire agreement qualifies if it is publicly announced and mutually agreed, and that a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement had been reached can suffice. It excludes informal arrangements, humanitarian pauses, energy- or Black Sea-only deals, and future frameworks without an explicit dated commitment to stop fighting. That definition matters because the proof here points to a dated May 9-May 11 ceasefire, not simply aspirational peace talks.\\n\\nThe strongest plaintiff proof in the existing packet is the convergence between official-source material and credible reporting. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, identifies a Kremlin source in which Yury Ushakov, speaking on instructions from President Putin, confirmed Russia’s acceptance of the U.S.-proposed ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and located the key agreement in the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. The same file records that Ukrainian-side confirmation is currently captured through Ukrinform because direct access to the Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in the packet environment. That creates a provenance gap we should fill later, but it is not a contradiction.\\n\\nThe secondary-reporting record, ev_cf0c77f2fe52, then supplies the market rule’s alternative path: multiple credible outlets and ISW are summarized as reporting that Russia and Ukraine confirmed or agreed to a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11, with suspension of kinetic activity and an associated 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, preserves the same source map and correctly warns that platform assertions are not independent proof. I accept that warning. Our case rests on the official and reporting source chain, not on the market’s final Yes label.\\n\\nThe defense will have real points to test. The Russian official framing connects the pause to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform appears narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, candidly identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s social-media confirmation, the Ukrainian presidential page, Trump’s announcement, and battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused generally. It also notes alleged violations and continuing hostilities around the period. Those issues affect weight and may affect how the council evaluates scope and implementation.\\n\\nBut those gaps do not change the core theory. A qualifying agreement can be temporary. It can be attached to a prisoner exchange. It can be violated after it is reached. The decisive question is whether the parties publicly and officially agreed to halt military engagement generally for a dated period, not whether the ceasefire became a lasting peace or achieved perfect compliance. The packet’s plaintiff-side evidence already points to both sides confirming a three-day suspension of kinetic activity, while the defense evidence mainly argues motive, context, and performance.\\n\\nIn the next evidence phase, the plaintiff should admit the strongest underlying sources: the Kremlin page, the best accessible Ukrainian official or official-adjacent confirmation, direct presidential or U.S. announcement records if obtainable, and implementation/violation assessments from ISW or similar monitors. Those materials will let the council separate three questions: agreement reached, scope of the agreed halt, and compliance in the field. For opening purposes, the record supports the plaintiff’s framing: this was not merely an informal understanding or a future framework, but an officially announced, mutually confirmed, dated ceasefire agreement broad enough to satisfy the proposition by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the thing this market asked for, not a nearby diplomatic event. The proposition requires an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict by May 31, 2026. It expressly excludes humanitarian pauses, limited arrangements, and future or partial frameworks.\\n\\nThe current packet does not yet carry that burden. It contains useful leads, but the strongest record materials point to a narrower event: a brief May 9-May 11 arrangement tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and a prisoner exchange. The market-page file, ev_f841be6ff80d, gives the rule and its exclusions, but it also warns that page-context assertions are platform assertions, not independent proof. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, repeats that caution: platform language cannot itself establish official mutuality, theatre-wide scope, implementation, or reliable consensus.\\n\\nThe official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, is where the burden problem becomes concrete. The Russian official text is not framed as a general pause in the conflict; it confirms Russia’s acceptance of a U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange, with the key agreement being a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during the May 9-May 11 period. On the Ukrainian side, the packet does not preserve a direct official presidential page; direct access reportedly returned 403. The available official-adjacent capture is Ukrinform’s report about a presidential decree that appears limited to allowing the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding Red Square from Ukrainian targeting during the parade. That is a substantial provenance and scope gap.\\n\\nThe plaintiff will rely on ev_cf0c77f2fe52, which summarizes credible reporting that both sides confirmed a three-day ceasefire. We do not ignore that. Secondary reporting may help find the underlying record and may later corroborate a mutual announcement. But at opening, those reports sit beside the packet’s own defense leads: Victory Day timing, Red Square security, prisoner-exchange purpose, allegations of violations, and ongoing retaliatory activity around the period. Those facts matter because the market did not ask whether some pause, some prisoner-exchange deconfliction, or some symbolic holiday arrangement occurred. It asked whether the parties had reached a general pause in military engagement.\\n\\nNor is this merely a compliance argument. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been agreed. But if the evidence shows the arrangement was designed and announced around a prisoner swap and parade security, and if fighting materially continued, that bears on whether the agreement was general in character at all. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, identifies the missing proof the council should want before finding for plaintiff: direct Zelenskyy confirmation, the direct Ukrainian presidential decree, direct Trump or White House announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence of whether hostilities generally paused, and complete official post-period violation statements.\\n\\nIn the evidence phase, the defense will test exactly those links: the full Kremlin text, the inaccessible Ukrainian decree or an authenticated archive, any direct Ukrainian presidential social-media confirmation, the U.S. announcement, ISW and other monitoring assessments, and post-period official violation statements. If those sources show a mutual, official, theatre-wide halt, plaintiff may have a case. If they show a short Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement amid continuing hostilities, the proposition fails.\\n\\nFor now, the packet supports caution, not a finding. Plaintiff’s opening treats a temporary three-day ceasefire label as enough. The market language demands more: a general pause in the conflict. On this record, the decisive proof is missing or points narrower, and the council should hold plaintiff to that burden.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the missing bridge the defense asked for. The record no longer rests only on the case packet. The admitted source captures show a public, mutual, dated ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine before the May 31 deadline, and the language used was broad enough to constitute a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. PX-1, the market-page record, requires an official ceasefire agreement: a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement. It excludes informal, humanitarian-only, energy-only, Black Sea-only, or future-framework arrangements. It also allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. That is exactly what the merits evidence now shows.\\n\\nPX-3, the Guardian May 8 capture, reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11. Its key points track the rule: Trump announced a ceasefire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine”; the ceasefire included suspension of all “kinetic activity”; and it was “confirmed by both sides.” The same capture records Ukrainian confirmation by Zelenskyy and Russian confirmation by Kremlin adviser Yury Ushakov. This is not a future framework. It is a dated ceasefire, announced before the deadline, with both parties identified.\\n\\nPX-4 directly answers the defense’s Ukrainian-source objection. Ukrainska Pravda, sourcing Zelenskyy on X, reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Trump’s truce with Russia for May 9-11 and quoted him saying Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement to conduct the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. That is Ukrainian-side public confirmation of Russia’s agreement and of the ceasefire regime. It is not merely a Red Square decree.\\n\\nPX-5 adds the U.S. announcement and the mutual-confirmation frame. RFE/RL reports Trump’s announcement of a three-day cease-fire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine,” including “suspension of all Kinetic activity,” and says both sides quickly confirmed the truce and prisoner swap. It also reports that Putin aide Yury Ushakov said Russia agreed to the three-day cease-fire and prisoner exchange. PX-2, the case-packet official-source record, independently preserves the Kremlin source path and confirms the Russian official framing.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is context: Victory Day, Red Square, and prisoner exchange. But context is not the same as limitation. A ceasefire can have an occasion and still be general in scope. A prisoner exchange can be conducted during a general ceasefire; it does not convert the ceasefire into a humanitarian-only pause when the announced term is suspension of all kinetic activity in the war between the two states. Likewise, the Red Square decree may be narrow by itself, but PX-4 and PX-5 show broader Ukrainian confirmation alongside that narrow parade-security action.\\n\\nThe defense also points to violations and continued activity. That matters for compliance, not formation. The proposition asks whether the parties had officially reached the public mutual halt by May 31. It does not require that no shot was later fired. PX-5 candidly includes adverse context: reports of earlier violations, strikes, and retaliatory claims around the period. Those facts show why compliance was contested, but they do not erase the public mutual agreement reported and confirmed on May 8.\\n\\nProvenance and custody: the five case-packet files are juror-visible case-packet evidence. PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5 were submitted in this merits phase as text captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and descriptions; AAR accepted each and assigned evidence IDs. Direct X pages and some official pages were hard to capture in this environment, but the accepted evidence faithfully preserves the relevant source-chain content and is corroborated across independent outlets and the existing official-source packet.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, plaintiff need not prove a lasting peace or flawless battlefield silence. The better reading of the admitted evidence is that by May 8, before the May 31 deadline, Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire in the war, including suspension of kinetic activity. That satisfies the proposition.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has improved the record, but not enough to satisfy the proposition. The record now supports that a three-day truce was publicly discussed and confirmed around May 8. The remaining question is whether that truce constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange arrangement. On this record, the better answer remains no.\\n\\nStart with the rule. DX-1, the market-page record, requires more than any official ceasefire label. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited agreements and requires a general pause in the conflict. That scope requirement does real work here.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own proof shows why. PX-4 says Zelenskyy framed the arrangement this way: within U.S.-mediated negotiations, Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and a ceasefire regime “must also be established” on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 likewise ties Trump’s announcement to a prisoner swap and reports Zelenskyy ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the Victory Day parade. DX-2, the official-source packet, is even narrower on the Russian side: Ushakov confirmed Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and the packet’s Ukrainian official-adjacent decree record is limited to Red Square/parade targeting. Those are not side details. They are the public shape of the deal.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat “suspension of all kinetic activity” as dispositive. But the source chain remains mostly media-captured, with direct X, Truth Social, and official Ukrainian decree captures still missing. More importantly, an announced aspiration to suspend kinetic activity does not resolve whether the parties actually reached a general conflict pause, as opposed to a brief operational deconfliction attached to POW exchange and parade security. The burden is plaintiff’s, and ambiguity on scope counts against them.\\n\\nThe implementation evidence confirms that ambiguity. DX-4, the NV/ISW capture, reports Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It says intensity decreased but did not stop, Ukraine reported 51 combat engagements, Russian forces continued strikes in Kharkiv and Kherson Oblasts, and Russia claimed thousands of Ukrainian violations. It also reports ISW’s assessment that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions and that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square, which Kyiv upheld. That is powerful evidence that the practical, defined commitment was narrow.\\n\\nDX-5, CBS/AP’s May 10 report, shows the same pattern during the supposed pause. Both sides accused each other of breaking the ceasefire; Zelenskyy said Russia was not observing the truce and that there was no calm in frontline areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks; Russia accused Ukraine of more than 1,000 violations and said it responded in kind. CBS/AP also noted the three-day pause’s timeline was somewhat unclear. This is not offered to impose a perfect-compliance requirement. It is offered because widespread continued operations, undefined conditions, and mutual “response in kind” claims are probative of what kind of arrangement was actually reached.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s best legal point is that an agreement can be violated and still be an agreement. Correct. But the proposition is not “was there an agreement called a ceasefire?” It asks whether there was a general pause in military engagement. Formation and scope are intertwined: if the only clearly defined official condition was Red Square non-targeting, if Russia’s official acceptance described a prisoner-exchange purpose, if the exchange did not even occur as the announced 1,000-for-1,000 event during the truce period on this record, and if operations continued across the theater, then plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause by a preponderance.\\n\\nProvenance matters too. Plaintiff’s new exhibits are accepted text captures from reputable outlets, but they remain secondary captures of hard-to-access primary statements. The case-packet itself, DX-3, flags the same gaps: missing direct Zelenskyy social-media confirmation, missing direct Ukrainian presidential decree, missing direct Trump/White House record, and missing battlefield/monitoring evidence. Defendant filled part of that last gap with DX-4 and DX-5, and the result undercuts plaintiff’s scope theory.\\n\\nSearch and capture ledger: I checked targeted May 9-11 ceasefire-violation and ISW queries after reading plaintiff’s exhibits. ISW May 9-11 assessments appeared as the strongest implementation target; accessible captures were preserved through NV’s ISW summary and CBS/AP’s contemporaneous violation report. A Guardian May 9 Red Square/frontline article was opened but not submitted because DX-4 and DX-5 more directly address implementation and scope.\\n\\nThe council can find that a short truce was announced. It should not find that plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition. The admitted evidence shows a fragile, underdefined, prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with continued frontline operations, not a publicly agreed general pause in the Russia-Ukraine conflict.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s new evidence proves the wrong point. DX-4 and DX-5 are evidence of poor compliance, weak monitoring, and violation accusations. They are not evidence that the May 8 agreement was merely Red Square-only or that no official public mutual ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nThat distinction matters because the proposition and PX-1 focus on whether the parties had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt by May 31. The market rule even says a qualifying agreement can resolve Yes if officially reached before the resolution date regardless of later start mechanics. Defendant’s evidence is mostly about what happened after the agreement was announced.\\n\\nDX-4, the NV/ISW capture, says fighting intensity decreased but did not stop completely. It reports continued operations and weak ceasefire mechanisms. But it also states President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 exchange. DX-5, the CBS/AP capture, likewise reports accusations of violations, but it also states Trump announced Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire and that both sides appeared to agree. These are concessions on formation.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn noncompliance into narrow scope. That does not follow. A general ceasefire with poor monitoring can be violated. A general ceasefire can be attached to a prisoner exchange. A general ceasefire can coincide with Victory Day. None of those facts converts broad language like “ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine” and “suspension of all kinetic activity” into a Red Square-only arrangement.\\n\\nThe best scope evidence remains PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5. PX-3 says both sides confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire and suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-4 gives the Ukrainian-side confirmation: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement and a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 gives the U.S. announcement and both-side confirmation: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides.\\n\\nThe Red Square material is narrower, but it is not the whole agreement. It is an additional operational commitment about parade targeting. The prisoner exchange is likewise not disqualifying. The market excludes humanitarian pauses, but this record does not show a prisoner-exchange-only corridor or a local evacuation window. It shows a ceasefire in the war, with all kinetic activity suspended, plus a prisoner swap during that pause.\\n\\nDefendant also leans on missing primary captures. Those gaps affect weight, and plaintiff disclosed them. But the rule expressly permits wide credible media consensus, and the accepted captures are mutually reinforcing: Guardian, Ukrainska Pravda, RFE/RL, and the case-packet official-source record all converge on public mutual confirmation. Defendant’s own exhibits do not break that chain; they accept the announcement and agreement, then dispute implementation.\\n\\nSo the actual evidentiary balance is this: plaintiff has multiple accepted sources proving official public mutual agreement to a dated ceasefire with broad kinetic-activity language. Defendant has sources proving the ceasefire was fragile and violated. Under a preponderance standard, the former satisfies the proposition; the latter does not rewrite it.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal is right about one thing but draws the wrong conclusion. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been reached. If the record showed a clearly defined general pause followed by isolated breaches, defendant would lose that point.\\n\\nBut DX-4 and DX-5 are not just breach evidence. They are scope and character evidence. DX-4 reports that, on the first day of the supposed May 9-11 general pause, Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline; combat declined but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and ISW assessed that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most importantly, DX-4 says the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade. That does not look like a defined, general halt in military engagement. It looks like a fragile holiday/prisoner-exchange deconfliction with one concrete parade-security condition.\\n\\nDX-5 is similar. Plaintiff stresses that CBS/AP says both sides appeared to agree. But the same exhibit says the timeline was somewhat unclear, both sides accused each other of breaking the truce, Zelenskyy said there was no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and Russia claimed it responded in kind. Again, defendant is not saying every violation voids formation. Defendant is saying the record as a whole does not show the qualifying thing: a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nThat distinction is why plaintiff’s “formation not compliance” framing is too narrow. The proposition contains a scope element. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. The official-source packet says Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange. Plaintiff’s Ukrainian-side evidence likewise puts the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange at the center, and the direct Ukrainian decree remains missing while the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square-specific. Plaintiff’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase is powerful, but it is mostly preserved through media captures, not through the unavailable primary posts, and it must be weighed against the operational evidence that no defined general pause actually existed.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat announcement language as enough and implementation as irrelevant. The market does not permit that shortcut. It asks whether the parties reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. Where the public official detail is prisoner exchange and Red Square, the conditions are undefined, and fighting continued across the theater from the first day, plaintiff has not carried that stricter burden by a preponderance.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record resolves this case on a preponderance standard.\\n\\nThe proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It does not ask whether the war ended, whether the ceasefire was durable, or whether neither side later accused the other of violations.\\n\\nThe decisive record is straightforward. PX-1 defines the qualifying event as an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and permits a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. PX-3 reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, that Trump announced it as a ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, that it included suspension of all kinetic activity, and that it was confirmed by both sides. PX-4 supplies Ukrainian-side confirmation: Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 truce with Russia, said Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement, and said a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 supplies the U.S. announcement and the same mutual-confirmation frame: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides, including Russian agreement through Ushakov. PX-2 independently preserves the Russian official-source path.\\n\\nThat evidence satisfies the elements: official/public, mutual, dated before the deadline, and general in the only sense the market required: a halt in military engagement in the war, not a sector-only Black Sea or energy arrangement, not a mere informal understanding, and not a future framework.\\n\\nThe defense’s contrary evidence is important, but it points mainly to performance. DX-4 and DX-5 show continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. We should not ignore that. But both exhibits also preserve the formation facts: Trump announced the ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. A breached ceasefire is still a ceasefire agreement. The proposition turns on whether the agreement was reached, not whether it was perfectly obeyed.\\n\\nThe defense says the prisoner exchange and Victory Day context make the pause non-general. The better reading is that they explain why the parties accepted a temporary general pause. A prisoner exchange can occur during a broad ceasefire; it does not make the ceasefire humanitarian-only when the announced scope is suspension of all kinetic activity. Red Square non-targeting was an additional concrete operational condition, not the whole agreement. The record contains separate broader language: ceasefire in the war, ceasefire regime on May 9-11, suspension of kinetic activity, and both sides confirmed.\\n\\nThere are source-chain gaps: direct X, Truth Social, and some official pages were hard to capture. But the market rule expressly allows credible media consensus, and here the accepted sources converge with the case-packet official-source record. The defense’s own evidence does not break that convergence; it disputes execution.\\n\\nOn balance, plaintiff’s evidence proves more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed May 9-11 halt in military engagement before May 31. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case is not about whether something happened on May 8. Something did. The record supports that a short May 9-11 truce was announced and that both sides were reported as accepting it. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition: an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause, limited arrangement, or future framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. The market-page record requires a general pause and excludes humanitarian and limited agreements. That means the council cannot stop at the word “ceasefire” or at the fact of a public announcement. It must ask what kind of ceasefire the record proves.\\n\\nThe official-source packet supplies the best answer. Russia’s official source, through Ushakov, accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.” The key agreement described there was a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during May 9-11. On the Ukrainian official side, the direct presidential decree was not captured; the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square and parade-specific. Those facts do not prove a theatre-wide general pause. They prove a prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with a concrete parade-security component.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own merits exhibits do not eliminate that limitation. PX-4 quotes Zelenskyy in the context of the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and says a ceasefire regime must also be established. PX-5 reports the Trump announcement but also says Zelenskyy ordered no attack on Red Square and preserves the same prisoner-swap frame. Yes, those sources use broad language such as “suspension of all kinetic activity.” But broad media language must be weighed against the actual official-source detail, the missing primary captures, and what the parties did when the supposed general pause began.\\n\\nThat implementation evidence is decisive because it goes to character and scope, not merely breach. DX-4 reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day; combat intensity decreased but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most tellingly, DX-4 reports that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square. DX-5 reports no calm in front line areas, mutual violation accusations, an unclear timeline, and Russian “response in kind.”\\n\\nPlaintiff says violations are only compliance. If this were a clearly defined general ceasefire followed by isolated breaches, that would be right. But the record shows something different: undefined conditions, the one clearly public operational term being Red Square, a prisoner-exchange purpose, and continued operations across the theater from day one. That is evidence that the arrangement never rose to the general pause required by the proposition.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce caution. Direct X or Telegram, direct Truth Social or White House, and the direct Ukrainian decree remain absent. The rule allows credible media consensus, but consensus reporting does not override ambiguity in the official-source record and battlefield evidence. At most, plaintiff proved a fragile, short, U.S.-brokered truce label attached to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The market required more.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, if the evidence is equally consistent with a limited prisoner-exchange/parade-security pause and a qualifying general pause, plaintiff loses. Here the limiting evidence is stronger than equal. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and resolution criteria\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Official-source case-packet record\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Guardian both-sides confirmation report\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Ukrainian-side Zelensky confirmation report\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 RFE/RL Trump announcement and both-sides confirmation\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule requiring general pause and excluding limited/humanitarian pauses\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Official-source packet: Russian prisoner-exchange framing and narrow Ukrainian decree capture\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Unresolved record gaps and known tension on scope/violations\\n# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 NV/ISW: continued offensive operations and undefined ceasefire conditions\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 CBS/AP: mutual violation accusations and no calm on front lines\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-4/DX-6 Zelenskyy report tying ceasefire regime to prisoner exchange\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-5/DX-7 RFE/RL report with Red Square and adverse violation context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Guardian broad ceasefire confirmation\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Zelenskyy confirmation of ceasefire regime\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 RFE/RL both-side confirmation and adverse context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R4 Defendant NV/ISW exhibit showing compliance dispute, not no agreement\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R5 Defendant CBS/AP exhibit showing both sides appeared to agree\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 NV/ISW: continued operations and unclear conditions as scope evidence\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 CBS/AP: mutual violations, unclear timeline, no calm on front line\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Official-source packet: prisoner-exchange and Red Square framing\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S4 Market rule requiring a general pause, not limited/humanitarian arrangements\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 8 2026 report: Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire (ev_236dce43c3d8_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-236dce43c3d8)\\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\\nSHA-256: `236dce43c3d8f0a768feb3c9aa5e4214f9afb219b3cc647e8679b1179e916c6c`\\nBytes: 1583\\nRelevance: Credible media report that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, suspension of kinetic activity, and prisoner swap; directly addresses public mutual agreement and scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026: Zelenskyy confirms truce with Russia on May 9-11 (ev_2c8cd49d9b00_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-2c8cd49d9b00)\\nSource: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033888/\\nSHA-256: `2c8cd49d9b0040da3a58b04496b028fae6de5fb2b66b02d1f9b68b7bb84bbcac`\\nBytes: 1248\\nRelevance: Ukrainian media report based on Zelenskyy on X/Twitter confirming Russia's agreement and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11; addresses Ukrainian-side public confirmation.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] RFE/RL May 8 2026: Trump announces three-day cease-fire; both sides confirm (ev_5d2cebff6f4b_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2cebff6f4b)\\nSource: https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-russia-victory-day-cease-fire-drone-attacks/33752482.html\\nSHA-256: `5d2cebff6f4b0f521cbfa77b06da6f8548e1352caa5fc5983a21cf59c675b46a`\\nBytes: 1405\\nRelevance: Report preserving Trump announcement, confirmation by both sides, suspension of kinetic activity, prisoner swap, and adverse context of earlier violations; addresses official public agreement and scope/compliance distinction.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] NV May 10 2026 report on ISW assessment: fighting continued during first day of ceasefire (ev_52a3277a9302_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-52a3277a9302)\\nSource: https://english.nv.ua/russian-war/isw-says-fighting-continued-despite-may-9-11-ceasefire-50606640.html\\nSHA-256: `52a3277a93024fbf92cdd1f34c2ebf0ee4a62600c40ffa7809cd520718baba32`\\nBytes: 1823\\nRelevance: Shows adverse implementation and scope evidence: offensive operations continued across the frontline, combat declined but did not stop, ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, only known condition was Red Square non-targeting, and Russian forces allegedly used the period to reinforce positions.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] CBS/AP May 10 2026: Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating ceasefire (ev_d5ef4e09892f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-d5ef4e09892f)\\nSource: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/russia-ukraine-accuse-each-other-ceasefire-violations/\\nSHA-256: `d5ef4e09892f541e4806e0e6d705f5472ab9890cf4567bf47bf3a56b73f03dd8`\\nBytes: 1606\\nRelevance: Shows contemporaneous post-agreement evidence that both sides accused each other of violations, Zelenskyy said there was no calm on front lines despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and the ceasefire timing was unclear; bears on whether the arrangement was a general pause rather than fragile/limited truce.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and capture ledger\\nPlaintiff searched official and source-specific paths for the May 8-11 ceasefire record. Successful captures submitted as evidence: Guardian May 8 report, Ukrainska Pravda May 8 Zelenskyy confirmation report, and RFE/RL May 8 Trump/both-sides confirmation report. Existing case-packet evidence supplies market criteria and a Kremlin official-source summary. Capture limits: direct X pages for Zelenskyy and WhiteHouse rendered no text in web open; PBS returned 403; Ukrinform opened without readable lines; ISW May 8/May 11 direct pages returned 403; earlier curl to the Kremlin page timed out. These failures leave some primary-source gaps, but the accepted captures preserve the material source-chain content and include adverse context on alleged violations.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nAt merits, defendant inspected the new plaintiff evidence and searched targeted terms for May 9-11 ceasefire scope, violations, and ISW assessments. Source targets included ISW May 9-11 assessments, accessible media captures of those assessments, and contemporaneous violation reports. Defendant submitted accepted captures from NV/ISW and CBS/AP. Direct primary social/official sources remain incompletely captured in the record, including direct Zelenskyy X/Telegram, Trump Truth Social/White House, and president.gov.ua decree text; those gaps affect weight because plaintiff relies heavily on secondary captures for scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff rebuttal evidence audit\\nPlaintiff inspected the two new defendant exhibits by stat/read_evidence_range. Both primarily address implementation: continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. Both also preserve or concede agreement facts: Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. No additional outside source was needed for this targeted rebuttal.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:22.654219585Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887016,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":13},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":18,\"version\":29}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C5","after_version":29,"case_id":"arb-ex07-20260630022841","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C5","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C5\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the dispute is not whether the May 2026 Russia-Ukraine war ended, whether the May 9-11 pause was perfectly honored, or whether every later market-platform statement was correct. The proposition asks a narrower question: by the May 31 deadline, had the parties officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that was general in character rather than merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or a future framework? On this record, the answer should be yes.\n\nThe case-packet evidence gives the governing lens. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d, states that an official ceasefire agreement qualifies if it is publicly announced and mutually agreed, and that a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement had been reached can suffice. It excludes informal arrangements, humanitarian pauses, energy- or Black Sea-only deals, and future frameworks without an explicit dated commitment to stop fighting. That definition matters because the proof here points to a dated May 9-May 11 ceasefire, not simply aspirational peace talks.\n\nThe strongest plaintiff proof in the existing packet is the convergence between official-source material and credible reporting. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, identifies a Kremlin source in which Yury Ushakov, speaking on instructions from President Putin, confirmed Russia’s acceptance of the U.S.-proposed ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and located the key agreement in the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. The same file records that Ukrainian-side confirmation is currently captured through Ukrinform because direct access to the Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in the packet environment. That creates a provenance gap we should fill later, but it is not a contradiction.\n\nThe secondary-reporting record, ev_cf0c77f2fe52, then supplies the market rule’s alternative path: multiple credible outlets and ISW are summarized as reporting that Russia and Ukraine confirmed or agreed to a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11, with suspension of kinetic activity and an associated 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, preserves the same source map and correctly warns that platform assertions are not independent proof. I accept that warning. Our case rests on the official and reporting source chain, not on the market’s final Yes label.\n\nThe defense will have real points to test. The Russian official framing connects the pause to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform appears narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, candidly identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s social-media confirmation, the Ukrainian presidential page, Trump’s announcement, and battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused generally. It also notes alleged violations and continuing hostilities around the period. Those issues affect weight and may affect how the council evaluates scope and implementation.\n\nBut those gaps do not change the core theory. A qualifying agreement can be temporary. It can be attached to a prisoner exchange. It can be violated after it is reached. The decisive question is whether the parties publicly and officially agreed to halt military engagement generally for a dated period, not whether the ceasefire became a lasting peace or achieved perfect compliance. The packet’s plaintiff-side evidence already points to both sides confirming a three-day suspension of kinetic activity, while the defense evidence mainly argues motive, context, and performance.\n\nIn the next evidence phase, the plaintiff should admit the strongest underlying sources: the Kremlin page, the best accessible Ukrainian official or official-adjacent confirmation, direct presidential or U.S. announcement records if obtainable, and implementation/violation assessments from ISW or similar monitors. Those materials will let the council separate three questions: agreement reached, scope of the agreed halt, and compliance in the field. For opening purposes, the record supports the plaintiff’s framing: this was not merely an informal understanding or a future framework, but an officially announced, mutually confirmed, dated ceasefire agreement broad enough to satisfy the proposition by a preponderance of the evidence.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the thing this market asked for, not a nearby diplomatic event. The proposition requires an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict by May 31, 2026. It expressly excludes humanitarian pauses, limited arrangements, and future or partial frameworks.\n\nThe current packet does not yet carry that burden. It contains useful leads, but the strongest record materials point to a narrower event: a brief May 9-May 11 arrangement tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and a prisoner exchange. The market-page file, ev_f841be6ff80d, gives the rule and its exclusions, but it also warns that page-context assertions are platform assertions, not independent proof. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, repeats that caution: platform language cannot itself establish official mutuality, theatre-wide scope, implementation, or reliable consensus.\n\nThe official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, is where the burden problem becomes concrete. The Russian official text is not framed as a general pause in the conflict; it confirms Russia’s acceptance of a U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange, with the key agreement being a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during the May 9-May 11 period. On the Ukrainian side, the packet does not preserve a direct official presidential page; direct access reportedly returned 403. The available official-adjacent capture is Ukrinform’s report about a presidential decree that appears limited to allowing the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding Red Square from Ukrainian targeting during the parade. That is a substantial provenance and scope gap.\n\nThe plaintiff will rely on ev_cf0c77f2fe52, which summarizes credible reporting that both sides confirmed a three-day ceasefire. We do not ignore that. Secondary reporting may help find the underlying record and may later corroborate a mutual announcement. But at opening, those reports sit beside the packet’s own defense leads: Victory Day timing, Red Square security, prisoner-exchange purpose, allegations of violations, and ongoing retaliatory activity around the period. Those facts matter because the market did not ask whether some pause, some prisoner-exchange deconfliction, or some symbolic holiday arrangement occurred. It asked whether the parties had reached a general pause in military engagement.\n\nNor is this merely a compliance argument. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been agreed. But if the evidence shows the arrangement was designed and announced around a prisoner swap and parade security, and if fighting materially continued, that bears on whether the agreement was general in character at all. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, identifies the missing proof the council should want before finding for plaintiff: direct Zelenskyy confirmation, the direct Ukrainian presidential decree, direct Trump or White House announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence of whether hostilities generally paused, and complete official post-period violation statements.\n\nIn the evidence phase, the defense will test exactly those links: the full Kremlin text, the inaccessible Ukrainian decree or an authenticated archive, any direct Ukrainian presidential social-media confirmation, the U.S. announcement, ISW and other monitoring assessments, and post-period official violation statements. If those sources show a mutual, official, theatre-wide halt, plaintiff may have a case. If they show a short Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement amid continuing hostilities, the proposition fails.\n\nFor now, the packet supports caution, not a finding. Plaintiff’s opening treats a temporary three-day ceasefire label as enough. The market language demands more: a general pause in the conflict. On this record, the decisive proof is missing or points narrower, and the council should hold plaintiff to that burden.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the missing bridge the defense asked for. The record no longer rests only on the case packet. The admitted source captures show a public, mutual, dated ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine before the May 31 deadline, and the language used was broad enough to constitute a general halt in military engagement.\n\nStart with the governing rule. PX-1, the market-page record, requires an official ceasefire agreement: a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement. It excludes informal, humanitarian-only, energy-only, Black Sea-only, or future-framework arrangements. It also allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. That is exactly what the merits evidence now shows.\n\nPX-3, the Guardian May 8 capture, reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11. Its key points track the rule: Trump announced a ceasefire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine”; the ceasefire included suspension of all “kinetic activity”; and it was “confirmed by both sides.” The same capture records Ukrainian confirmation by Zelenskyy and Russian confirmation by Kremlin adviser Yury Ushakov. This is not a future framework. It is a dated ceasefire, announced before the deadline, with both parties identified.\n\nPX-4 directly answers the defense’s Ukrainian-source objection. Ukrainska Pravda, sourcing Zelenskyy on X, reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Trump’s truce with Russia for May 9-11 and quoted him saying Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement to conduct the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. That is Ukrainian-side public confirmation of Russia’s agreement and of the ceasefire regime. It is not merely a Red Square decree.\n\nPX-5 adds the U.S. announcement and the mutual-confirmation frame. RFE/RL reports Trump’s announcement of a three-day cease-fire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine,” including “suspension of all Kinetic activity,” and says both sides quickly confirmed the truce and prisoner swap. It also reports that Putin aide Yury Ushakov said Russia agreed to the three-day cease-fire and prisoner exchange. PX-2, the case-packet official-source record, independently preserves the Kremlin source path and confirms the Russian official framing.\n\nThe defense’s best point is context: Victory Day, Red Square, and prisoner exchange. But context is not the same as limitation. A ceasefire can have an occasion and still be general in scope. A prisoner exchange can be conducted during a general ceasefire; it does not convert the ceasefire into a humanitarian-only pause when the announced term is suspension of all kinetic activity in the war between the two states. Likewise, the Red Square decree may be narrow by itself, but PX-4 and PX-5 show broader Ukrainian confirmation alongside that narrow parade-security action.\n\nThe defense also points to violations and continued activity. That matters for compliance, not formation. The proposition asks whether the parties had officially reached the public mutual halt by May 31. It does not require that no shot was later fired. PX-5 candidly includes adverse context: reports of earlier violations, strikes, and retaliatory claims around the period. Those facts show why compliance was contested, but they do not erase the public mutual agreement reported and confirmed on May 8.\n\nProvenance and custody: the five case-packet files are juror-visible case-packet evidence. PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5 were submitted in this merits phase as text captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and descriptions; AAR accepted each and assigned evidence IDs. Direct X pages and some official pages were hard to capture in this environment, but the accepted evidence faithfully preserves the relevant source-chain content and is corroborated across independent outlets and the existing official-source packet.\n\nOn a preponderance standard, plaintiff need not prove a lasting peace or flawless battlefield silence. The better reading of the admitted evidence is that by May 8, before the May 31 deadline, Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire in the war, including suspension of kinetic activity. That satisfies the proposition.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has improved the record, but not enough to satisfy the proposition. The record now supports that a three-day truce was publicly discussed and confirmed around May 8. The remaining question is whether that truce constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange arrangement. On this record, the better answer remains no.\n\nStart with the rule. DX-1, the market-page record, requires more than any official ceasefire label. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited agreements and requires a general pause in the conflict. That scope requirement does real work here.\n\nPlaintiff’s own proof shows why. PX-4 says Zelenskyy framed the arrangement this way: within U.S.-mediated negotiations, Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and a ceasefire regime “must also be established” on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 likewise ties Trump’s announcement to a prisoner swap and reports Zelenskyy ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the Victory Day parade. DX-2, the official-source packet, is even narrower on the Russian side: Ushakov confirmed Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and the packet’s Ukrainian official-adjacent decree record is limited to Red Square/parade targeting. Those are not side details. They are the public shape of the deal.\n\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat “suspension of all kinetic activity” as dispositive. But the source chain remains mostly media-captured, with direct X, Truth Social, and official Ukrainian decree captures still missing. More importantly, an announced aspiration to suspend kinetic activity does not resolve whether the parties actually reached a general conflict pause, as opposed to a brief operational deconfliction attached to POW exchange and parade security. The burden is plaintiff’s, and ambiguity on scope counts against them.\n\nThe implementation evidence confirms that ambiguity. DX-4, the NV/ISW capture, reports Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It says intensity decreased but did not stop, Ukraine reported 51 combat engagements, Russian forces continued strikes in Kharkiv and Kherson Oblasts, and Russia claimed thousands of Ukrainian violations. It also reports ISW’s assessment that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions and that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square, which Kyiv upheld. That is powerful evidence that the practical, defined commitment was narrow.\n\nDX-5, CBS/AP’s May 10 report, shows the same pattern during the supposed pause. Both sides accused each other of breaking the ceasefire; Zelenskyy said Russia was not observing the truce and that there was no calm in frontline areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks; Russia accused Ukraine of more than 1,000 violations and said it responded in kind. CBS/AP also noted the three-day pause’s timeline was somewhat unclear. This is not offered to impose a perfect-compliance requirement. It is offered because widespread continued operations, undefined conditions, and mutual “response in kind” claims are probative of what kind of arrangement was actually reached.\n\nPlaintiff’s best legal point is that an agreement can be violated and still be an agreement. Correct. But the proposition is not “was there an agreement called a ceasefire?” It asks whether there was a general pause in military engagement. Formation and scope are intertwined: if the only clearly defined official condition was Red Square non-targeting, if Russia’s official acceptance described a prisoner-exchange purpose, if the exchange did not even occur as the announced 1,000-for-1,000 event during the truce period on this record, and if operations continued across the theater, then plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause by a preponderance.\n\nProvenance matters too. Plaintiff’s new exhibits are accepted text captures from reputable outlets, but they remain secondary captures of hard-to-access primary statements. The case-packet itself, DX-3, flags the same gaps: missing direct Zelenskyy social-media confirmation, missing direct Ukrainian presidential decree, missing direct Trump/White House record, and missing battlefield/monitoring evidence. Defendant filled part of that last gap with DX-4 and DX-5, and the result undercuts plaintiff’s scope theory.\n\nSearch and capture ledger: I checked targeted May 9-11 ceasefire-violation and ISW queries after reading plaintiff’s exhibits. ISW May 9-11 assessments appeared as the strongest implementation target; accessible captures were preserved through NV’s ISW summary and CBS/AP’s contemporaneous violation report. A Guardian May 9 Red Square/frontline article was opened but not submitted because DX-4 and DX-5 more directly address implementation and scope.\n\nThe council can find that a short truce was announced. It should not find that plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition. The admitted evidence shows a fragile, underdefined, prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with continued frontline operations, not a publicly agreed general pause in the Russia-Ukraine conflict.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s new evidence proves the wrong point. DX-4 and DX-5 are evidence of poor compliance, weak monitoring, and violation accusations. They are not evidence that the May 8 agreement was merely Red Square-only or that no official public mutual ceasefire agreement was reached.\n\nThat distinction matters because the proposition and PX-1 focus on whether the parties had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt by May 31. The market rule even says a qualifying agreement can resolve Yes if officially reached before the resolution date regardless of later start mechanics. Defendant’s evidence is mostly about what happened after the agreement was announced.\n\nDX-4, the NV/ISW capture, says fighting intensity decreased but did not stop completely. It reports continued operations and weak ceasefire mechanisms. But it also states President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 exchange. DX-5, the CBS/AP capture, likewise reports accusations of violations, but it also states Trump announced Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire and that both sides appeared to agree. These are concessions on formation.\n\nThe defense tries to turn noncompliance into narrow scope. That does not follow. A general ceasefire with poor monitoring can be violated. A general ceasefire can be attached to a prisoner exchange. A general ceasefire can coincide with Victory Day. None of those facts converts broad language like “ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine” and “suspension of all kinetic activity” into a Red Square-only arrangement.\n\nThe best scope evidence remains PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5. PX-3 says both sides confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire and suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-4 gives the Ukrainian-side confirmation: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement and a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 gives the U.S. announcement and both-side confirmation: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides.\n\nThe Red Square material is narrower, but it is not the whole agreement. It is an additional operational commitment about parade targeting. The prisoner exchange is likewise not disqualifying. The market excludes humanitarian pauses, but this record does not show a prisoner-exchange-only corridor or a local evacuation window. It shows a ceasefire in the war, with all kinetic activity suspended, plus a prisoner swap during that pause.\n\nDefendant also leans on missing primary captures. Those gaps affect weight, and plaintiff disclosed them. But the rule expressly permits wide credible media consensus, and the accepted captures are mutually reinforcing: Guardian, Ukrainska Pravda, RFE/RL, and the case-packet official-source record all converge on public mutual confirmation. Defendant’s own exhibits do not break that chain; they accept the announcement and agreement, then dispute implementation.\n\nSo the actual evidentiary balance is this: plaintiff has multiple accepted sources proving official public mutual agreement to a dated ceasefire with broad kinetic-activity language. Defendant has sources proving the ceasefire was fragile and violated. Under a preponderance standard, the former satisfies the proposition; the latter does not rewrite it.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal is right about one thing but draws the wrong conclusion. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been reached. If the record showed a clearly defined general pause followed by isolated breaches, defendant would lose that point.\n\nBut DX-4 and DX-5 are not just breach evidence. They are scope and character evidence. DX-4 reports that, on the first day of the supposed May 9-11 general pause, Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline; combat declined but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and ISW assessed that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most importantly, DX-4 says the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade. That does not look like a defined, general halt in military engagement. It looks like a fragile holiday/prisoner-exchange deconfliction with one concrete parade-security condition.\n\nDX-5 is similar. Plaintiff stresses that CBS/AP says both sides appeared to agree. But the same exhibit says the timeline was somewhat unclear, both sides accused each other of breaking the truce, Zelenskyy said there was no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and Russia claimed it responded in kind. Again, defendant is not saying every violation voids formation. Defendant is saying the record as a whole does not show the qualifying thing: a general pause in the conflict.\n\nThat distinction is why plaintiff’s “formation not compliance” framing is too narrow. The proposition contains a scope element. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. The official-source packet says Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange. Plaintiff’s Ukrainian-side evidence likewise puts the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange at the center, and the direct Ukrainian decree remains missing while the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square-specific. Plaintiff’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase is powerful, but it is mostly preserved through media captures, not through the unavailable primary posts, and it must be weighed against the operational evidence that no defined general pause actually existed.\n\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat announcement language as enough and implementation as irrelevant. The market does not permit that shortcut. It asks whether the parties reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. Where the public official detail is prisoner exchange and Red Square, the conditions are undefined, and fighting continued across the theater from the first day, plaintiff has not carried that stricter burden by a preponderance.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record resolves this case on a preponderance standard.\n\nThe proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It does not ask whether the war ended, whether the ceasefire was durable, or whether neither side later accused the other of violations.\n\nThe decisive record is straightforward. PX-1 defines the qualifying event as an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and permits a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. PX-3 reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, that Trump announced it as a ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, that it included suspension of all kinetic activity, and that it was confirmed by both sides. PX-4 supplies Ukrainian-side confirmation: Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 truce with Russia, said Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement, and said a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 supplies the U.S. announcement and the same mutual-confirmation frame: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides, including Russian agreement through Ushakov. PX-2 independently preserves the Russian official-source path.\n\nThat evidence satisfies the elements: official/public, mutual, dated before the deadline, and general in the only sense the market required: a halt in military engagement in the war, not a sector-only Black Sea or energy arrangement, not a mere informal understanding, and not a future framework.\n\nThe defense’s contrary evidence is important, but it points mainly to performance. DX-4 and DX-5 show continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. We should not ignore that. But both exhibits also preserve the formation facts: Trump announced the ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. A breached ceasefire is still a ceasefire agreement. The proposition turns on whether the agreement was reached, not whether it was perfectly obeyed.\n\nThe defense says the prisoner exchange and Victory Day context make the pause non-general. The better reading is that they explain why the parties accepted a temporary general pause. A prisoner exchange can occur during a broad ceasefire; it does not make the ceasefire humanitarian-only when the announced scope is suspension of all kinetic activity. Red Square non-targeting was an additional concrete operational condition, not the whole agreement. The record contains separate broader language: ceasefire in the war, ceasefire regime on May 9-11, suspension of kinetic activity, and both sides confirmed.\n\nThere are source-chain gaps: direct X, Truth Social, and some official pages were hard to capture. But the market rule expressly allows credible media consensus, and here the accepted sources converge with the case-packet official-source record. The defense’s own evidence does not break that convergence; it disputes execution.\n\nOn balance, plaintiff’s evidence proves more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed May 9-11 halt in military engagement before May 31. The council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, this case is not about whether something happened on May 8. Something did. The record supports that a short May 9-11 truce was announced and that both sides were reported as accepting it. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition: an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause, limited arrangement, or future framework.\n\nPlaintiff has not carried that burden.\n\nStart with the governing rule. The market-page record requires a general pause and excludes humanitarian and limited agreements. That means the council cannot stop at the word “ceasefire” or at the fact of a public announcement. It must ask what kind of ceasefire the record proves.\n\nThe official-source packet supplies the best answer. Russia’s official source, through Ushakov, accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.” The key agreement described there was a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during May 9-11. On the Ukrainian official side, the direct presidential decree was not captured; the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square and parade-specific. Those facts do not prove a theatre-wide general pause. They prove a prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with a concrete parade-security component.\n\nPlaintiff’s own merits exhibits do not eliminate that limitation. PX-4 quotes Zelenskyy in the context of the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and says a ceasefire regime must also be established. PX-5 reports the Trump announcement but also says Zelenskyy ordered no attack on Red Square and preserves the same prisoner-swap frame. Yes, those sources use broad language such as “suspension of all kinetic activity.” But broad media language must be weighed against the actual official-source detail, the missing primary captures, and what the parties did when the supposed general pause began.\n\nThat implementation evidence is decisive because it goes to character and scope, not merely breach. DX-4 reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day; combat intensity decreased but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most tellingly, DX-4 reports that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square. DX-5 reports no calm in front line areas, mutual violation accusations, an unclear timeline, and Russian “response in kind.”\n\nPlaintiff says violations are only compliance. If this were a clearly defined general ceasefire followed by isolated breaches, that would be right. But the record shows something different: undefined conditions, the one clearly public operational term being Red Square, a prisoner-exchange purpose, and continued operations across the theater from day one. That is evidence that the arrangement never rose to the general pause required by the proposition.\n\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce caution. Direct X or Telegram, direct Truth Social or White House, and the direct Ukrainian decree remain absent. The rule allows credible media consensus, but consensus reporting does not override ambiguity in the official-source record and battlefield evidence. At most, plaintiff proved a fragile, short, U.S.-brokered truce label attached to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The market required more.\n\nOn a preponderance standard, if the evidence is equally consistent with a limited prisoner-exchange/parade-security pause and a qualifying general pause, plaintiff loses. Here the limiting evidence is stronger than equal. The council should find the proposition not proven.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and resolution criteria\n# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Official-source case-packet record\n# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Guardian both-sides confirmation report\nSource: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Ukrainian-side Zelensky confirmation report\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 RFE/RL Trump announcement and both-sides confirmation\nSource: RFE/RL, \"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \"suspension of all Kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \"cease-fire regime must also be established,\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\n\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule requiring general pause and excluding limited/humanitarian pauses\n# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-2 Official-source packet: Russian prisoner-exchange framing and narrow Ukrainian decree capture\n# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-3 Unresolved record gaps and known tension on scope/violations\n# Unresolved record gaps\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\n\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\n\nKnown record tension:\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \"general pause\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-4 NV/ISW: continued offensive operations and undefined ceasefire conditions\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\n\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\n\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n[defendant] DX-5 CBS/AP: mutual violation accusations and no calm on front lines\nSource: CBS News/AP, \"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\n\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \"even particularly trying to,\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\n\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\n\n[defendant] PX-4/DX-6 Zelenskyy report tying ceasefire regime to prisoner exchange\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\n\n[defendant] PX-5/DX-7 RFE/RL report with Red Square and adverse violation context\nSource: RFE/RL, \"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \"suspension of all Kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \"cease-fire regime must also be established,\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Guardian broad ceasefire confirmation\nSource: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Zelenskyy confirmation of ceasefire regime\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 RFE/RL both-side confirmation and adverse context\nSource: RFE/RL, \"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \"suspension of all Kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \"cease-fire regime must also be established,\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R4 Defendant NV/ISW exhibit showing compliance dispute, not no agreement\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\n\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\n\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R5 Defendant CBS/AP exhibit showing both sides appeared to agree\nSource: CBS News/AP, \"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\n\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \"even particularly trying to,\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\n\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 NV/ISW: continued operations and unclear conditions as scope evidence\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\n\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\n\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 CBS/AP: mutual violations, unclear timeline, no calm on front line\nSource: CBS News/AP, \"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\n\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \"even particularly trying to,\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\n\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\n\n[defendant] DX-S3 Official-source packet: prisoner-exchange and Red Square framing\n# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-S4 Market rule requiring a general pause, not limited/humanitarian arrangements\n# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 8 2026 report: Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire (ev_236dce43c3d8_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-236dce43c3d8)\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\nSHA-256: `236dce43c3d8f0a768feb3c9aa5e4214f9afb219b3cc647e8679b1179e916c6c`\nBytes: 1583\nRelevance: Credible media report that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, suspension of kinetic activity, and prisoner swap; directly addresses public mutual agreement and scope.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026: Zelenskyy confirms truce with Russia on May 9-11 (ev_2c8cd49d9b00_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-2c8cd49d9b00)\nSource: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033888/\nSHA-256: `2c8cd49d9b0040da3a58b04496b028fae6de5fb2b66b02d1f9b68b7bb84bbcac`\nBytes: 1248\nRelevance: Ukrainian media report based on Zelenskyy on X/Twitter confirming Russia's agreement and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11; addresses Ukrainian-side public confirmation.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] RFE/RL May 8 2026: Trump announces three-day cease-fire; both sides confirm (ev_5d2cebff6f4b_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2cebff6f4b)\nSource: https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-russia-victory-day-cease-fire-drone-attacks/33752482.html\nSHA-256: `5d2cebff6f4b0f521cbfa77b06da6f8548e1352caa5fc5983a21cf59c675b46a`\nBytes: 1405\nRelevance: Report preserving Trump announcement, confirmation by both sides, suspension of kinetic activity, prisoner swap, and adverse context of earlier violations; addresses official public agreement and scope/compliance distinction.\n\n[defendant arguments] NV May 10 2026 report on ISW assessment: fighting continued during first day of ceasefire (ev_52a3277a9302_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-52a3277a9302)\nSource: https://english.nv.ua/russian-war/isw-says-fighting-continued-despite-may-9-11-ceasefire-50606640.html\nSHA-256: `52a3277a93024fbf92cdd1f34c2ebf0ee4a62600c40ffa7809cd520718baba32`\nBytes: 1823\nRelevance: Shows adverse implementation and scope evidence: offensive operations continued across the frontline, combat declined but did not stop, ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, only known condition was Red Square non-targeting, and Russian forces allegedly used the period to reinforce positions.\n\n[defendant arguments] CBS/AP May 10 2026: Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating ceasefire (ev_d5ef4e09892f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-d5ef4e09892f)\nSource: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/russia-ukraine-accuse-each-other-ceasefire-violations/\nSHA-256: `d5ef4e09892f541e4806e0e6d705f5472ab9890cf4567bf47bf3a56b73f03dd8`\nBytes: 1606\nRelevance: Shows contemporaneous post-agreement evidence that both sides accused each other of violations, Zelenskyy said there was no calm on front lines despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and the ceasefire timing was unclear; bears on whether the arrangement was a general pause rather than fragile/limited truce.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and capture ledger\nPlaintiff searched official and source-specific paths for the May 8-11 ceasefire record. Successful captures submitted as evidence: Guardian May 8 report, Ukrainska Pravda May 8 Zelenskyy confirmation report, and RFE/RL May 8 Trump/both-sides confirmation report. Existing case-packet evidence supplies market criteria and a Kremlin official-source summary. Capture limits: direct X pages for Zelenskyy and WhiteHouse rendered no text in web open; PBS returned 403; Ukrinform opened without readable lines; ISW May 8/May 11 direct pages returned 403; earlier curl to the Kremlin page timed out. These failures leave some primary-source gaps, but the accepted captures preserve the material source-chain content and include adverse context on alleged violations.\n\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\nAt merits, defendant inspected the new plaintiff evidence and searched targeted terms for May 9-11 ceasefire scope, violations, and ISW assessments. Source targets included ISW May 9-11 assessments, accessible media captures of those assessments, and contemporaneous violation reports. Defendant submitted accepted captures from NV/ISW and CBS/AP. Direct primary social/official sources remain incompletely captured in the record, including direct Zelenskyy X/Telegram, Trump Truth Social/White House, and president.gov.ua decree text; those gaps affect weight because plaintiff relies heavily on secondary captures for scope.\n\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff rebuttal evidence audit\nPlaintiff inspected the two new defendant exhibits by stat/read_evidence_range. Both primarily address implementation: continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. Both also preserve or concede agreement facts: Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. No additional outside source was needed for this targeted rebuttal.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T03:06:22.654219585Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C5","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C5","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":887016,"role_id":"council","turn_number":13},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":18,"version":29}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782787895642}}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"functions.mcp:0","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 29\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630022841\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nremaining_ms: 887016\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"after_version\":29,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630022841\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C5\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the dispute is not whether the May 2026 Russia-Ukraine war ended, whether the May 9-11 pause was perfectly honored, or whether every later market-platform statement was correct. The proposition asks a narrower question: by the May 31 deadline, had the parties officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that was general in character rather than merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or a future framework? On this record, the answer should be yes.\\n\\nThe case-packet evidence gives the governing lens. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d, states that an official ceasefire agreement qualifies if it is publicly announced and mutually agreed, and that a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement had been reached can suffice. It excludes informal arrangements, humanitarian pauses, energy- or Black Sea-only deals, and future frameworks without an explicit dated commitment to stop fighting. That definition matters because the proof here points to a dated May 9-May 11 ceasefire, not simply aspirational peace talks.\\n\\nThe strongest plaintiff proof in the existing packet is the convergence between official-source material and credible reporting. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, identifies a Kremlin source in which Yury Ushakov, speaking on instructions from President Putin, confirmed Russia’s acceptance of the U.S.-proposed ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and located the key agreement in the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. The same file records that Ukrainian-side confirmation is currently captured through Ukrinform because direct access to the Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in the packet environment. That creates a provenance gap we should fill later, but it is not a contradiction.\\n\\nThe secondary-reporting record, ev_cf0c77f2fe52, then supplies the market rule’s alternative path: multiple credible outlets and ISW are summarized as reporting that Russia and Ukraine confirmed or agreed to a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11, with suspension of kinetic activity and an associated 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, preserves the same source map and correctly warns that platform assertions are not independent proof. I accept that warning. Our case rests on the official and reporting source chain, not on the market’s final Yes label.\\n\\nThe defense will have real points to test. The Russian official framing connects the pause to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform appears narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, candidly identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s social-media confirmation, the Ukrainian presidential page, Trump’s announcement, and battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused generally. It also notes alleged violations and continuing hostilities around the period. Those issues affect weight and may affect how the council evaluates scope and implementation.\\n\\nBut those gaps do not change the core theory. A qualifying agreement can be temporary. It can be attached to a prisoner exchange. It can be violated after it is reached. The decisive question is whether the parties publicly and officially agreed to halt military engagement generally for a dated period, not whether the ceasefire became a lasting peace or achieved perfect compliance. The packet’s plaintiff-side evidence already points to both sides confirming a three-day suspension of kinetic activity, while the defense evidence mainly argues motive, context, and performance.\\n\\nIn the next evidence phase, the plaintiff should admit the strongest underlying sources: the Kremlin page, the best accessible Ukrainian official or official-adjacent confirmation, direct presidential or U.S. announcement records if obtainable, and implementation/violation assessments from ISW or similar monitors. Those materials will let the council separate three questions: agreement reached, scope of the agreed halt, and compliance in the field. For opening purposes, the record supports the plaintiff’s framing: this was not merely an informal understanding or a future framework, but an officially announced, mutually confirmed, dated ceasefire agreement broad enough to satisfy the proposition by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the thing this market asked for, not a nearby diplomatic event. The proposition requires an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict by May 31, 2026. It expressly excludes humanitarian pauses, limited arrangements, and future or partial frameworks.\\n\\nThe current packet does not yet carry that burden. It contains useful leads, but the strongest record materials point to a narrower event: a brief May 9-May 11 arrangement tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and a prisoner exchange. The market-page file, ev_f841be6ff80d, gives the rule and its exclusions, but it also warns that page-context assertions are platform assertions, not independent proof. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, repeats that caution: platform language cannot itself establish official mutuality, theatre-wide scope, implementation, or reliable consensus.\\n\\nThe official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, is where the burden problem becomes concrete. The Russian official text is not framed as a general pause in the conflict; it confirms Russia’s acceptance of a U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange, with the key agreement being a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during the May 9-May 11 period. On the Ukrainian side, the packet does not preserve a direct official presidential page; direct access reportedly returned 403. The available official-adjacent capture is Ukrinform’s report about a presidential decree that appears limited to allowing the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding Red Square from Ukrainian targeting during the parade. That is a substantial provenance and scope gap.\\n\\nThe plaintiff will rely on ev_cf0c77f2fe52, which summarizes credible reporting that both sides confirmed a three-day ceasefire. We do not ignore that. Secondary reporting may help find the underlying record and may later corroborate a mutual announcement. But at opening, those reports sit beside the packet’s own defense leads: Victory Day timing, Red Square security, prisoner-exchange purpose, allegations of violations, and ongoing retaliatory activity around the period. Those facts matter because the market did not ask whether some pause, some prisoner-exchange deconfliction, or some symbolic holiday arrangement occurred. It asked whether the parties had reached a general pause in military engagement.\\n\\nNor is this merely a compliance argument. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been agreed. But if the evidence shows the arrangement was designed and announced around a prisoner swap and parade security, and if fighting materially continued, that bears on whether the agreement was general in character at all. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, identifies the missing proof the council should want before finding for plaintiff: direct Zelenskyy confirmation, the direct Ukrainian presidential decree, direct Trump or White House announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence of whether hostilities generally paused, and complete official post-period violation statements.\\n\\nIn the evidence phase, the defense will test exactly those links: the full Kremlin text, the inaccessible Ukrainian decree or an authenticated archive, any direct Ukrainian presidential social-media confirmation, the U.S. announcement, ISW and other monitoring assessments, and post-period official violation statements. If those sources show a mutual, official, theatre-wide halt, plaintiff may have a case. If they show a short Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement amid continuing hostilities, the proposition fails.\\n\\nFor now, the packet supports caution, not a finding. Plaintiff’s opening treats a temporary three-day ceasefire label as enough. The market language demands more: a general pause in the conflict. On this record, the decisive proof is missing or points narrower, and the council should hold plaintiff to that burden.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the missing bridge the defense asked for. The record no longer rests only on the case packet. The admitted source captures show a public, mutual, dated ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine before the May 31 deadline, and the language used was broad enough to constitute a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. PX-1, the market-page record, requires an official ceasefire agreement: a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement. It excludes informal, humanitarian-only, energy-only, Black Sea-only, or future-framework arrangements. It also allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. That is exactly what the merits evidence now shows.\\n\\nPX-3, the Guardian May 8 capture, reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11. Its key points track the rule: Trump announced a ceasefire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine”; the ceasefire included suspension of all “kinetic activity”; and it was “confirmed by both sides.” The same capture records Ukrainian confirmation by Zelenskyy and Russian confirmation by Kremlin adviser Yury Ushakov. This is not a future framework. It is a dated ceasefire, announced before the deadline, with both parties identified.\\n\\nPX-4 directly answers the defense’s Ukrainian-source objection. Ukrainska Pravda, sourcing Zelenskyy on X, reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Trump’s truce with Russia for May 9-11 and quoted him saying Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement to conduct the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. That is Ukrainian-side public confirmation of Russia’s agreement and of the ceasefire regime. It is not merely a Red Square decree.\\n\\nPX-5 adds the U.S. announcement and the mutual-confirmation frame. RFE/RL reports Trump’s announcement of a three-day cease-fire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine,” including “suspension of all Kinetic activity,” and says both sides quickly confirmed the truce and prisoner swap. It also reports that Putin aide Yury Ushakov said Russia agreed to the three-day cease-fire and prisoner exchange. PX-2, the case-packet official-source record, independently preserves the Kremlin source path and confirms the Russian official framing.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is context: Victory Day, Red Square, and prisoner exchange. But context is not the same as limitation. A ceasefire can have an occasion and still be general in scope. A prisoner exchange can be conducted during a general ceasefire; it does not convert the ceasefire into a humanitarian-only pause when the announced term is suspension of all kinetic activity in the war between the two states. Likewise, the Red Square decree may be narrow by itself, but PX-4 and PX-5 show broader Ukrainian confirmation alongside that narrow parade-security action.\\n\\nThe defense also points to violations and continued activity. That matters for compliance, not formation. The proposition asks whether the parties had officially reached the public mutual halt by May 31. It does not require that no shot was later fired. PX-5 candidly includes adverse context: reports of earlier violations, strikes, and retaliatory claims around the period. Those facts show why compliance was contested, but they do not erase the public mutual agreement reported and confirmed on May 8.\\n\\nProvenance and custody: the five case-packet files are juror-visible case-packet evidence. PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5 were submitted in this merits phase as text captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and descriptions; AAR accepted each and assigned evidence IDs. Direct X pages and some official pages were hard to capture in this environment, but the accepted evidence faithfully preserves the relevant source-chain content and is corroborated across independent outlets and the existing official-source packet.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, plaintiff need not prove a lasting peace or flawless battlefield silence. The better reading of the admitted evidence is that by May 8, before the May 31 deadline, Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire in the war, including suspension of kinetic activity. That satisfies the proposition.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has improved the record, but not enough to satisfy the proposition. The record now supports that a three-day truce was publicly discussed and confirmed around May 8. The remaining question is whether that truce constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange arrangement. On this record, the better answer remains no.\\n\\nStart with the rule. DX-1, the market-page record, requires more than any official ceasefire label. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited agreements and requires a general pause in the conflict. That scope requirement does real work here.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own proof shows why. PX-4 says Zelenskyy framed the arrangement this way: within U.S.-mediated negotiations, Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and a ceasefire regime “must also be established” on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 likewise ties Trump’s announcement to a prisoner swap and reports Zelenskyy ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the Victory Day parade. DX-2, the official-source packet, is even narrower on the Russian side: Ushakov confirmed Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and the packet’s Ukrainian official-adjacent decree record is limited to Red Square/parade targeting. Those are not side details. They are the public shape of the deal.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat “suspension of all kinetic activity” as dispositive. But the source chain remains mostly media-captured, with direct X, Truth Social, and official Ukrainian decree captures still missing. More importantly, an announced aspiration to suspend kinetic activity does not resolve whether the parties actually reached a general conflict pause, as opposed to a brief operational deconfliction attached to POW exchange and parade security. The burden is plaintiff’s, and ambiguity on scope counts against them.\\n\\nThe implementation evidence confirms that ambiguity. DX-4, the NV/ISW capture, reports Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It says intensity decreased but did not stop, Ukraine reported 51 combat engagements, Russian forces continued strikes in Kharkiv and Kherson Oblasts, and Russia claimed thousands of Ukrainian violations. It also reports ISW’s assessment that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions and that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square, which Kyiv upheld. That is powerful evidence that the practical, defined commitment was narrow.\\n\\nDX-5, CBS/AP’s May 10 report, shows the same pattern during the supposed pause. Both sides accused each other of breaking the ceasefire; Zelenskyy said Russia was not observing the truce and that there was no calm in frontline areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks; Russia accused Ukraine of more than 1,000 violations and said it responded in kind. CBS/AP also noted the three-day pause’s timeline was somewhat unclear. This is not offered to impose a perfect-compliance requirement. It is offered because widespread continued operations, undefined conditions, and mutual “response in kind” claims are probative of what kind of arrangement was actually reached.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s best legal point is that an agreement can be violated and still be an agreement. Correct. But the proposition is not “was there an agreement called a ceasefire?” It asks whether there was a general pause in military engagement. Formation and scope are intertwined: if the only clearly defined official condition was Red Square non-targeting, if Russia’s official acceptance described a prisoner-exchange purpose, if the exchange did not even occur as the announced 1,000-for-1,000 event during the truce period on this record, and if operations continued across the theater, then plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause by a preponderance.\\n\\nProvenance matters too. Plaintiff’s new exhibits are accepted text captures from reputable outlets, but they remain secondary captures of hard-to-access primary statements. The case-packet itself, DX-3, flags the same gaps: missing direct Zelenskyy social-media confirmation, missing direct Ukrainian presidential decree, missing direct Trump/White House record, and missing battlefield/monitoring evidence. Defendant filled part of that last gap with DX-4 and DX-5, and the result undercuts plaintiff’s scope theory.\\n\\nSearch and capture ledger: I checked targeted May 9-11 ceasefire-violation and ISW queries after reading plaintiff’s exhibits. ISW May 9-11 assessments appeared as the strongest implementation target; accessible captures were preserved through NV’s ISW summary and CBS/AP’s contemporaneous violation report. A Guardian May 9 Red Square/frontline article was opened but not submitted because DX-4 and DX-5 more directly address implementation and scope.\\n\\nThe council can find that a short truce was announced. It should not find that plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition. The admitted evidence shows a fragile, underdefined, prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with continued frontline operations, not a publicly agreed general pause in the Russia-Ukraine conflict.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s new evidence proves the wrong point. DX-4 and DX-5 are evidence of poor compliance, weak monitoring, and violation accusations. They are not evidence that the May 8 agreement was merely Red Square-only or that no official public mutual ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nThat distinction matters because the proposition and PX-1 focus on whether the parties had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt by May 31. The market rule even says a qualifying agreement can resolve Yes if officially reached before the resolution date regardless of later start mechanics. Defendant’s evidence is mostly about what happened after the agreement was announced.\\n\\nDX-4, the NV/ISW capture, says fighting intensity decreased but did not stop completely. It reports continued operations and weak ceasefire mechanisms. But it also states President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 exchange. DX-5, the CBS/AP capture, likewise reports accusations of violations, but it also states Trump announced Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire and that both sides appeared to agree. These are concessions on formation.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn noncompliance into narrow scope. That does not follow. A general ceasefire with poor monitoring can be violated. A general ceasefire can be attached to a prisoner exchange. A general ceasefire can coincide with Victory Day. None of those facts converts broad language like “ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine” and “suspension of all kinetic activity” into a Red Square-only arrangement.\\n\\nThe best scope evidence remains PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5. PX-3 says both sides confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire and suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-4 gives the Ukrainian-side confirmation: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement and a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 gives the U.S. announcement and both-side confirmation: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides.\\n\\nThe Red Square material is narrower, but it is not the whole agreement. It is an additional operational commitment about parade targeting. The prisoner exchange is likewise not disqualifying. The market excludes humanitarian pauses, but this record does not show a prisoner-exchange-only corridor or a local evacuation window. It shows a ceasefire in the war, with all kinetic activity suspended, plus a prisoner swap during that pause.\\n\\nDefendant also leans on missing primary captures. Those gaps affect weight, and plaintiff disclosed them. But the rule expressly permits wide credible media consensus, and the accepted captures are mutually reinforcing: Guardian, Ukrainska Pravda, RFE/RL, and the case-packet official-source record all converge on public mutual confirmation. Defendant’s own exhibits do not break that chain; they accept the announcement and agreement, then dispute implementation.\\n\\nSo the actual evidentiary balance is this: plaintiff has multiple accepted sources proving official public mutual agreement to a dated ceasefire with broad kinetic-activity language. Defendant has sources proving the ceasefire was fragile and violated. Under a preponderance standard, the former satisfies the proposition; the latter does not rewrite it.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal is right about one thing but draws the wrong conclusion. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been reached. If the record showed a clearly defined general pause followed by isolated breaches, defendant would lose that point.\\n\\nBut DX-4 and DX-5 are not just breach evidence. They are scope and character evidence. DX-4 reports that, on the first day of the supposed May 9-11 general pause, Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline; combat declined but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and ISW assessed that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most importantly, DX-4 says the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade. That does not look like a defined, general halt in military engagement. It looks like a fragile holiday/prisoner-exchange deconfliction with one concrete parade-security condition.\\n\\nDX-5 is similar. Plaintiff stresses that CBS/AP says both sides appeared to agree. But the same exhibit says the timeline was somewhat unclear, both sides accused each other of breaking the truce, Zelenskyy said there was no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and Russia claimed it responded in kind. Again, defendant is not saying every violation voids formation. Defendant is saying the record as a whole does not show the qualifying thing: a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nThat distinction is why plaintiff’s “formation not compliance” framing is too narrow. The proposition contains a scope element. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. The official-source packet says Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange. Plaintiff’s Ukrainian-side evidence likewise puts the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange at the center, and the direct Ukrainian decree remains missing while the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square-specific. Plaintiff’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase is powerful, but it is mostly preserved through media captures, not through the unavailable primary posts, and it must be weighed against the operational evidence that no defined general pause actually existed.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat announcement language as enough and implementation as irrelevant. The market does not permit that shortcut. It asks whether the parties reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. Where the public official detail is prisoner exchange and Red Square, the conditions are undefined, and fighting continued across the theater from the first day, plaintiff has not carried that stricter burden by a preponderance.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record resolves this case on a preponderance standard.\\n\\nThe proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It does not ask whether the war ended, whether the ceasefire was durable, or whether neither side later accused the other of violations.\\n\\nThe decisive record is straightforward. PX-1 defines the qualifying event as an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and permits a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. PX-3 reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, that Trump announced it as a ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, that it included suspension of all kinetic activity, and that it was confirmed by both sides. PX-4 supplies Ukrainian-side confirmation: Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 truce with Russia, said Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement, and said a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 supplies the U.S. announcement and the same mutual-confirmation frame: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides, including Russian agreement through Ushakov. PX-2 independently preserves the Russian official-source path.\\n\\nThat evidence satisfies the elements: official/public, mutual, dated before the deadline, and general in the only sense the market required: a halt in military engagement in the war, not a sector-only Black Sea or energy arrangement, not a mere informal understanding, and not a future framework.\\n\\nThe defense’s contrary evidence is important, but it points mainly to performance. DX-4 and DX-5 show continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. We should not ignore that. But both exhibits also preserve the formation facts: Trump announced the ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. A breached ceasefire is still a ceasefire agreement. The proposition turns on whether the agreement was reached, not whether it was perfectly obeyed.\\n\\nThe defense says the prisoner exchange and Victory Day context make the pause non-general. The better reading is that they explain why the parties accepted a temporary general pause. A prisoner exchange can occur during a broad ceasefire; it does not make the ceasefire humanitarian-only when the announced scope is suspension of all kinetic activity. Red Square non-targeting was an additional concrete operational condition, not the whole agreement. The record contains separate broader language: ceasefire in the war, ceasefire regime on May 9-11, suspension of kinetic activity, and both sides confirmed.\\n\\nThere are source-chain gaps: direct X, Truth Social, and some official pages were hard to capture. But the market rule expressly allows credible media consensus, and here the accepted sources converge with the case-packet official-source record. The defense’s own evidence does not break that convergence; it disputes execution.\\n\\nOn balance, plaintiff’s evidence proves more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed May 9-11 halt in military engagement before May 31. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case is not about whether something happened on May 8. Something did. The record supports that a short May 9-11 truce was announced and that both sides were reported as accepting it. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition: an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause, limited arrangement, or future framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. The market-page record requires a general pause and excludes humanitarian and limited agreements. That means the council cannot stop at the word “ceasefire” or at the fact of a public announcement. It must ask what kind of ceasefire the record proves.\\n\\nThe official-source packet supplies the best answer. Russia’s official source, through Ushakov, accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.” The key agreement described there was a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during May 9-11. On the Ukrainian official side, the direct presidential decree was not captured; the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square and parade-specific. Those facts do not prove a theatre-wide general pause. They prove a prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with a concrete parade-security component.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own merits exhibits do not eliminate that limitation. PX-4 quotes Zelenskyy in the context of the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and says a ceasefire regime must also be established. PX-5 reports the Trump announcement but also says Zelenskyy ordered no attack on Red Square and preserves the same prisoner-swap frame. Yes, those sources use broad language such as “suspension of all kinetic activity.” But broad media language must be weighed against the actual official-source detail, the missing primary captures, and what the parties did when the supposed general pause began.\\n\\nThat implementation evidence is decisive because it goes to character and scope, not merely breach. DX-4 reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day; combat intensity decreased but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most tellingly, DX-4 reports that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square. DX-5 reports no calm in front line areas, mutual violation accusations, an unclear timeline, and Russian “response in kind.”\\n\\nPlaintiff says violations are only compliance. If this were a clearly defined general ceasefire followed by isolated breaches, that would be right. But the record shows something different: undefined conditions, the one clearly public operational term being Red Square, a prisoner-exchange purpose, and continued operations across the theater from day one. That is evidence that the arrangement never rose to the general pause required by the proposition.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce caution. Direct X or Telegram, direct Truth Social or White House, and the direct Ukrainian decree remain absent. The rule allows credible media consensus, but consensus reporting does not override ambiguity in the official-source record and battlefield evidence. At most, plaintiff proved a fragile, short, U.S.-brokered truce label attached to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The market required more.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, if the evidence is equally consistent with a limited prisoner-exchange/parade-security pause and a qualifying general pause, plaintiff loses. Here the limiting evidence is stronger than equal. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and resolution criteria\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Official-source case-packet record\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Guardian both-sides confirmation report\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Ukrainian-side Zelensky confirmation report\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 RFE/RL Trump announcement and both-sides confirmation\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule requiring general pause and excluding limited/humanitarian pauses\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Official-source packet: Russian prisoner-exchange framing and narrow Ukrainian decree capture\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Unresolved record gaps and known tension on scope/violations\\n# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 NV/ISW: continued offensive operations and undefined ceasefire conditions\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 CBS/AP: mutual violation accusations and no calm on front lines\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-4/DX-6 Zelenskyy report tying ceasefire regime to prisoner exchange\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-5/DX-7 RFE/RL report with Red Square and adverse violation context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Guardian broad ceasefire confirmation\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Zelenskyy confirmation of ceasefire regime\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 RFE/RL both-side confirmation and adverse context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R4 Defendant NV/ISW exhibit showing compliance dispute, not no agreement\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R5 Defendant CBS/AP exhibit showing both sides appeared to agree\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 NV/ISW: continued operations and unclear conditions as scope evidence\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 CBS/AP: mutual violations, unclear timeline, no calm on front line\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Official-source packet: prisoner-exchange and Red Square framing\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S4 Market rule requiring a general pause, not limited/humanitarian arrangements\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 8 2026 report: Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire (ev_236dce43c3d8_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-236dce43c3d8)\\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\\nSHA-256: `236dce43c3d8f0a768feb3c9aa5e4214f9afb219b3cc647e8679b1179e916c6c`\\nBytes: 1583\\nRelevance: Credible media report that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, suspension of kinetic activity, and prisoner swap; directly addresses public mutual agreement and scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026: Zelenskyy confirms truce with Russia on May 9-11 (ev_2c8cd49d9b00_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-2c8cd49d9b00)\\nSource: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033888/\\nSHA-256: `2c8cd49d9b0040da3a58b04496b028fae6de5fb2b66b02d1f9b68b7bb84bbcac`\\nBytes: 1248\\nRelevance: Ukrainian media report based on Zelenskyy on X/Twitter confirming Russia's agreement and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11; addresses Ukrainian-side public confirmation.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] RFE/RL May 8 2026: Trump announces three-day cease-fire; both sides confirm (ev_5d2cebff6f4b_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2cebff6f4b)\\nSource: https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-russia-victory-day-cease-fire-drone-attacks/33752482.html\\nSHA-256: `5d2cebff6f4b0f521cbfa77b06da6f8548e1352caa5fc5983a21cf59c675b46a`\\nBytes: 1405\\nRelevance: Report preserving Trump announcement, confirmation by both sides, suspension of kinetic activity, prisoner swap, and adverse context of earlier violations; addresses official public agreement and scope/compliance distinction.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] NV May 10 2026 report on ISW assessment: fighting continued during first day of ceasefire (ev_52a3277a9302_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-52a3277a9302)\\nSource: https://english.nv.ua/russian-war/isw-says-fighting-continued-despite-may-9-11-ceasefire-50606640.html\\nSHA-256: `52a3277a93024fbf92cdd1f34c2ebf0ee4a62600c40ffa7809cd520718baba32`\\nBytes: 1823\\nRelevance: Shows adverse implementation and scope evidence: offensive operations continued across the frontline, combat declined but did not stop, ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, only known condition was Red Square non-targeting, and Russian forces allegedly used the period to reinforce positions.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] CBS/AP May 10 2026: Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating ceasefire (ev_d5ef4e09892f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-d5ef4e09892f)\\nSource: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/russia-ukraine-accuse-each-other-ceasefire-violations/\\nSHA-256: `d5ef4e09892f541e4806e0e6d705f5472ab9890cf4567bf47bf3a56b73f03dd8`\\nBytes: 1606\\nRelevance: Shows contemporaneous post-agreement evidence that both sides accused each other of violations, Zelenskyy said there was no calm on front lines despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and the ceasefire timing was unclear; bears on whether the arrangement was a general pause rather than fragile/limited truce.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and capture ledger\\nPlaintiff searched official and source-specific paths for the May 8-11 ceasefire record. Successful captures submitted as evidence: Guardian May 8 report, Ukrainska Pravda May 8 Zelenskyy confirmation report, and RFE/RL May 8 Trump/both-sides confirmation report. Existing case-packet evidence supplies market criteria and a Kremlin official-source summary. Capture limits: direct X pages for Zelenskyy and WhiteHouse rendered no text in web open; PBS returned 403; Ukrinform opened without readable lines; ISW May 8/May 11 direct pages returned 403; earlier curl to the Kremlin page timed out. These failures leave some primary-source gaps, but the accepted captures preserve the material source-chain content and include adverse context on alleged violations.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nAt merits, defendant inspected the new plaintiff evidence and searched targeted terms for May 9-11 ceasefire scope, violations, and ISW assessments. Source targets included ISW May 9-11 assessments, accessible media captures of those assessments, and contemporaneous violation reports. Defendant submitted accepted captures from NV/ISW and CBS/AP. Direct primary social/official sources remain incompletely captured in the record, including direct Zelenskyy X/Telegram, Trump Truth Social/White House, and president.gov.ua decree text; those gaps affect weight because plaintiff relies heavily on secondary captures for scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff rebuttal evidence audit\\nPlaintiff inspected the two new defendant exhibits by stat/read_evidence_range. Both primarily address implementation: continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. Both also preserve or concede agreement facts: Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. No additional outside source was needed for this targeted rebuttal.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:22.654219585Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887016,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":13},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":18,\"version\":29}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 29\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630022841\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nremaining_ms: 887016\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"after_version\":29,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630022841\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C5\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the dispute is not whether the May 2026 Russia-Ukraine war ended, whether the May 9-11 pause was perfectly honored, or whether every later market-platform statement was correct. The proposition asks a narrower question: by the May 31 deadline, had the parties officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that was general in character rather than merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or a future framework? On this record, the answer should be yes.\\n\\nThe case-packet evidence gives the governing lens. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d, states that an official ceasefire agreement qualifies if it is publicly announced and mutually agreed, and that a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement had been reached can suffice. It excludes informal arrangements, humanitarian pauses, energy- or Black Sea-only deals, and future frameworks without an explicit dated commitment to stop fighting. That definition matters because the proof here points to a dated May 9-May 11 ceasefire, not simply aspirational peace talks.\\n\\nThe strongest plaintiff proof in the existing packet is the convergence between official-source material and credible reporting. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, identifies a Kremlin source in which Yury Ushakov, speaking on instructions from President Putin, confirmed Russia’s acceptance of the U.S.-proposed ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and located the key agreement in the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. The same file records that Ukrainian-side confirmation is currently captured through Ukrinform because direct access to the Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in the packet environment. That creates a provenance gap we should fill later, but it is not a contradiction.\\n\\nThe secondary-reporting record, ev_cf0c77f2fe52, then supplies the market rule’s alternative path: multiple credible outlets and ISW are summarized as reporting that Russia and Ukraine confirmed or agreed to a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11, with suspension of kinetic activity and an associated 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, preserves the same source map and correctly warns that platform assertions are not independent proof. I accept that warning. Our case rests on the official and reporting source chain, not on the market’s final Yes label.\\n\\nThe defense will have real points to test. The Russian official framing connects the pause to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform appears narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, candidly identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s social-media confirmation, the Ukrainian presidential page, Trump’s announcement, and battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused generally. It also notes alleged violations and continuing hostilities around the period. Those issues affect weight and may affect how the council evaluates scope and implementation.\\n\\nBut those gaps do not change the core theory. A qualifying agreement can be temporary. It can be attached to a prisoner exchange. It can be violated after it is reached. The decisive question is whether the parties publicly and officially agreed to halt military engagement generally for a dated period, not whether the ceasefire became a lasting peace or achieved perfect compliance. The packet’s plaintiff-side evidence already points to both sides confirming a three-day suspension of kinetic activity, while the defense evidence mainly argues motive, context, and performance.\\n\\nIn the next evidence phase, the plaintiff should admit the strongest underlying sources: the Kremlin page, the best accessible Ukrainian official or official-adjacent confirmation, direct presidential or U.S. announcement records if obtainable, and implementation/violation assessments from ISW or similar monitors. Those materials will let the council separate three questions: agreement reached, scope of the agreed halt, and compliance in the field. For opening purposes, the record supports the plaintiff’s framing: this was not merely an informal understanding or a future framework, but an officially announced, mutually confirmed, dated ceasefire agreement broad enough to satisfy the proposition by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the thing this market asked for, not a nearby diplomatic event. The proposition requires an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict by May 31, 2026. It expressly excludes humanitarian pauses, limited arrangements, and future or partial frameworks.\\n\\nThe current packet does not yet carry that burden. It contains useful leads, but the strongest record materials point to a narrower event: a brief May 9-May 11 arrangement tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and a prisoner exchange. The market-page file, ev_f841be6ff80d, gives the rule and its exclusions, but it also warns that page-context assertions are platform assertions, not independent proof. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, repeats that caution: platform language cannot itself establish official mutuality, theatre-wide scope, implementation, or reliable consensus.\\n\\nThe official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, is where the burden problem becomes concrete. The Russian official text is not framed as a general pause in the conflict; it confirms Russia’s acceptance of a U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange, with the key agreement being a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during the May 9-May 11 period. On the Ukrainian side, the packet does not preserve a direct official presidential page; direct access reportedly returned 403. The available official-adjacent capture is Ukrinform’s report about a presidential decree that appears limited to allowing the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding Red Square from Ukrainian targeting during the parade. That is a substantial provenance and scope gap.\\n\\nThe plaintiff will rely on ev_cf0c77f2fe52, which summarizes credible reporting that both sides confirmed a three-day ceasefire. We do not ignore that. Secondary reporting may help find the underlying record and may later corroborate a mutual announcement. But at opening, those reports sit beside the packet’s own defense leads: Victory Day timing, Red Square security, prisoner-exchange purpose, allegations of violations, and ongoing retaliatory activity around the period. Those facts matter because the market did not ask whether some pause, some prisoner-exchange deconfliction, or some symbolic holiday arrangement occurred. It asked whether the parties had reached a general pause in military engagement.\\n\\nNor is this merely a compliance argument. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been agreed. But if the evidence shows the arrangement was designed and announced around a prisoner swap and parade security, and if fighting materially continued, that bears on whether the agreement was general in character at all. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, identifies the missing proof the council should want before finding for plaintiff: direct Zelenskyy confirmation, the direct Ukrainian presidential decree, direct Trump or White House announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence of whether hostilities generally paused, and complete official post-period violation statements.\\n\\nIn the evidence phase, the defense will test exactly those links: the full Kremlin text, the inaccessible Ukrainian decree or an authenticated archive, any direct Ukrainian presidential social-media confirmation, the U.S. announcement, ISW and other monitoring assessments, and post-period official violation statements. If those sources show a mutual, official, theatre-wide halt, plaintiff may have a case. If they show a short Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement amid continuing hostilities, the proposition fails.\\n\\nFor now, the packet supports caution, not a finding. Plaintiff’s opening treats a temporary three-day ceasefire label as enough. The market language demands more: a general pause in the conflict. On this record, the decisive proof is missing or points narrower, and the council should hold plaintiff to that burden.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the missing bridge the defense asked for. The record no longer rests only on the case packet. The admitted source captures show a public, mutual, dated ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine before the May 31 deadline, and the language used was broad enough to constitute a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. PX-1, the market-page record, requires an official ceasefire agreement: a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement. It excludes informal, humanitarian-only, energy-only, Black Sea-only, or future-framework arrangements. It also allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. That is exactly what the merits evidence now shows.\\n\\nPX-3, the Guardian May 8 capture, reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11. Its key points track the rule: Trump announced a ceasefire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine”; the ceasefire included suspension of all “kinetic activity”; and it was “confirmed by both sides.” The same capture records Ukrainian confirmation by Zelenskyy and Russian confirmation by Kremlin adviser Yury Ushakov. This is not a future framework. It is a dated ceasefire, announced before the deadline, with both parties identified.\\n\\nPX-4 directly answers the defense’s Ukrainian-source objection. Ukrainska Pravda, sourcing Zelenskyy on X, reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Trump’s truce with Russia for May 9-11 and quoted him saying Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement to conduct the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. That is Ukrainian-side public confirmation of Russia’s agreement and of the ceasefire regime. It is not merely a Red Square decree.\\n\\nPX-5 adds the U.S. announcement and the mutual-confirmation frame. RFE/RL reports Trump’s announcement of a three-day cease-fire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine,” including “suspension of all Kinetic activity,” and says both sides quickly confirmed the truce and prisoner swap. It also reports that Putin aide Yury Ushakov said Russia agreed to the three-day cease-fire and prisoner exchange. PX-2, the case-packet official-source record, independently preserves the Kremlin source path and confirms the Russian official framing.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is context: Victory Day, Red Square, and prisoner exchange. But context is not the same as limitation. A ceasefire can have an occasion and still be general in scope. A prisoner exchange can be conducted during a general ceasefire; it does not convert the ceasefire into a humanitarian-only pause when the announced term is suspension of all kinetic activity in the war between the two states. Likewise, the Red Square decree may be narrow by itself, but PX-4 and PX-5 show broader Ukrainian confirmation alongside that narrow parade-security action.\\n\\nThe defense also points to violations and continued activity. That matters for compliance, not formation. The proposition asks whether the parties had officially reached the public mutual halt by May 31. It does not require that no shot was later fired. PX-5 candidly includes adverse context: reports of earlier violations, strikes, and retaliatory claims around the period. Those facts show why compliance was contested, but they do not erase the public mutual agreement reported and confirmed on May 8.\\n\\nProvenance and custody: the five case-packet files are juror-visible case-packet evidence. PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5 were submitted in this merits phase as text captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and descriptions; AAR accepted each and assigned evidence IDs. Direct X pages and some official pages were hard to capture in this environment, but the accepted evidence faithfully preserves the relevant source-chain content and is corroborated across independent outlets and the existing official-source packet.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, plaintiff need not prove a lasting peace or flawless battlefield silence. The better reading of the admitted evidence is that by May 8, before the May 31 deadline, Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire in the war, including suspension of kinetic activity. That satisfies the proposition.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has improved the record, but not enough to satisfy the proposition. The record now supports that a three-day truce was publicly discussed and confirmed around May 8. The remaining question is whether that truce constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange arrangement. On this record, the better answer remains no.\\n\\nStart with the rule. DX-1, the market-page record, requires more than any official ceasefire label. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited agreements and requires a general pause in the conflict. That scope requirement does real work here.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own proof shows why. PX-4 says Zelenskyy framed the arrangement this way: within U.S.-mediated negotiations, Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and a ceasefire regime “must also be established” on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 likewise ties Trump’s announcement to a prisoner swap and reports Zelenskyy ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the Victory Day parade. DX-2, the official-source packet, is even narrower on the Russian side: Ushakov confirmed Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and the packet’s Ukrainian official-adjacent decree record is limited to Red Square/parade targeting. Those are not side details. They are the public shape of the deal.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat “suspension of all kinetic activity” as dispositive. But the source chain remains mostly media-captured, with direct X, Truth Social, and official Ukrainian decree captures still missing. More importantly, an announced aspiration to suspend kinetic activity does not resolve whether the parties actually reached a general conflict pause, as opposed to a brief operational deconfliction attached to POW exchange and parade security. The burden is plaintiff’s, and ambiguity on scope counts against them.\\n\\nThe implementation evidence confirms that ambiguity. DX-4, the NV/ISW capture, reports Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It says intensity decreased but did not stop, Ukraine reported 51 combat engagements, Russian forces continued strikes in Kharkiv and Kherson Oblasts, and Russia claimed thousands of Ukrainian violations. It also reports ISW’s assessment that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions and that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square, which Kyiv upheld. That is powerful evidence that the practical, defined commitment was narrow.\\n\\nDX-5, CBS/AP’s May 10 report, shows the same pattern during the supposed pause. Both sides accused each other of breaking the ceasefire; Zelenskyy said Russia was not observing the truce and that there was no calm in frontline areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks; Russia accused Ukraine of more than 1,000 violations and said it responded in kind. CBS/AP also noted the three-day pause’s timeline was somewhat unclear. This is not offered to impose a perfect-compliance requirement. It is offered because widespread continued operations, undefined conditions, and mutual “response in kind” claims are probative of what kind of arrangement was actually reached.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s best legal point is that an agreement can be violated and still be an agreement. Correct. But the proposition is not “was there an agreement called a ceasefire?” It asks whether there was a general pause in military engagement. Formation and scope are intertwined: if the only clearly defined official condition was Red Square non-targeting, if Russia’s official acceptance described a prisoner-exchange purpose, if the exchange did not even occur as the announced 1,000-for-1,000 event during the truce period on this record, and if operations continued across the theater, then plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause by a preponderance.\\n\\nProvenance matters too. Plaintiff’s new exhibits are accepted text captures from reputable outlets, but they remain secondary captures of hard-to-access primary statements. The case-packet itself, DX-3, flags the same gaps: missing direct Zelenskyy social-media confirmation, missing direct Ukrainian presidential decree, missing direct Trump/White House record, and missing battlefield/monitoring evidence. Defendant filled part of that last gap with DX-4 and DX-5, and the result undercuts plaintiff’s scope theory.\\n\\nSearch and capture ledger: I checked targeted May 9-11 ceasefire-violation and ISW queries after reading plaintiff’s exhibits. ISW May 9-11 assessments appeared as the strongest implementation target; accessible captures were preserved through NV’s ISW summary and CBS/AP’s contemporaneous violation report. A Guardian May 9 Red Square/frontline article was opened but not submitted because DX-4 and DX-5 more directly address implementation and scope.\\n\\nThe council can find that a short truce was announced. It should not find that plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition. The admitted evidence shows a fragile, underdefined, prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with continued frontline operations, not a publicly agreed general pause in the Russia-Ukraine conflict.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s new evidence proves the wrong point. DX-4 and DX-5 are evidence of poor compliance, weak monitoring, and violation accusations. They are not evidence that the May 8 agreement was merely Red Square-only or that no official public mutual ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nThat distinction matters because the proposition and PX-1 focus on whether the parties had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt by May 31. The market rule even says a qualifying agreement can resolve Yes if officially reached before the resolution date regardless of later start mechanics. Defendant’s evidence is mostly about what happened after the agreement was announced.\\n\\nDX-4, the NV/ISW capture, says fighting intensity decreased but did not stop completely. It reports continued operations and weak ceasefire mechanisms. But it also states President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 exchange. DX-5, the CBS/AP capture, likewise reports accusations of violations, but it also states Trump announced Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire and that both sides appeared to agree. These are concessions on formation.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn noncompliance into narrow scope. That does not follow. A general ceasefire with poor monitoring can be violated. A general ceasefire can be attached to a prisoner exchange. A general ceasefire can coincide with Victory Day. None of those facts converts broad language like “ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine” and “suspension of all kinetic activity” into a Red Square-only arrangement.\\n\\nThe best scope evidence remains PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5. PX-3 says both sides confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire and suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-4 gives the Ukrainian-side confirmation: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement and a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 gives the U.S. announcement and both-side confirmation: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides.\\n\\nThe Red Square material is narrower, but it is not the whole agreement. It is an additional operational commitment about parade targeting. The prisoner exchange is likewise not disqualifying. The market excludes humanitarian pauses, but this record does not show a prisoner-exchange-only corridor or a local evacuation window. It shows a ceasefire in the war, with all kinetic activity suspended, plus a prisoner swap during that pause.\\n\\nDefendant also leans on missing primary captures. Those gaps affect weight, and plaintiff disclosed them. But the rule expressly permits wide credible media consensus, and the accepted captures are mutually reinforcing: Guardian, Ukrainska Pravda, RFE/RL, and the case-packet official-source record all converge on public mutual confirmation. Defendant’s own exhibits do not break that chain; they accept the announcement and agreement, then dispute implementation.\\n\\nSo the actual evidentiary balance is this: plaintiff has multiple accepted sources proving official public mutual agreement to a dated ceasefire with broad kinetic-activity language. Defendant has sources proving the ceasefire was fragile and violated. Under a preponderance standard, the former satisfies the proposition; the latter does not rewrite it.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal is right about one thing but draws the wrong conclusion. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been reached. If the record showed a clearly defined general pause followed by isolated breaches, defendant would lose that point.\\n\\nBut DX-4 and DX-5 are not just breach evidence. They are scope and character evidence. DX-4 reports that, on the first day of the supposed May 9-11 general pause, Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline; combat declined but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and ISW assessed that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most importantly, DX-4 says the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade. That does not look like a defined, general halt in military engagement. It looks like a fragile holiday/prisoner-exchange deconfliction with one concrete parade-security condition.\\n\\nDX-5 is similar. Plaintiff stresses that CBS/AP says both sides appeared to agree. But the same exhibit says the timeline was somewhat unclear, both sides accused each other of breaking the truce, Zelenskyy said there was no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and Russia claimed it responded in kind. Again, defendant is not saying every violation voids formation. Defendant is saying the record as a whole does not show the qualifying thing: a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nThat distinction is why plaintiff’s “formation not compliance” framing is too narrow. The proposition contains a scope element. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. The official-source packet says Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange. Plaintiff’s Ukrainian-side evidence likewise puts the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange at the center, and the direct Ukrainian decree remains missing while the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square-specific. Plaintiff’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase is powerful, but it is mostly preserved through media captures, not through the unavailable primary posts, and it must be weighed against the operational evidence that no defined general pause actually existed.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat announcement language as enough and implementation as irrelevant. The market does not permit that shortcut. It asks whether the parties reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. Where the public official detail is prisoner exchange and Red Square, the conditions are undefined, and fighting continued across the theater from the first day, plaintiff has not carried that stricter burden by a preponderance.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record resolves this case on a preponderance standard.\\n\\nThe proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It does not ask whether the war ended, whether the ceasefire was durable, or whether neither side later accused the other of violations.\\n\\nThe decisive record is straightforward. PX-1 defines the qualifying event as an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and permits a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. PX-3 reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, that Trump announced it as a ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, that it included suspension of all kinetic activity, and that it was confirmed by both sides. PX-4 supplies Ukrainian-side confirmation: Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 truce with Russia, said Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement, and said a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 supplies the U.S. announcement and the same mutual-confirmation frame: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides, including Russian agreement through Ushakov. PX-2 independently preserves the Russian official-source path.\\n\\nThat evidence satisfies the elements: official/public, mutual, dated before the deadline, and general in the only sense the market required: a halt in military engagement in the war, not a sector-only Black Sea or energy arrangement, not a mere informal understanding, and not a future framework.\\n\\nThe defense’s contrary evidence is important, but it points mainly to performance. DX-4 and DX-5 show continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. We should not ignore that. But both exhibits also preserve the formation facts: Trump announced the ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. A breached ceasefire is still a ceasefire agreement. The proposition turns on whether the agreement was reached, not whether it was perfectly obeyed.\\n\\nThe defense says the prisoner exchange and Victory Day context make the pause non-general. The better reading is that they explain why the parties accepted a temporary general pause. A prisoner exchange can occur during a broad ceasefire; it does not make the ceasefire humanitarian-only when the announced scope is suspension of all kinetic activity. Red Square non-targeting was an additional concrete operational condition, not the whole agreement. The record contains separate broader language: ceasefire in the war, ceasefire regime on May 9-11, suspension of kinetic activity, and both sides confirmed.\\n\\nThere are source-chain gaps: direct X, Truth Social, and some official pages were hard to capture. But the market rule expressly allows credible media consensus, and here the accepted sources converge with the case-packet official-source record. The defense’s own evidence does not break that convergence; it disputes execution.\\n\\nOn balance, plaintiff’s evidence proves more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed May 9-11 halt in military engagement before May 31. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case is not about whether something happened on May 8. Something did. The record supports that a short May 9-11 truce was announced and that both sides were reported as accepting it. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition: an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause, limited arrangement, or future framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. The market-page record requires a general pause and excludes humanitarian and limited agreements. That means the council cannot stop at the word “ceasefire” or at the fact of a public announcement. It must ask what kind of ceasefire the record proves.\\n\\nThe official-source packet supplies the best answer. Russia’s official source, through Ushakov, accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.” The key agreement described there was a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during May 9-11. On the Ukrainian official side, the direct presidential decree was not captured; the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square and parade-specific. Those facts do not prove a theatre-wide general pause. They prove a prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with a concrete parade-security component.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own merits exhibits do not eliminate that limitation. PX-4 quotes Zelenskyy in the context of the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and says a ceasefire regime must also be established. PX-5 reports the Trump announcement but also says Zelenskyy ordered no attack on Red Square and preserves the same prisoner-swap frame. Yes, those sources use broad language such as “suspension of all kinetic activity.” But broad media language must be weighed against the actual official-source detail, the missing primary captures, and what the parties did when the supposed general pause began.\\n\\nThat implementation evidence is decisive because it goes to character and scope, not merely breach. DX-4 reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day; combat intensity decreased but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most tellingly, DX-4 reports that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square. DX-5 reports no calm in front line areas, mutual violation accusations, an unclear timeline, and Russian “response in kind.”\\n\\nPlaintiff says violations are only compliance. If this were a clearly defined general ceasefire followed by isolated breaches, that would be right. But the record shows something different: undefined conditions, the one clearly public operational term being Red Square, a prisoner-exchange purpose, and continued operations across the theater from day one. That is evidence that the arrangement never rose to the general pause required by the proposition.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce caution. Direct X or Telegram, direct Truth Social or White House, and the direct Ukrainian decree remain absent. The rule allows credible media consensus, but consensus reporting does not override ambiguity in the official-source record and battlefield evidence. At most, plaintiff proved a fragile, short, U.S.-brokered truce label attached to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The market required more.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, if the evidence is equally consistent with a limited prisoner-exchange/parade-security pause and a qualifying general pause, plaintiff loses. Here the limiting evidence is stronger than equal. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and resolution criteria\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Official-source case-packet record\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Guardian both-sides confirmation report\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Ukrainian-side Zelensky confirmation report\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 RFE/RL Trump announcement and both-sides confirmation\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule requiring general pause and excluding limited/humanitarian pauses\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Official-source packet: Russian prisoner-exchange framing and narrow Ukrainian decree capture\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Unresolved record gaps and known tension on scope/violations\\n# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 NV/ISW: continued offensive operations and undefined ceasefire conditions\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 CBS/AP: mutual violation accusations and no calm on front lines\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-4/DX-6 Zelenskyy report tying ceasefire regime to prisoner exchange\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-5/DX-7 RFE/RL report with Red Square and adverse violation context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Guardian broad ceasefire confirmation\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Zelenskyy confirmation of ceasefire regime\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 RFE/RL both-side confirmation and adverse context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R4 Defendant NV/ISW exhibit showing compliance dispute, not no agreement\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R5 Defendant CBS/AP exhibit showing both sides appeared to agree\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 NV/ISW: continued operations and unclear conditions as scope evidence\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 CBS/AP: mutual violations, unclear timeline, no calm on front line\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Official-source packet: prisoner-exchange and Red Square framing\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S4 Market rule requiring a general pause, not limited/humanitarian arrangements\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 8 2026 report: Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire (ev_236dce43c3d8_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-236dce43c3d8)\\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\\nSHA-256: `236dce43c3d8f0a768feb3c9aa5e4214f9afb219b3cc647e8679b1179e916c6c`\\nBytes: 1583\\nRelevance: Credible media report that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, suspension of kinetic activity, and prisoner swap; directly addresses public mutual agreement and scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026: Zelenskyy confirms truce with Russia on May 9-11 (ev_2c8cd49d9b00_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-2c8cd49d9b00)\\nSource: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033888/\\nSHA-256: `2c8cd49d9b0040da3a58b04496b028fae6de5fb2b66b02d1f9b68b7bb84bbcac`\\nBytes: 1248\\nRelevance: Ukrainian media report based on Zelenskyy on X/Twitter confirming Russia's agreement and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11; addresses Ukrainian-side public confirmation.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] RFE/RL May 8 2026: Trump announces three-day cease-fire; both sides confirm (ev_5d2cebff6f4b_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2cebff6f4b)\\nSource: https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-russia-victory-day-cease-fire-drone-attacks/33752482.html\\nSHA-256: `5d2cebff6f4b0f521cbfa77b06da6f8548e1352caa5fc5983a21cf59c675b46a`\\nBytes: 1405\\nRelevance: Report preserving Trump announcement, confirmation by both sides, suspension of kinetic activity, prisoner swap, and adverse context of earlier violations; addresses official public agreement and scope/compliance distinction.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] NV May 10 2026 report on ISW assessment: fighting continued during first day of ceasefire (ev_52a3277a9302_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-52a3277a9302)\\nSource: https://english.nv.ua/russian-war/isw-says-fighting-continued-despite-may-9-11-ceasefire-50606640.html\\nSHA-256: `52a3277a93024fbf92cdd1f34c2ebf0ee4a62600c40ffa7809cd520718baba32`\\nBytes: 1823\\nRelevance: Shows adverse implementation and scope evidence: offensive operations continued across the frontline, combat declined but did not stop, ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, only known condition was Red Square non-targeting, and Russian forces allegedly used the period to reinforce positions.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] CBS/AP May 10 2026: Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating ceasefire (ev_d5ef4e09892f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-d5ef4e09892f)\\nSource: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/russia-ukraine-accuse-each-other-ceasefire-violations/\\nSHA-256: `d5ef4e09892f541e4806e0e6d705f5472ab9890cf4567bf47bf3a56b73f03dd8`\\nBytes: 1606\\nRelevance: Shows contemporaneous post-agreement evidence that both sides accused each other of violations, Zelenskyy said there was no calm on front lines despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and the ceasefire timing was unclear; bears on whether the arrangement was a general pause rather than fragile/limited truce.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and capture ledger\\nPlaintiff searched official and source-specific paths for the May 8-11 ceasefire record. Successful captures submitted as evidence: Guardian May 8 report, Ukrainska Pravda May 8 Zelenskyy confirmation report, and RFE/RL May 8 Trump/both-sides confirmation report. Existing case-packet evidence supplies market criteria and a Kremlin official-source summary. Capture limits: direct X pages for Zelenskyy and WhiteHouse rendered no text in web open; PBS returned 403; Ukrinform opened without readable lines; ISW May 8/May 11 direct pages returned 403; earlier curl to the Kremlin page timed out. These failures leave some primary-source gaps, but the accepted captures preserve the material source-chain content and include adverse context on alleged violations.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nAt merits, defendant inspected the new plaintiff evidence and searched targeted terms for May 9-11 ceasefire scope, violations, and ISW assessments. Source targets included ISW May 9-11 assessments, accessible media captures of those assessments, and contemporaneous violation reports. Defendant submitted accepted captures from NV/ISW and CBS/AP. Direct primary social/official sources remain incompletely captured in the record, including direct Zelenskyy X/Telegram, Trump Truth Social/White House, and president.gov.ua decree text; those gaps affect weight because plaintiff relies heavily on secondary captures for scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff rebuttal evidence audit\\nPlaintiff inspected the two new defendant exhibits by stat/read_evidence_range. Both primarily address implementation: continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. Both also preserve or concede agreement facts: Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. No additional outside source was needed for this targeted rebuttal.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:22.654219585Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887016,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":13},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":18,\"version\":29}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C5","after_version":29,"case_id":"arb-ex07-20260630022841","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C5","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C5\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the dispute is not whether the May 2026 Russia-Ukraine war ended, whether the May 9-11 pause was perfectly honored, or whether every later market-platform statement was correct. The proposition asks a narrower question: by the May 31 deadline, had the parties officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that was general in character rather than merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or a future framework? On this record, the answer should be yes.\n\nThe case-packet evidence gives the governing lens. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d, states that an official ceasefire agreement qualifies if it is publicly announced and mutually agreed, and that a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement had been reached can suffice. It excludes informal arrangements, humanitarian pauses, energy- or Black Sea-only deals, and future frameworks without an explicit dated commitment to stop fighting. That definition matters because the proof here points to a dated May 9-May 11 ceasefire, not simply aspirational peace talks.\n\nThe strongest plaintiff proof in the existing packet is the convergence between official-source material and credible reporting. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, identifies a Kremlin source in which Yury Ushakov, speaking on instructions from President Putin, confirmed Russia’s acceptance of the U.S.-proposed ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and located the key agreement in the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. The same file records that Ukrainian-side confirmation is currently captured through Ukrinform because direct access to the Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in the packet environment. That creates a provenance gap we should fill later, but it is not a contradiction.\n\nThe secondary-reporting record, ev_cf0c77f2fe52, then supplies the market rule’s alternative path: multiple credible outlets and ISW are summarized as reporting that Russia and Ukraine confirmed or agreed to a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11, with suspension of kinetic activity and an associated 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, preserves the same source map and correctly warns that platform assertions are not independent proof. I accept that warning. Our case rests on the official and reporting source chain, not on the market’s final Yes label.\n\nThe defense will have real points to test. The Russian official framing connects the pause to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform appears narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, candidly identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s social-media confirmation, the Ukrainian presidential page, Trump’s announcement, and battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused generally. It also notes alleged violations and continuing hostilities around the period. Those issues affect weight and may affect how the council evaluates scope and implementation.\n\nBut those gaps do not change the core theory. A qualifying agreement can be temporary. It can be attached to a prisoner exchange. It can be violated after it is reached. The decisive question is whether the parties publicly and officially agreed to halt military engagement generally for a dated period, not whether the ceasefire became a lasting peace or achieved perfect compliance. The packet’s plaintiff-side evidence already points to both sides confirming a three-day suspension of kinetic activity, while the defense evidence mainly argues motive, context, and performance.\n\nIn the next evidence phase, the plaintiff should admit the strongest underlying sources: the Kremlin page, the best accessible Ukrainian official or official-adjacent confirmation, direct presidential or U.S. announcement records if obtainable, and implementation/violation assessments from ISW or similar monitors. Those materials will let the council separate three questions: agreement reached, scope of the agreed halt, and compliance in the field. For opening purposes, the record supports the plaintiff’s framing: this was not merely an informal understanding or a future framework, but an officially announced, mutually confirmed, dated ceasefire agreement broad enough to satisfy the proposition by a preponderance of the evidence.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the thing this market asked for, not a nearby diplomatic event. The proposition requires an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict by May 31, 2026. It expressly excludes humanitarian pauses, limited arrangements, and future or partial frameworks.\n\nThe current packet does not yet carry that burden. It contains useful leads, but the strongest record materials point to a narrower event: a brief May 9-May 11 arrangement tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and a prisoner exchange. The market-page file, ev_f841be6ff80d, gives the rule and its exclusions, but it also warns that page-context assertions are platform assertions, not independent proof. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, repeats that caution: platform language cannot itself establish official mutuality, theatre-wide scope, implementation, or reliable consensus.\n\nThe official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, is where the burden problem becomes concrete. The Russian official text is not framed as a general pause in the conflict; it confirms Russia’s acceptance of a U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange, with the key agreement being a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during the May 9-May 11 period. On the Ukrainian side, the packet does not preserve a direct official presidential page; direct access reportedly returned 403. The available official-adjacent capture is Ukrinform’s report about a presidential decree that appears limited to allowing the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding Red Square from Ukrainian targeting during the parade. That is a substantial provenance and scope gap.\n\nThe plaintiff will rely on ev_cf0c77f2fe52, which summarizes credible reporting that both sides confirmed a three-day ceasefire. We do not ignore that. Secondary reporting may help find the underlying record and may later corroborate a mutual announcement. But at opening, those reports sit beside the packet’s own defense leads: Victory Day timing, Red Square security, prisoner-exchange purpose, allegations of violations, and ongoing retaliatory activity around the period. Those facts matter because the market did not ask whether some pause, some prisoner-exchange deconfliction, or some symbolic holiday arrangement occurred. It asked whether the parties had reached a general pause in military engagement.\n\nNor is this merely a compliance argument. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been agreed. But if the evidence shows the arrangement was designed and announced around a prisoner swap and parade security, and if fighting materially continued, that bears on whether the agreement was general in character at all. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, identifies the missing proof the council should want before finding for plaintiff: direct Zelenskyy confirmation, the direct Ukrainian presidential decree, direct Trump or White House announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence of whether hostilities generally paused, and complete official post-period violation statements.\n\nIn the evidence phase, the defense will test exactly those links: the full Kremlin text, the inaccessible Ukrainian decree or an authenticated archive, any direct Ukrainian presidential social-media confirmation, the U.S. announcement, ISW and other monitoring assessments, and post-period official violation statements. If those sources show a mutual, official, theatre-wide halt, plaintiff may have a case. If they show a short Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement amid continuing hostilities, the proposition fails.\n\nFor now, the packet supports caution, not a finding. Plaintiff’s opening treats a temporary three-day ceasefire label as enough. The market language demands more: a general pause in the conflict. On this record, the decisive proof is missing or points narrower, and the council should hold plaintiff to that burden.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the missing bridge the defense asked for. The record no longer rests only on the case packet. The admitted source captures show a public, mutual, dated ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine before the May 31 deadline, and the language used was broad enough to constitute a general halt in military engagement.\n\nStart with the governing rule. PX-1, the market-page record, requires an official ceasefire agreement: a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement. It excludes informal, humanitarian-only, energy-only, Black Sea-only, or future-framework arrangements. It also allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. That is exactly what the merits evidence now shows.\n\nPX-3, the Guardian May 8 capture, reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11. Its key points track the rule: Trump announced a ceasefire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine”; the ceasefire included suspension of all “kinetic activity”; and it was “confirmed by both sides.” The same capture records Ukrainian confirmation by Zelenskyy and Russian confirmation by Kremlin adviser Yury Ushakov. This is not a future framework. It is a dated ceasefire, announced before the deadline, with both parties identified.\n\nPX-4 directly answers the defense’s Ukrainian-source objection. Ukrainska Pravda, sourcing Zelenskyy on X, reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Trump’s truce with Russia for May 9-11 and quoted him saying Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement to conduct the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. That is Ukrainian-side public confirmation of Russia’s agreement and of the ceasefire regime. It is not merely a Red Square decree.\n\nPX-5 adds the U.S. announcement and the mutual-confirmation frame. RFE/RL reports Trump’s announcement of a three-day cease-fire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine,” including “suspension of all Kinetic activity,” and says both sides quickly confirmed the truce and prisoner swap. It also reports that Putin aide Yury Ushakov said Russia agreed to the three-day cease-fire and prisoner exchange. PX-2, the case-packet official-source record, independently preserves the Kremlin source path and confirms the Russian official framing.\n\nThe defense’s best point is context: Victory Day, Red Square, and prisoner exchange. But context is not the same as limitation. A ceasefire can have an occasion and still be general in scope. A prisoner exchange can be conducted during a general ceasefire; it does not convert the ceasefire into a humanitarian-only pause when the announced term is suspension of all kinetic activity in the war between the two states. Likewise, the Red Square decree may be narrow by itself, but PX-4 and PX-5 show broader Ukrainian confirmation alongside that narrow parade-security action.\n\nThe defense also points to violations and continued activity. That matters for compliance, not formation. The proposition asks whether the parties had officially reached the public mutual halt by May 31. It does not require that no shot was later fired. PX-5 candidly includes adverse context: reports of earlier violations, strikes, and retaliatory claims around the period. Those facts show why compliance was contested, but they do not erase the public mutual agreement reported and confirmed on May 8.\n\nProvenance and custody: the five case-packet files are juror-visible case-packet evidence. PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5 were submitted in this merits phase as text captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and descriptions; AAR accepted each and assigned evidence IDs. Direct X pages and some official pages were hard to capture in this environment, but the accepted evidence faithfully preserves the relevant source-chain content and is corroborated across independent outlets and the existing official-source packet.\n\nOn a preponderance standard, plaintiff need not prove a lasting peace or flawless battlefield silence. The better reading of the admitted evidence is that by May 8, before the May 31 deadline, Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire in the war, including suspension of kinetic activity. That satisfies the proposition.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has improved the record, but not enough to satisfy the proposition. The record now supports that a three-day truce was publicly discussed and confirmed around May 8. The remaining question is whether that truce constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange arrangement. On this record, the better answer remains no.\n\nStart with the rule. DX-1, the market-page record, requires more than any official ceasefire label. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited agreements and requires a general pause in the conflict. That scope requirement does real work here.\n\nPlaintiff’s own proof shows why. PX-4 says Zelenskyy framed the arrangement this way: within U.S.-mediated negotiations, Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and a ceasefire regime “must also be established” on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 likewise ties Trump’s announcement to a prisoner swap and reports Zelenskyy ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the Victory Day parade. DX-2, the official-source packet, is even narrower on the Russian side: Ushakov confirmed Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and the packet’s Ukrainian official-adjacent decree record is limited to Red Square/parade targeting. Those are not side details. They are the public shape of the deal.\n\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat “suspension of all kinetic activity” as dispositive. But the source chain remains mostly media-captured, with direct X, Truth Social, and official Ukrainian decree captures still missing. More importantly, an announced aspiration to suspend kinetic activity does not resolve whether the parties actually reached a general conflict pause, as opposed to a brief operational deconfliction attached to POW exchange and parade security. The burden is plaintiff’s, and ambiguity on scope counts against them.\n\nThe implementation evidence confirms that ambiguity. DX-4, the NV/ISW capture, reports Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It says intensity decreased but did not stop, Ukraine reported 51 combat engagements, Russian forces continued strikes in Kharkiv and Kherson Oblasts, and Russia claimed thousands of Ukrainian violations. It also reports ISW’s assessment that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions and that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square, which Kyiv upheld. That is powerful evidence that the practical, defined commitment was narrow.\n\nDX-5, CBS/AP’s May 10 report, shows the same pattern during the supposed pause. Both sides accused each other of breaking the ceasefire; Zelenskyy said Russia was not observing the truce and that there was no calm in frontline areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks; Russia accused Ukraine of more than 1,000 violations and said it responded in kind. CBS/AP also noted the three-day pause’s timeline was somewhat unclear. This is not offered to impose a perfect-compliance requirement. It is offered because widespread continued operations, undefined conditions, and mutual “response in kind” claims are probative of what kind of arrangement was actually reached.\n\nPlaintiff’s best legal point is that an agreement can be violated and still be an agreement. Correct. But the proposition is not “was there an agreement called a ceasefire?” It asks whether there was a general pause in military engagement. Formation and scope are intertwined: if the only clearly defined official condition was Red Square non-targeting, if Russia’s official acceptance described a prisoner-exchange purpose, if the exchange did not even occur as the announced 1,000-for-1,000 event during the truce period on this record, and if operations continued across the theater, then plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause by a preponderance.\n\nProvenance matters too. Plaintiff’s new exhibits are accepted text captures from reputable outlets, but they remain secondary captures of hard-to-access primary statements. The case-packet itself, DX-3, flags the same gaps: missing direct Zelenskyy social-media confirmation, missing direct Ukrainian presidential decree, missing direct Trump/White House record, and missing battlefield/monitoring evidence. Defendant filled part of that last gap with DX-4 and DX-5, and the result undercuts plaintiff’s scope theory.\n\nSearch and capture ledger: I checked targeted May 9-11 ceasefire-violation and ISW queries after reading plaintiff’s exhibits. ISW May 9-11 assessments appeared as the strongest implementation target; accessible captures were preserved through NV’s ISW summary and CBS/AP’s contemporaneous violation report. A Guardian May 9 Red Square/frontline article was opened but not submitted because DX-4 and DX-5 more directly address implementation and scope.\n\nThe council can find that a short truce was announced. It should not find that plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition. The admitted evidence shows a fragile, underdefined, prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with continued frontline operations, not a publicly agreed general pause in the Russia-Ukraine conflict.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s new evidence proves the wrong point. DX-4 and DX-5 are evidence of poor compliance, weak monitoring, and violation accusations. They are not evidence that the May 8 agreement was merely Red Square-only or that no official public mutual ceasefire agreement was reached.\n\nThat distinction matters because the proposition and PX-1 focus on whether the parties had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt by May 31. The market rule even says a qualifying agreement can resolve Yes if officially reached before the resolution date regardless of later start mechanics. Defendant’s evidence is mostly about what happened after the agreement was announced.\n\nDX-4, the NV/ISW capture, says fighting intensity decreased but did not stop completely. It reports continued operations and weak ceasefire mechanisms. But it also states President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 exchange. DX-5, the CBS/AP capture, likewise reports accusations of violations, but it also states Trump announced Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire and that both sides appeared to agree. These are concessions on formation.\n\nThe defense tries to turn noncompliance into narrow scope. That does not follow. A general ceasefire with poor monitoring can be violated. A general ceasefire can be attached to a prisoner exchange. A general ceasefire can coincide with Victory Day. None of those facts converts broad language like “ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine” and “suspension of all kinetic activity” into a Red Square-only arrangement.\n\nThe best scope evidence remains PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5. PX-3 says both sides confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire and suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-4 gives the Ukrainian-side confirmation: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement and a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 gives the U.S. announcement and both-side confirmation: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides.\n\nThe Red Square material is narrower, but it is not the whole agreement. It is an additional operational commitment about parade targeting. The prisoner exchange is likewise not disqualifying. The market excludes humanitarian pauses, but this record does not show a prisoner-exchange-only corridor or a local evacuation window. It shows a ceasefire in the war, with all kinetic activity suspended, plus a prisoner swap during that pause.\n\nDefendant also leans on missing primary captures. Those gaps affect weight, and plaintiff disclosed them. But the rule expressly permits wide credible media consensus, and the accepted captures are mutually reinforcing: Guardian, Ukrainska Pravda, RFE/RL, and the case-packet official-source record all converge on public mutual confirmation. Defendant’s own exhibits do not break that chain; they accept the announcement and agreement, then dispute implementation.\n\nSo the actual evidentiary balance is this: plaintiff has multiple accepted sources proving official public mutual agreement to a dated ceasefire with broad kinetic-activity language. Defendant has sources proving the ceasefire was fragile and violated. Under a preponderance standard, the former satisfies the proposition; the latter does not rewrite it.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal is right about one thing but draws the wrong conclusion. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been reached. If the record showed a clearly defined general pause followed by isolated breaches, defendant would lose that point.\n\nBut DX-4 and DX-5 are not just breach evidence. They are scope and character evidence. DX-4 reports that, on the first day of the supposed May 9-11 general pause, Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline; combat declined but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and ISW assessed that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most importantly, DX-4 says the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade. That does not look like a defined, general halt in military engagement. It looks like a fragile holiday/prisoner-exchange deconfliction with one concrete parade-security condition.\n\nDX-5 is similar. Plaintiff stresses that CBS/AP says both sides appeared to agree. But the same exhibit says the timeline was somewhat unclear, both sides accused each other of breaking the truce, Zelenskyy said there was no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and Russia claimed it responded in kind. Again, defendant is not saying every violation voids formation. Defendant is saying the record as a whole does not show the qualifying thing: a general pause in the conflict.\n\nThat distinction is why plaintiff’s “formation not compliance” framing is too narrow. The proposition contains a scope element. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. The official-source packet says Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange. Plaintiff’s Ukrainian-side evidence likewise puts the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange at the center, and the direct Ukrainian decree remains missing while the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square-specific. Plaintiff’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase is powerful, but it is mostly preserved through media captures, not through the unavailable primary posts, and it must be weighed against the operational evidence that no defined general pause actually existed.\n\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat announcement language as enough and implementation as irrelevant. The market does not permit that shortcut. It asks whether the parties reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. Where the public official detail is prisoner exchange and Red Square, the conditions are undefined, and fighting continued across the theater from the first day, plaintiff has not carried that stricter burden by a preponderance.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record resolves this case on a preponderance standard.\n\nThe proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It does not ask whether the war ended, whether the ceasefire was durable, or whether neither side later accused the other of violations.\n\nThe decisive record is straightforward. PX-1 defines the qualifying event as an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and permits a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. PX-3 reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, that Trump announced it as a ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, that it included suspension of all kinetic activity, and that it was confirmed by both sides. PX-4 supplies Ukrainian-side confirmation: Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 truce with Russia, said Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement, and said a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 supplies the U.S. announcement and the same mutual-confirmation frame: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides, including Russian agreement through Ushakov. PX-2 independently preserves the Russian official-source path.\n\nThat evidence satisfies the elements: official/public, mutual, dated before the deadline, and general in the only sense the market required: a halt in military engagement in the war, not a sector-only Black Sea or energy arrangement, not a mere informal understanding, and not a future framework.\n\nThe defense’s contrary evidence is important, but it points mainly to performance. DX-4 and DX-5 show continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. We should not ignore that. But both exhibits also preserve the formation facts: Trump announced the ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. A breached ceasefire is still a ceasefire agreement. The proposition turns on whether the agreement was reached, not whether it was perfectly obeyed.\n\nThe defense says the prisoner exchange and Victory Day context make the pause non-general. The better reading is that they explain why the parties accepted a temporary general pause. A prisoner exchange can occur during a broad ceasefire; it does not make the ceasefire humanitarian-only when the announced scope is suspension of all kinetic activity. Red Square non-targeting was an additional concrete operational condition, not the whole agreement. The record contains separate broader language: ceasefire in the war, ceasefire regime on May 9-11, suspension of kinetic activity, and both sides confirmed.\n\nThere are source-chain gaps: direct X, Truth Social, and some official pages were hard to capture. But the market rule expressly allows credible media consensus, and here the accepted sources converge with the case-packet official-source record. The defense’s own evidence does not break that convergence; it disputes execution.\n\nOn balance, plaintiff’s evidence proves more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed May 9-11 halt in military engagement before May 31. The council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, this case is not about whether something happened on May 8. Something did. The record supports that a short May 9-11 truce was announced and that both sides were reported as accepting it. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition: an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause, limited arrangement, or future framework.\n\nPlaintiff has not carried that burden.\n\nStart with the governing rule. The market-page record requires a general pause and excludes humanitarian and limited agreements. That means the council cannot stop at the word “ceasefire” or at the fact of a public announcement. It must ask what kind of ceasefire the record proves.\n\nThe official-source packet supplies the best answer. Russia’s official source, through Ushakov, accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.” The key agreement described there was a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during May 9-11. On the Ukrainian official side, the direct presidential decree was not captured; the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square and parade-specific. Those facts do not prove a theatre-wide general pause. They prove a prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with a concrete parade-security component.\n\nPlaintiff’s own merits exhibits do not eliminate that limitation. PX-4 quotes Zelenskyy in the context of the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and says a ceasefire regime must also be established. PX-5 reports the Trump announcement but also says Zelenskyy ordered no attack on Red Square and preserves the same prisoner-swap frame. Yes, those sources use broad language such as “suspension of all kinetic activity.” But broad media language must be weighed against the actual official-source detail, the missing primary captures, and what the parties did when the supposed general pause began.\n\nThat implementation evidence is decisive because it goes to character and scope, not merely breach. DX-4 reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day; combat intensity decreased but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most tellingly, DX-4 reports that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square. DX-5 reports no calm in front line areas, mutual violation accusations, an unclear timeline, and Russian “response in kind.”\n\nPlaintiff says violations are only compliance. If this were a clearly defined general ceasefire followed by isolated breaches, that would be right. But the record shows something different: undefined conditions, the one clearly public operational term being Red Square, a prisoner-exchange purpose, and continued operations across the theater from day one. That is evidence that the arrangement never rose to the general pause required by the proposition.\n\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce caution. Direct X or Telegram, direct Truth Social or White House, and the direct Ukrainian decree remain absent. The rule allows credible media consensus, but consensus reporting does not override ambiguity in the official-source record and battlefield evidence. At most, plaintiff proved a fragile, short, U.S.-brokered truce label attached to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The market required more.\n\nOn a preponderance standard, if the evidence is equally consistent with a limited prisoner-exchange/parade-security pause and a qualifying general pause, plaintiff loses. Here the limiting evidence is stronger than equal. The council should find the proposition not proven.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and resolution criteria\n# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Official-source case-packet record\n# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Guardian both-sides confirmation report\nSource: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Ukrainian-side Zelensky confirmation report\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 RFE/RL Trump announcement and both-sides confirmation\nSource: RFE/RL, \"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \"suspension of all Kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \"cease-fire regime must also be established,\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\n\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule requiring general pause and excluding limited/humanitarian pauses\n# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-2 Official-source packet: Russian prisoner-exchange framing and narrow Ukrainian decree capture\n# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-3 Unresolved record gaps and known tension on scope/violations\n# Unresolved record gaps\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\n\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\n\nKnown record tension:\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \"general pause\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-4 NV/ISW: continued offensive operations and undefined ceasefire conditions\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\n\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\n\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n[defendant] DX-5 CBS/AP: mutual violation accusations and no calm on front lines\nSource: CBS News/AP, \"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\n\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \"even particularly trying to,\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\n\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\n\n[defendant] PX-4/DX-6 Zelenskyy report tying ceasefire regime to prisoner exchange\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\n\n[defendant] PX-5/DX-7 RFE/RL report with Red Square and adverse violation context\nSource: RFE/RL, \"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \"suspension of all Kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \"cease-fire regime must also be established,\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Guardian broad ceasefire confirmation\nSource: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Zelenskyy confirmation of ceasefire regime\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 RFE/RL both-side confirmation and adverse context\nSource: RFE/RL, \"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \"suspension of all Kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \"cease-fire regime must also be established,\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R4 Defendant NV/ISW exhibit showing compliance dispute, not no agreement\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\n\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\n\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R5 Defendant CBS/AP exhibit showing both sides appeared to agree\nSource: CBS News/AP, \"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\n\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \"even particularly trying to,\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\n\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 NV/ISW: continued operations and unclear conditions as scope evidence\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\n\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\n\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 CBS/AP: mutual violations, unclear timeline, no calm on front line\nSource: CBS News/AP, \"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\n\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \"even particularly trying to,\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\n\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\n\n[defendant] DX-S3 Official-source packet: prisoner-exchange and Red Square framing\n# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-S4 Market rule requiring a general pause, not limited/humanitarian arrangements\n# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 8 2026 report: Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire (ev_236dce43c3d8_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-236dce43c3d8)\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\nSHA-256: `236dce43c3d8f0a768feb3c9aa5e4214f9afb219b3cc647e8679b1179e916c6c`\nBytes: 1583\nRelevance: Credible media report that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, suspension of kinetic activity, and prisoner swap; directly addresses public mutual agreement and scope.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026: Zelenskyy confirms truce with Russia on May 9-11 (ev_2c8cd49d9b00_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-2c8cd49d9b00)\nSource: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033888/\nSHA-256: `2c8cd49d9b0040da3a58b04496b028fae6de5fb2b66b02d1f9b68b7bb84bbcac`\nBytes: 1248\nRelevance: Ukrainian media report based on Zelenskyy on X/Twitter confirming Russia's agreement and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11; addresses Ukrainian-side public confirmation.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] RFE/RL May 8 2026: Trump announces three-day cease-fire; both sides confirm (ev_5d2cebff6f4b_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2cebff6f4b)\nSource: https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-russia-victory-day-cease-fire-drone-attacks/33752482.html\nSHA-256: `5d2cebff6f4b0f521cbfa77b06da6f8548e1352caa5fc5983a21cf59c675b46a`\nBytes: 1405\nRelevance: Report preserving Trump announcement, confirmation by both sides, suspension of kinetic activity, prisoner swap, and adverse context of earlier violations; addresses official public agreement and scope/compliance distinction.\n\n[defendant arguments] NV May 10 2026 report on ISW assessment: fighting continued during first day of ceasefire (ev_52a3277a9302_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-52a3277a9302)\nSource: https://english.nv.ua/russian-war/isw-says-fighting-continued-despite-may-9-11-ceasefire-50606640.html\nSHA-256: `52a3277a93024fbf92cdd1f34c2ebf0ee4a62600c40ffa7809cd520718baba32`\nBytes: 1823\nRelevance: Shows adverse implementation and scope evidence: offensive operations continued across the frontline, combat declined but did not stop, ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, only known condition was Red Square non-targeting, and Russian forces allegedly used the period to reinforce positions.\n\n[defendant arguments] CBS/AP May 10 2026: Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating ceasefire (ev_d5ef4e09892f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-d5ef4e09892f)\nSource: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/russia-ukraine-accuse-each-other-ceasefire-violations/\nSHA-256: `d5ef4e09892f541e4806e0e6d705f5472ab9890cf4567bf47bf3a56b73f03dd8`\nBytes: 1606\nRelevance: Shows contemporaneous post-agreement evidence that both sides accused each other of violations, Zelenskyy said there was no calm on front lines despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and the ceasefire timing was unclear; bears on whether the arrangement was a general pause rather than fragile/limited truce.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and capture ledger\nPlaintiff searched official and source-specific paths for the May 8-11 ceasefire record. Successful captures submitted as evidence: Guardian May 8 report, Ukrainska Pravda May 8 Zelenskyy confirmation report, and RFE/RL May 8 Trump/both-sides confirmation report. Existing case-packet evidence supplies market criteria and a Kremlin official-source summary. Capture limits: direct X pages for Zelenskyy and WhiteHouse rendered no text in web open; PBS returned 403; Ukrinform opened without readable lines; ISW May 8/May 11 direct pages returned 403; earlier curl to the Kremlin page timed out. These failures leave some primary-source gaps, but the accepted captures preserve the material source-chain content and include adverse context on alleged violations.\n\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\nAt merits, defendant inspected the new plaintiff evidence and searched targeted terms for May 9-11 ceasefire scope, violations, and ISW assessments. Source targets included ISW May 9-11 assessments, accessible media captures of those assessments, and contemporaneous violation reports. Defendant submitted accepted captures from NV/ISW and CBS/AP. Direct primary social/official sources remain incompletely captured in the record, including direct Zelenskyy X/Telegram, Trump Truth Social/White House, and president.gov.ua decree text; those gaps affect weight because plaintiff relies heavily on secondary captures for scope.\n\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff rebuttal evidence audit\nPlaintiff inspected the two new defendant exhibits by stat/read_evidence_range. Both primarily address implementation: continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. Both also preserve or concede agreement facts: Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. No additional outside source was needed for this targeted rebuttal.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T03:06:22.654219585Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C5","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C5","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":887016,"role_id":"council","turn_number":13},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":18,"version":29}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782787895642}}
{"type":"turn_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is giving me instructions to act as a council member for an AAR (Automated Arbitration Resolution) case. Let me break down what I need to do:\n\n1. Use the Pi MCP proxy tool named `mcp` to call AAR tools\n2. The tools are prefixed with `aar_` \n3. First, I need to call `mcp` with `{\"tool\":\"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\"args\":\"{}\"}`\n4. If it returns `state: waiting`, I need to call it again with the returned `after_version`\n5. If it returns `state: ready`, I need to read the returned information (prompt, turn, limits, remaining time, attempts remaining, opportunity id)\n6. Review the visible arbitration record and admitted evidence using appropriate tools\n7. When ready, submit my vote using `aar_submit_council_vote`\n8. Stop after receiving `ok: true`\n\nLet me start by calling the wait_for_opportunity tool.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"functions.mcp:0","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_wait_for_opportunity","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"moonshotai/kimi-k2-thinking","usage":{"input":2081,"output":229,"cacheRead":63,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":2373,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782787891239,"responseId":"gen-1782787891-jXDUEIVHypYOQRSqsZaN","responseModel":"moonshotai/kimi-k2-thinking-20251106"},"toolResults":[{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"functions.mcp:0","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 29\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630022841\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nremaining_ms: 887016\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"after_version\":29,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630022841\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C5\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the dispute is not whether the May 2026 Russia-Ukraine war ended, whether the May 9-11 pause was perfectly honored, or whether every later market-platform statement was correct. The proposition asks a narrower question: by the May 31 deadline, had the parties officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that was general in character rather than merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or a future framework? On this record, the answer should be yes.\\n\\nThe case-packet evidence gives the governing lens. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d, states that an official ceasefire agreement qualifies if it is publicly announced and mutually agreed, and that a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement had been reached can suffice. It excludes informal arrangements, humanitarian pauses, energy- or Black Sea-only deals, and future frameworks without an explicit dated commitment to stop fighting. That definition matters because the proof here points to a dated May 9-May 11 ceasefire, not simply aspirational peace talks.\\n\\nThe strongest plaintiff proof in the existing packet is the convergence between official-source material and credible reporting. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, identifies a Kremlin source in which Yury Ushakov, speaking on instructions from President Putin, confirmed Russia’s acceptance of the U.S.-proposed ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and located the key agreement in the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. The same file records that Ukrainian-side confirmation is currently captured through Ukrinform because direct access to the Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in the packet environment. That creates a provenance gap we should fill later, but it is not a contradiction.\\n\\nThe secondary-reporting record, ev_cf0c77f2fe52, then supplies the market rule’s alternative path: multiple credible outlets and ISW are summarized as reporting that Russia and Ukraine confirmed or agreed to a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11, with suspension of kinetic activity and an associated 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, preserves the same source map and correctly warns that platform assertions are not independent proof. I accept that warning. Our case rests on the official and reporting source chain, not on the market’s final Yes label.\\n\\nThe defense will have real points to test. The Russian official framing connects the pause to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform appears narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, candidly identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s social-media confirmation, the Ukrainian presidential page, Trump’s announcement, and battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused generally. It also notes alleged violations and continuing hostilities around the period. Those issues affect weight and may affect how the council evaluates scope and implementation.\\n\\nBut those gaps do not change the core theory. A qualifying agreement can be temporary. It can be attached to a prisoner exchange. It can be violated after it is reached. The decisive question is whether the parties publicly and officially agreed to halt military engagement generally for a dated period, not whether the ceasefire became a lasting peace or achieved perfect compliance. The packet’s plaintiff-side evidence already points to both sides confirming a three-day suspension of kinetic activity, while the defense evidence mainly argues motive, context, and performance.\\n\\nIn the next evidence phase, the plaintiff should admit the strongest underlying sources: the Kremlin page, the best accessible Ukrainian official or official-adjacent confirmation, direct presidential or U.S. announcement records if obtainable, and implementation/violation assessments from ISW or similar monitors. Those materials will let the council separate three questions: agreement reached, scope of the agreed halt, and compliance in the field. For opening purposes, the record supports the plaintiff’s framing: this was not merely an informal understanding or a future framework, but an officially announced, mutually confirmed, dated ceasefire agreement broad enough to satisfy the proposition by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the thing this market asked for, not a nearby diplomatic event. The proposition requires an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict by May 31, 2026. It expressly excludes humanitarian pauses, limited arrangements, and future or partial frameworks.\\n\\nThe current packet does not yet carry that burden. It contains useful leads, but the strongest record materials point to a narrower event: a brief May 9-May 11 arrangement tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and a prisoner exchange. The market-page file, ev_f841be6ff80d, gives the rule and its exclusions, but it also warns that page-context assertions are platform assertions, not independent proof. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, repeats that caution: platform language cannot itself establish official mutuality, theatre-wide scope, implementation, or reliable consensus.\\n\\nThe official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, is where the burden problem becomes concrete. The Russian official text is not framed as a general pause in the conflict; it confirms Russia’s acceptance of a U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange, with the key agreement being a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during the May 9-May 11 period. On the Ukrainian side, the packet does not preserve a direct official presidential page; direct access reportedly returned 403. The available official-adjacent capture is Ukrinform’s report about a presidential decree that appears limited to allowing the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding Red Square from Ukrainian targeting during the parade. That is a substantial provenance and scope gap.\\n\\nThe plaintiff will rely on ev_cf0c77f2fe52, which summarizes credible reporting that both sides confirmed a three-day ceasefire. We do not ignore that. Secondary reporting may help find the underlying record and may later corroborate a mutual announcement. But at opening, those reports sit beside the packet’s own defense leads: Victory Day timing, Red Square security, prisoner-exchange purpose, allegations of violations, and ongoing retaliatory activity around the period. Those facts matter because the market did not ask whether some pause, some prisoner-exchange deconfliction, or some symbolic holiday arrangement occurred. It asked whether the parties had reached a general pause in military engagement.\\n\\nNor is this merely a compliance argument. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been agreed. But if the evidence shows the arrangement was designed and announced around a prisoner swap and parade security, and if fighting materially continued, that bears on whether the agreement was general in character at all. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, identifies the missing proof the council should want before finding for plaintiff: direct Zelenskyy confirmation, the direct Ukrainian presidential decree, direct Trump or White House announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence of whether hostilities generally paused, and complete official post-period violation statements.\\n\\nIn the evidence phase, the defense will test exactly those links: the full Kremlin text, the inaccessible Ukrainian decree or an authenticated archive, any direct Ukrainian presidential social-media confirmation, the U.S. announcement, ISW and other monitoring assessments, and post-period official violation statements. If those sources show a mutual, official, theatre-wide halt, plaintiff may have a case. If they show a short Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement amid continuing hostilities, the proposition fails.\\n\\nFor now, the packet supports caution, not a finding. Plaintiff’s opening treats a temporary three-day ceasefire label as enough. The market language demands more: a general pause in the conflict. On this record, the decisive proof is missing or points narrower, and the council should hold plaintiff to that burden.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the missing bridge the defense asked for. The record no longer rests only on the case packet. The admitted source captures show a public, mutual, dated ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine before the May 31 deadline, and the language used was broad enough to constitute a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. PX-1, the market-page record, requires an official ceasefire agreement: a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement. It excludes informal, humanitarian-only, energy-only, Black Sea-only, or future-framework arrangements. It also allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. That is exactly what the merits evidence now shows.\\n\\nPX-3, the Guardian May 8 capture, reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11. Its key points track the rule: Trump announced a ceasefire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine”; the ceasefire included suspension of all “kinetic activity”; and it was “confirmed by both sides.” The same capture records Ukrainian confirmation by Zelenskyy and Russian confirmation by Kremlin adviser Yury Ushakov. This is not a future framework. It is a dated ceasefire, announced before the deadline, with both parties identified.\\n\\nPX-4 directly answers the defense’s Ukrainian-source objection. Ukrainska Pravda, sourcing Zelenskyy on X, reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Trump’s truce with Russia for May 9-11 and quoted him saying Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement to conduct the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. That is Ukrainian-side public confirmation of Russia’s agreement and of the ceasefire regime. It is not merely a Red Square decree.\\n\\nPX-5 adds the U.S. announcement and the mutual-confirmation frame. RFE/RL reports Trump’s announcement of a three-day cease-fire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine,” including “suspension of all Kinetic activity,” and says both sides quickly confirmed the truce and prisoner swap. It also reports that Putin aide Yury Ushakov said Russia agreed to the three-day cease-fire and prisoner exchange. PX-2, the case-packet official-source record, independently preserves the Kremlin source path and confirms the Russian official framing.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is context: Victory Day, Red Square, and prisoner exchange. But context is not the same as limitation. A ceasefire can have an occasion and still be general in scope. A prisoner exchange can be conducted during a general ceasefire; it does not convert the ceasefire into a humanitarian-only pause when the announced term is suspension of all kinetic activity in the war between the two states. Likewise, the Red Square decree may be narrow by itself, but PX-4 and PX-5 show broader Ukrainian confirmation alongside that narrow parade-security action.\\n\\nThe defense also points to violations and continued activity. That matters for compliance, not formation. The proposition asks whether the parties had officially reached the public mutual halt by May 31. It does not require that no shot was later fired. PX-5 candidly includes adverse context: reports of earlier violations, strikes, and retaliatory claims around the period. Those facts show why compliance was contested, but they do not erase the public mutual agreement reported and confirmed on May 8.\\n\\nProvenance and custody: the five case-packet files are juror-visible case-packet evidence. PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5 were submitted in this merits phase as text captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and descriptions; AAR accepted each and assigned evidence IDs. Direct X pages and some official pages were hard to capture in this environment, but the accepted evidence faithfully preserves the relevant source-chain content and is corroborated across independent outlets and the existing official-source packet.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, plaintiff need not prove a lasting peace or flawless battlefield silence. The better reading of the admitted evidence is that by May 8, before the May 31 deadline, Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire in the war, including suspension of kinetic activity. That satisfies the proposition.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has improved the record, but not enough to satisfy the proposition. The record now supports that a three-day truce was publicly discussed and confirmed around May 8. The remaining question is whether that truce constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange arrangement. On this record, the better answer remains no.\\n\\nStart with the rule. DX-1, the market-page record, requires more than any official ceasefire label. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited agreements and requires a general pause in the conflict. That scope requirement does real work here.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own proof shows why. PX-4 says Zelenskyy framed the arrangement this way: within U.S.-mediated negotiations, Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and a ceasefire regime “must also be established” on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 likewise ties Trump’s announcement to a prisoner swap and reports Zelenskyy ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the Victory Day parade. DX-2, the official-source packet, is even narrower on the Russian side: Ushakov confirmed Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and the packet’s Ukrainian official-adjacent decree record is limited to Red Square/parade targeting. Those are not side details. They are the public shape of the deal.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat “suspension of all kinetic activity” as dispositive. But the source chain remains mostly media-captured, with direct X, Truth Social, and official Ukrainian decree captures still missing. More importantly, an announced aspiration to suspend kinetic activity does not resolve whether the parties actually reached a general conflict pause, as opposed to a brief operational deconfliction attached to POW exchange and parade security. The burden is plaintiff’s, and ambiguity on scope counts against them.\\n\\nThe implementation evidence confirms that ambiguity. DX-4, the NV/ISW capture, reports Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It says intensity decreased but did not stop, Ukraine reported 51 combat engagements, Russian forces continued strikes in Kharkiv and Kherson Oblasts, and Russia claimed thousands of Ukrainian violations. It also reports ISW’s assessment that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions and that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square, which Kyiv upheld. That is powerful evidence that the practical, defined commitment was narrow.\\n\\nDX-5, CBS/AP’s May 10 report, shows the same pattern during the supposed pause. Both sides accused each other of breaking the ceasefire; Zelenskyy said Russia was not observing the truce and that there was no calm in frontline areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks; Russia accused Ukraine of more than 1,000 violations and said it responded in kind. CBS/AP also noted the three-day pause’s timeline was somewhat unclear. This is not offered to impose a perfect-compliance requirement. It is offered because widespread continued operations, undefined conditions, and mutual “response in kind” claims are probative of what kind of arrangement was actually reached.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s best legal point is that an agreement can be violated and still be an agreement. Correct. But the proposition is not “was there an agreement called a ceasefire?” It asks whether there was a general pause in military engagement. Formation and scope are intertwined: if the only clearly defined official condition was Red Square non-targeting, if Russia’s official acceptance described a prisoner-exchange purpose, if the exchange did not even occur as the announced 1,000-for-1,000 event during the truce period on this record, and if operations continued across the theater, then plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause by a preponderance.\\n\\nProvenance matters too. Plaintiff’s new exhibits are accepted text captures from reputable outlets, but they remain secondary captures of hard-to-access primary statements. The case-packet itself, DX-3, flags the same gaps: missing direct Zelenskyy social-media confirmation, missing direct Ukrainian presidential decree, missing direct Trump/White House record, and missing battlefield/monitoring evidence. Defendant filled part of that last gap with DX-4 and DX-5, and the result undercuts plaintiff’s scope theory.\\n\\nSearch and capture ledger: I checked targeted May 9-11 ceasefire-violation and ISW queries after reading plaintiff’s exhibits. ISW May 9-11 assessments appeared as the strongest implementation target; accessible captures were preserved through NV’s ISW summary and CBS/AP’s contemporaneous violation report. A Guardian May 9 Red Square/frontline article was opened but not submitted because DX-4 and DX-5 more directly address implementation and scope.\\n\\nThe council can find that a short truce was announced. It should not find that plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition. The admitted evidence shows a fragile, underdefined, prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with continued frontline operations, not a publicly agreed general pause in the Russia-Ukraine conflict.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s new evidence proves the wrong point. DX-4 and DX-5 are evidence of poor compliance, weak monitoring, and violation accusations. They are not evidence that the May 8 agreement was merely Red Square-only or that no official public mutual ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nThat distinction matters because the proposition and PX-1 focus on whether the parties had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt by May 31. The market rule even says a qualifying agreement can resolve Yes if officially reached before the resolution date regardless of later start mechanics. Defendant’s evidence is mostly about what happened after the agreement was announced.\\n\\nDX-4, the NV/ISW capture, says fighting intensity decreased but did not stop completely. It reports continued operations and weak ceasefire mechanisms. But it also states President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 exchange. DX-5, the CBS/AP capture, likewise reports accusations of violations, but it also states Trump announced Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire and that both sides appeared to agree. These are concessions on formation.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn noncompliance into narrow scope. That does not follow. A general ceasefire with poor monitoring can be violated. A general ceasefire can be attached to a prisoner exchange. A general ceasefire can coincide with Victory Day. None of those facts converts broad language like “ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine” and “suspension of all kinetic activity” into a Red Square-only arrangement.\\n\\nThe best scope evidence remains PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5. PX-3 says both sides confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire and suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-4 gives the Ukrainian-side confirmation: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement and a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 gives the U.S. announcement and both-side confirmation: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides.\\n\\nThe Red Square material is narrower, but it is not the whole agreement. It is an additional operational commitment about parade targeting. The prisoner exchange is likewise not disqualifying. The market excludes humanitarian pauses, but this record does not show a prisoner-exchange-only corridor or a local evacuation window. It shows a ceasefire in the war, with all kinetic activity suspended, plus a prisoner swap during that pause.\\n\\nDefendant also leans on missing primary captures. Those gaps affect weight, and plaintiff disclosed them. But the rule expressly permits wide credible media consensus, and the accepted captures are mutually reinforcing: Guardian, Ukrainska Pravda, RFE/RL, and the case-packet official-source record all converge on public mutual confirmation. Defendant’s own exhibits do not break that chain; they accept the announcement and agreement, then dispute implementation.\\n\\nSo the actual evidentiary balance is this: plaintiff has multiple accepted sources proving official public mutual agreement to a dated ceasefire with broad kinetic-activity language. Defendant has sources proving the ceasefire was fragile and violated. Under a preponderance standard, the former satisfies the proposition; the latter does not rewrite it.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal is right about one thing but draws the wrong conclusion. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been reached. If the record showed a clearly defined general pause followed by isolated breaches, defendant would lose that point.\\n\\nBut DX-4 and DX-5 are not just breach evidence. They are scope and character evidence. DX-4 reports that, on the first day of the supposed May 9-11 general pause, Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline; combat declined but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and ISW assessed that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most importantly, DX-4 says the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade. That does not look like a defined, general halt in military engagement. It looks like a fragile holiday/prisoner-exchange deconfliction with one concrete parade-security condition.\\n\\nDX-5 is similar. Plaintiff stresses that CBS/AP says both sides appeared to agree. But the same exhibit says the timeline was somewhat unclear, both sides accused each other of breaking the truce, Zelenskyy said there was no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and Russia claimed it responded in kind. Again, defendant is not saying every violation voids formation. Defendant is saying the record as a whole does not show the qualifying thing: a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nThat distinction is why plaintiff’s “formation not compliance” framing is too narrow. The proposition contains a scope element. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. The official-source packet says Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange. Plaintiff’s Ukrainian-side evidence likewise puts the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange at the center, and the direct Ukrainian decree remains missing while the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square-specific. Plaintiff’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase is powerful, but it is mostly preserved through media captures, not through the unavailable primary posts, and it must be weighed against the operational evidence that no defined general pause actually existed.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat announcement language as enough and implementation as irrelevant. The market does not permit that shortcut. It asks whether the parties reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. Where the public official detail is prisoner exchange and Red Square, the conditions are undefined, and fighting continued across the theater from the first day, plaintiff has not carried that stricter burden by a preponderance.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record resolves this case on a preponderance standard.\\n\\nThe proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It does not ask whether the war ended, whether the ceasefire was durable, or whether neither side later accused the other of violations.\\n\\nThe decisive record is straightforward. PX-1 defines the qualifying event as an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and permits a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. PX-3 reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, that Trump announced it as a ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, that it included suspension of all kinetic activity, and that it was confirmed by both sides. PX-4 supplies Ukrainian-side confirmation: Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 truce with Russia, said Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement, and said a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 supplies the U.S. announcement and the same mutual-confirmation frame: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides, including Russian agreement through Ushakov. PX-2 independently preserves the Russian official-source path.\\n\\nThat evidence satisfies the elements: official/public, mutual, dated before the deadline, and general in the only sense the market required: a halt in military engagement in the war, not a sector-only Black Sea or energy arrangement, not a mere informal understanding, and not a future framework.\\n\\nThe defense’s contrary evidence is important, but it points mainly to performance. DX-4 and DX-5 show continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. We should not ignore that. But both exhibits also preserve the formation facts: Trump announced the ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. A breached ceasefire is still a ceasefire agreement. The proposition turns on whether the agreement was reached, not whether it was perfectly obeyed.\\n\\nThe defense says the prisoner exchange and Victory Day context make the pause non-general. The better reading is that they explain why the parties accepted a temporary general pause. A prisoner exchange can occur during a broad ceasefire; it does not make the ceasefire humanitarian-only when the announced scope is suspension of all kinetic activity. Red Square non-targeting was an additional concrete operational condition, not the whole agreement. The record contains separate broader language: ceasefire in the war, ceasefire regime on May 9-11, suspension of kinetic activity, and both sides confirmed.\\n\\nThere are source-chain gaps: direct X, Truth Social, and some official pages were hard to capture. But the market rule expressly allows credible media consensus, and here the accepted sources converge with the case-packet official-source record. The defense’s own evidence does not break that convergence; it disputes execution.\\n\\nOn balance, plaintiff’s evidence proves more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed May 9-11 halt in military engagement before May 31. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case is not about whether something happened on May 8. Something did. The record supports that a short May 9-11 truce was announced and that both sides were reported as accepting it. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition: an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause, limited arrangement, or future framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. The market-page record requires a general pause and excludes humanitarian and limited agreements. That means the council cannot stop at the word “ceasefire” or at the fact of a public announcement. It must ask what kind of ceasefire the record proves.\\n\\nThe official-source packet supplies the best answer. Russia’s official source, through Ushakov, accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.” The key agreement described there was a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during May 9-11. On the Ukrainian official side, the direct presidential decree was not captured; the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square and parade-specific. Those facts do not prove a theatre-wide general pause. They prove a prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with a concrete parade-security component.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own merits exhibits do not eliminate that limitation. PX-4 quotes Zelenskyy in the context of the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and says a ceasefire regime must also be established. PX-5 reports the Trump announcement but also says Zelenskyy ordered no attack on Red Square and preserves the same prisoner-swap frame. Yes, those sources use broad language such as “suspension of all kinetic activity.” But broad media language must be weighed against the actual official-source detail, the missing primary captures, and what the parties did when the supposed general pause began.\\n\\nThat implementation evidence is decisive because it goes to character and scope, not merely breach. DX-4 reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day; combat intensity decreased but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most tellingly, DX-4 reports that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square. DX-5 reports no calm in front line areas, mutual violation accusations, an unclear timeline, and Russian “response in kind.”\\n\\nPlaintiff says violations are only compliance. If this were a clearly defined general ceasefire followed by isolated breaches, that would be right. But the record shows something different: undefined conditions, the one clearly public operational term being Red Square, a prisoner-exchange purpose, and continued operations across the theater from day one. That is evidence that the arrangement never rose to the general pause required by the proposition.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce caution. Direct X or Telegram, direct Truth Social or White House, and the direct Ukrainian decree remain absent. The rule allows credible media consensus, but consensus reporting does not override ambiguity in the official-source record and battlefield evidence. At most, plaintiff proved a fragile, short, U.S.-brokered truce label attached to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The market required more.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, if the evidence is equally consistent with a limited prisoner-exchange/parade-security pause and a qualifying general pause, plaintiff loses. Here the limiting evidence is stronger than equal. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and resolution criteria\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Official-source case-packet record\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Guardian both-sides confirmation report\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Ukrainian-side Zelensky confirmation report\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 RFE/RL Trump announcement and both-sides confirmation\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule requiring general pause and excluding limited/humanitarian pauses\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Official-source packet: Russian prisoner-exchange framing and narrow Ukrainian decree capture\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Unresolved record gaps and known tension on scope/violations\\n# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 NV/ISW: continued offensive operations and undefined ceasefire conditions\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 CBS/AP: mutual violation accusations and no calm on front lines\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-4/DX-6 Zelenskyy report tying ceasefire regime to prisoner exchange\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-5/DX-7 RFE/RL report with Red Square and adverse violation context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Guardian broad ceasefire confirmation\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Zelenskyy confirmation of ceasefire regime\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 RFE/RL both-side confirmation and adverse context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R4 Defendant NV/ISW exhibit showing compliance dispute, not no agreement\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R5 Defendant CBS/AP exhibit showing both sides appeared to agree\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 NV/ISW: continued operations and unclear conditions as scope evidence\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 CBS/AP: mutual violations, unclear timeline, no calm on front line\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Official-source packet: prisoner-exchange and Red Square framing\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S4 Market rule requiring a general pause, not limited/humanitarian arrangements\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 8 2026 report: Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire (ev_236dce43c3d8_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-236dce43c3d8)\\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\\nSHA-256: `236dce43c3d8f0a768feb3c9aa5e4214f9afb219b3cc647e8679b1179e916c6c`\\nBytes: 1583\\nRelevance: Credible media report that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, suspension of kinetic activity, and prisoner swap; directly addresses public mutual agreement and scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026: Zelenskyy confirms truce with Russia on May 9-11 (ev_2c8cd49d9b00_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-2c8cd49d9b00)\\nSource: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033888/\\nSHA-256: `2c8cd49d9b0040da3a58b04496b028fae6de5fb2b66b02d1f9b68b7bb84bbcac`\\nBytes: 1248\\nRelevance: Ukrainian media report based on Zelenskyy on X/Twitter confirming Russia's agreement and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11; addresses Ukrainian-side public confirmation.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] RFE/RL May 8 2026: Trump announces three-day cease-fire; both sides confirm (ev_5d2cebff6f4b_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2cebff6f4b)\\nSource: https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-russia-victory-day-cease-fire-drone-attacks/33752482.html\\nSHA-256: `5d2cebff6f4b0f521cbfa77b06da6f8548e1352caa5fc5983a21cf59c675b46a`\\nBytes: 1405\\nRelevance: Report preserving Trump announcement, confirmation by both sides, suspension of kinetic activity, prisoner swap, and adverse context of earlier violations; addresses official public agreement and scope/compliance distinction.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] NV May 10 2026 report on ISW assessment: fighting continued during first day of ceasefire (ev_52a3277a9302_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-52a3277a9302)\\nSource: https://english.nv.ua/russian-war/isw-says-fighting-continued-despite-may-9-11-ceasefire-50606640.html\\nSHA-256: `52a3277a93024fbf92cdd1f34c2ebf0ee4a62600c40ffa7809cd520718baba32`\\nBytes: 1823\\nRelevance: Shows adverse implementation and scope evidence: offensive operations continued across the frontline, combat declined but did not stop, ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, only known condition was Red Square non-targeting, and Russian forces allegedly used the period to reinforce positions.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] CBS/AP May 10 2026: Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating ceasefire (ev_d5ef4e09892f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-d5ef4e09892f)\\nSource: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/russia-ukraine-accuse-each-other-ceasefire-violations/\\nSHA-256: `d5ef4e09892f541e4806e0e6d705f5472ab9890cf4567bf47bf3a56b73f03dd8`\\nBytes: 1606\\nRelevance: Shows contemporaneous post-agreement evidence that both sides accused each other of violations, Zelenskyy said there was no calm on front lines despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and the ceasefire timing was unclear; bears on whether the arrangement was a general pause rather than fragile/limited truce.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and capture ledger\\nPlaintiff searched official and source-specific paths for the May 8-11 ceasefire record. Successful captures submitted as evidence: Guardian May 8 report, Ukrainska Pravda May 8 Zelenskyy confirmation report, and RFE/RL May 8 Trump/both-sides confirmation report. Existing case-packet evidence supplies market criteria and a Kremlin official-source summary. Capture limits: direct X pages for Zelenskyy and WhiteHouse rendered no text in web open; PBS returned 403; Ukrinform opened without readable lines; ISW May 8/May 11 direct pages returned 403; earlier curl to the Kremlin page timed out. These failures leave some primary-source gaps, but the accepted captures preserve the material source-chain content and include adverse context on alleged violations.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nAt merits, defendant inspected the new plaintiff evidence and searched targeted terms for May 9-11 ceasefire scope, violations, and ISW assessments. Source targets included ISW May 9-11 assessments, accessible media captures of those assessments, and contemporaneous violation reports. Defendant submitted accepted captures from NV/ISW and CBS/AP. Direct primary social/official sources remain incompletely captured in the record, including direct Zelenskyy X/Telegram, Trump Truth Social/White House, and president.gov.ua decree text; those gaps affect weight because plaintiff relies heavily on secondary captures for scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff rebuttal evidence audit\\nPlaintiff inspected the two new defendant exhibits by stat/read_evidence_range. Both primarily address implementation: continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. Both also preserve or concede agreement facts: Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. No additional outside source was needed for this targeted rebuttal.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:22.654219585Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887016,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":13},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":18,\"version\":29}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 29\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630022841\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C5\nremaining_ms: 887016\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"after_version\":29,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630022841\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C5\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the dispute is not whether the May 2026 Russia-Ukraine war ended, whether the May 9-11 pause was perfectly honored, or whether every later market-platform statement was correct. The proposition asks a narrower question: by the May 31 deadline, had the parties officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that was general in character rather than merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or a future framework? On this record, the answer should be yes.\\n\\nThe case-packet evidence gives the governing lens. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d, states that an official ceasefire agreement qualifies if it is publicly announced and mutually agreed, and that a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement had been reached can suffice. It excludes informal arrangements, humanitarian pauses, energy- or Black Sea-only deals, and future frameworks without an explicit dated commitment to stop fighting. That definition matters because the proof here points to a dated May 9-May 11 ceasefire, not simply aspirational peace talks.\\n\\nThe strongest plaintiff proof in the existing packet is the convergence between official-source material and credible reporting. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, identifies a Kremlin source in which Yury Ushakov, speaking on instructions from President Putin, confirmed Russia’s acceptance of the U.S.-proposed ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and located the key agreement in the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. The same file records that Ukrainian-side confirmation is currently captured through Ukrinform because direct access to the Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in the packet environment. That creates a provenance gap we should fill later, but it is not a contradiction.\\n\\nThe secondary-reporting record, ev_cf0c77f2fe52, then supplies the market rule’s alternative path: multiple credible outlets and ISW are summarized as reporting that Russia and Ukraine confirmed or agreed to a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11, with suspension of kinetic activity and an associated 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, preserves the same source map and correctly warns that platform assertions are not independent proof. I accept that warning. Our case rests on the official and reporting source chain, not on the market’s final Yes label.\\n\\nThe defense will have real points to test. The Russian official framing connects the pause to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform appears narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, candidly identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s social-media confirmation, the Ukrainian presidential page, Trump’s announcement, and battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused generally. It also notes alleged violations and continuing hostilities around the period. Those issues affect weight and may affect how the council evaluates scope and implementation.\\n\\nBut those gaps do not change the core theory. A qualifying agreement can be temporary. It can be attached to a prisoner exchange. It can be violated after it is reached. The decisive question is whether the parties publicly and officially agreed to halt military engagement generally for a dated period, not whether the ceasefire became a lasting peace or achieved perfect compliance. The packet’s plaintiff-side evidence already points to both sides confirming a three-day suspension of kinetic activity, while the defense evidence mainly argues motive, context, and performance.\\n\\nIn the next evidence phase, the plaintiff should admit the strongest underlying sources: the Kremlin page, the best accessible Ukrainian official or official-adjacent confirmation, direct presidential or U.S. announcement records if obtainable, and implementation/violation assessments from ISW or similar monitors. Those materials will let the council separate three questions: agreement reached, scope of the agreed halt, and compliance in the field. For opening purposes, the record supports the plaintiff’s framing: this was not merely an informal understanding or a future framework, but an officially announced, mutually confirmed, dated ceasefire agreement broad enough to satisfy the proposition by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the thing this market asked for, not a nearby diplomatic event. The proposition requires an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict by May 31, 2026. It expressly excludes humanitarian pauses, limited arrangements, and future or partial frameworks.\\n\\nThe current packet does not yet carry that burden. It contains useful leads, but the strongest record materials point to a narrower event: a brief May 9-May 11 arrangement tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and a prisoner exchange. The market-page file, ev_f841be6ff80d, gives the rule and its exclusions, but it also warns that page-context assertions are platform assertions, not independent proof. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, repeats that caution: platform language cannot itself establish official mutuality, theatre-wide scope, implementation, or reliable consensus.\\n\\nThe official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, is where the burden problem becomes concrete. The Russian official text is not framed as a general pause in the conflict; it confirms Russia’s acceptance of a U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange, with the key agreement being a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during the May 9-May 11 period. On the Ukrainian side, the packet does not preserve a direct official presidential page; direct access reportedly returned 403. The available official-adjacent capture is Ukrinform’s report about a presidential decree that appears limited to allowing the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding Red Square from Ukrainian targeting during the parade. That is a substantial provenance and scope gap.\\n\\nThe plaintiff will rely on ev_cf0c77f2fe52, which summarizes credible reporting that both sides confirmed a three-day ceasefire. We do not ignore that. Secondary reporting may help find the underlying record and may later corroborate a mutual announcement. But at opening, those reports sit beside the packet’s own defense leads: Victory Day timing, Red Square security, prisoner-exchange purpose, allegations of violations, and ongoing retaliatory activity around the period. Those facts matter because the market did not ask whether some pause, some prisoner-exchange deconfliction, or some symbolic holiday arrangement occurred. It asked whether the parties had reached a general pause in military engagement.\\n\\nNor is this merely a compliance argument. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been agreed. But if the evidence shows the arrangement was designed and announced around a prisoner swap and parade security, and if fighting materially continued, that bears on whether the agreement was general in character at all. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, identifies the missing proof the council should want before finding for plaintiff: direct Zelenskyy confirmation, the direct Ukrainian presidential decree, direct Trump or White House announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence of whether hostilities generally paused, and complete official post-period violation statements.\\n\\nIn the evidence phase, the defense will test exactly those links: the full Kremlin text, the inaccessible Ukrainian decree or an authenticated archive, any direct Ukrainian presidential social-media confirmation, the U.S. announcement, ISW and other monitoring assessments, and post-period official violation statements. If those sources show a mutual, official, theatre-wide halt, plaintiff may have a case. If they show a short Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement amid continuing hostilities, the proposition fails.\\n\\nFor now, the packet supports caution, not a finding. Plaintiff’s opening treats a temporary three-day ceasefire label as enough. The market language demands more: a general pause in the conflict. On this record, the decisive proof is missing or points narrower, and the council should hold plaintiff to that burden.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the missing bridge the defense asked for. The record no longer rests only on the case packet. The admitted source captures show a public, mutual, dated ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine before the May 31 deadline, and the language used was broad enough to constitute a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. PX-1, the market-page record, requires an official ceasefire agreement: a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement. It excludes informal, humanitarian-only, energy-only, Black Sea-only, or future-framework arrangements. It also allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. That is exactly what the merits evidence now shows.\\n\\nPX-3, the Guardian May 8 capture, reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11. Its key points track the rule: Trump announced a ceasefire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine”; the ceasefire included suspension of all “kinetic activity”; and it was “confirmed by both sides.” The same capture records Ukrainian confirmation by Zelenskyy and Russian confirmation by Kremlin adviser Yury Ushakov. This is not a future framework. It is a dated ceasefire, announced before the deadline, with both parties identified.\\n\\nPX-4 directly answers the defense’s Ukrainian-source objection. Ukrainska Pravda, sourcing Zelenskyy on X, reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Trump’s truce with Russia for May 9-11 and quoted him saying Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement to conduct the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. That is Ukrainian-side public confirmation of Russia’s agreement and of the ceasefire regime. It is not merely a Red Square decree.\\n\\nPX-5 adds the U.S. announcement and the mutual-confirmation frame. RFE/RL reports Trump’s announcement of a three-day cease-fire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine,” including “suspension of all Kinetic activity,” and says both sides quickly confirmed the truce and prisoner swap. It also reports that Putin aide Yury Ushakov said Russia agreed to the three-day cease-fire and prisoner exchange. PX-2, the case-packet official-source record, independently preserves the Kremlin source path and confirms the Russian official framing.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is context: Victory Day, Red Square, and prisoner exchange. But context is not the same as limitation. A ceasefire can have an occasion and still be general in scope. A prisoner exchange can be conducted during a general ceasefire; it does not convert the ceasefire into a humanitarian-only pause when the announced term is suspension of all kinetic activity in the war between the two states. Likewise, the Red Square decree may be narrow by itself, but PX-4 and PX-5 show broader Ukrainian confirmation alongside that narrow parade-security action.\\n\\nThe defense also points to violations and continued activity. That matters for compliance, not formation. The proposition asks whether the parties had officially reached the public mutual halt by May 31. It does not require that no shot was later fired. PX-5 candidly includes adverse context: reports of earlier violations, strikes, and retaliatory claims around the period. Those facts show why compliance was contested, but they do not erase the public mutual agreement reported and confirmed on May 8.\\n\\nProvenance and custody: the five case-packet files are juror-visible case-packet evidence. PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5 were submitted in this merits phase as text captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and descriptions; AAR accepted each and assigned evidence IDs. Direct X pages and some official pages were hard to capture in this environment, but the accepted evidence faithfully preserves the relevant source-chain content and is corroborated across independent outlets and the existing official-source packet.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, plaintiff need not prove a lasting peace or flawless battlefield silence. The better reading of the admitted evidence is that by May 8, before the May 31 deadline, Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire in the war, including suspension of kinetic activity. That satisfies the proposition.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has improved the record, but not enough to satisfy the proposition. The record now supports that a three-day truce was publicly discussed and confirmed around May 8. The remaining question is whether that truce constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange arrangement. On this record, the better answer remains no.\\n\\nStart with the rule. DX-1, the market-page record, requires more than any official ceasefire label. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited agreements and requires a general pause in the conflict. That scope requirement does real work here.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own proof shows why. PX-4 says Zelenskyy framed the arrangement this way: within U.S.-mediated negotiations, Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and a ceasefire regime “must also be established” on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 likewise ties Trump’s announcement to a prisoner swap and reports Zelenskyy ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the Victory Day parade. DX-2, the official-source packet, is even narrower on the Russian side: Ushakov confirmed Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and the packet’s Ukrainian official-adjacent decree record is limited to Red Square/parade targeting. Those are not side details. They are the public shape of the deal.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat “suspension of all kinetic activity” as dispositive. But the source chain remains mostly media-captured, with direct X, Truth Social, and official Ukrainian decree captures still missing. More importantly, an announced aspiration to suspend kinetic activity does not resolve whether the parties actually reached a general conflict pause, as opposed to a brief operational deconfliction attached to POW exchange and parade security. The burden is plaintiff’s, and ambiguity on scope counts against them.\\n\\nThe implementation evidence confirms that ambiguity. DX-4, the NV/ISW capture, reports Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It says intensity decreased but did not stop, Ukraine reported 51 combat engagements, Russian forces continued strikes in Kharkiv and Kherson Oblasts, and Russia claimed thousands of Ukrainian violations. It also reports ISW’s assessment that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions and that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square, which Kyiv upheld. That is powerful evidence that the practical, defined commitment was narrow.\\n\\nDX-5, CBS/AP’s May 10 report, shows the same pattern during the supposed pause. Both sides accused each other of breaking the ceasefire; Zelenskyy said Russia was not observing the truce and that there was no calm in frontline areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks; Russia accused Ukraine of more than 1,000 violations and said it responded in kind. CBS/AP also noted the three-day pause’s timeline was somewhat unclear. This is not offered to impose a perfect-compliance requirement. It is offered because widespread continued operations, undefined conditions, and mutual “response in kind” claims are probative of what kind of arrangement was actually reached.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s best legal point is that an agreement can be violated and still be an agreement. Correct. But the proposition is not “was there an agreement called a ceasefire?” It asks whether there was a general pause in military engagement. Formation and scope are intertwined: if the only clearly defined official condition was Red Square non-targeting, if Russia’s official acceptance described a prisoner-exchange purpose, if the exchange did not even occur as the announced 1,000-for-1,000 event during the truce period on this record, and if operations continued across the theater, then plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause by a preponderance.\\n\\nProvenance matters too. Plaintiff’s new exhibits are accepted text captures from reputable outlets, but they remain secondary captures of hard-to-access primary statements. The case-packet itself, DX-3, flags the same gaps: missing direct Zelenskyy social-media confirmation, missing direct Ukrainian presidential decree, missing direct Trump/White House record, and missing battlefield/monitoring evidence. Defendant filled part of that last gap with DX-4 and DX-5, and the result undercuts plaintiff’s scope theory.\\n\\nSearch and capture ledger: I checked targeted May 9-11 ceasefire-violation and ISW queries after reading plaintiff’s exhibits. ISW May 9-11 assessments appeared as the strongest implementation target; accessible captures were preserved through NV’s ISW summary and CBS/AP’s contemporaneous violation report. A Guardian May 9 Red Square/frontline article was opened but not submitted because DX-4 and DX-5 more directly address implementation and scope.\\n\\nThe council can find that a short truce was announced. It should not find that plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition. The admitted evidence shows a fragile, underdefined, prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with continued frontline operations, not a publicly agreed general pause in the Russia-Ukraine conflict.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s new evidence proves the wrong point. DX-4 and DX-5 are evidence of poor compliance, weak monitoring, and violation accusations. They are not evidence that the May 8 agreement was merely Red Square-only or that no official public mutual ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nThat distinction matters because the proposition and PX-1 focus on whether the parties had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt by May 31. The market rule even says a qualifying agreement can resolve Yes if officially reached before the resolution date regardless of later start mechanics. Defendant’s evidence is mostly about what happened after the agreement was announced.\\n\\nDX-4, the NV/ISW capture, says fighting intensity decreased but did not stop completely. It reports continued operations and weak ceasefire mechanisms. But it also states President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 exchange. DX-5, the CBS/AP capture, likewise reports accusations of violations, but it also states Trump announced Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire and that both sides appeared to agree. These are concessions on formation.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn noncompliance into narrow scope. That does not follow. A general ceasefire with poor monitoring can be violated. A general ceasefire can be attached to a prisoner exchange. A general ceasefire can coincide with Victory Day. None of those facts converts broad language like “ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine” and “suspension of all kinetic activity” into a Red Square-only arrangement.\\n\\nThe best scope evidence remains PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5. PX-3 says both sides confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire and suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-4 gives the Ukrainian-side confirmation: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement and a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 gives the U.S. announcement and both-side confirmation: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides.\\n\\nThe Red Square material is narrower, but it is not the whole agreement. It is an additional operational commitment about parade targeting. The prisoner exchange is likewise not disqualifying. The market excludes humanitarian pauses, but this record does not show a prisoner-exchange-only corridor or a local evacuation window. It shows a ceasefire in the war, with all kinetic activity suspended, plus a prisoner swap during that pause.\\n\\nDefendant also leans on missing primary captures. Those gaps affect weight, and plaintiff disclosed them. But the rule expressly permits wide credible media consensus, and the accepted captures are mutually reinforcing: Guardian, Ukrainska Pravda, RFE/RL, and the case-packet official-source record all converge on public mutual confirmation. Defendant’s own exhibits do not break that chain; they accept the announcement and agreement, then dispute implementation.\\n\\nSo the actual evidentiary balance is this: plaintiff has multiple accepted sources proving official public mutual agreement to a dated ceasefire with broad kinetic-activity language. Defendant has sources proving the ceasefire was fragile and violated. Under a preponderance standard, the former satisfies the proposition; the latter does not rewrite it.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal is right about one thing but draws the wrong conclusion. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been reached. If the record showed a clearly defined general pause followed by isolated breaches, defendant would lose that point.\\n\\nBut DX-4 and DX-5 are not just breach evidence. They are scope and character evidence. DX-4 reports that, on the first day of the supposed May 9-11 general pause, Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline; combat declined but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and ISW assessed that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most importantly, DX-4 says the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade. That does not look like a defined, general halt in military engagement. It looks like a fragile holiday/prisoner-exchange deconfliction with one concrete parade-security condition.\\n\\nDX-5 is similar. Plaintiff stresses that CBS/AP says both sides appeared to agree. But the same exhibit says the timeline was somewhat unclear, both sides accused each other of breaking the truce, Zelenskyy said there was no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and Russia claimed it responded in kind. Again, defendant is not saying every violation voids formation. Defendant is saying the record as a whole does not show the qualifying thing: a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nThat distinction is why plaintiff’s “formation not compliance” framing is too narrow. The proposition contains a scope element. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. The official-source packet says Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange. Plaintiff’s Ukrainian-side evidence likewise puts the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange at the center, and the direct Ukrainian decree remains missing while the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square-specific. Plaintiff’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase is powerful, but it is mostly preserved through media captures, not through the unavailable primary posts, and it must be weighed against the operational evidence that no defined general pause actually existed.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat announcement language as enough and implementation as irrelevant. The market does not permit that shortcut. It asks whether the parties reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. Where the public official detail is prisoner exchange and Red Square, the conditions are undefined, and fighting continued across the theater from the first day, plaintiff has not carried that stricter burden by a preponderance.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record resolves this case on a preponderance standard.\\n\\nThe proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It does not ask whether the war ended, whether the ceasefire was durable, or whether neither side later accused the other of violations.\\n\\nThe decisive record is straightforward. PX-1 defines the qualifying event as an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and permits a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. PX-3 reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, that Trump announced it as a ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, that it included suspension of all kinetic activity, and that it was confirmed by both sides. PX-4 supplies Ukrainian-side confirmation: Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 truce with Russia, said Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement, and said a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 supplies the U.S. announcement and the same mutual-confirmation frame: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides, including Russian agreement through Ushakov. PX-2 independently preserves the Russian official-source path.\\n\\nThat evidence satisfies the elements: official/public, mutual, dated before the deadline, and general in the only sense the market required: a halt in military engagement in the war, not a sector-only Black Sea or energy arrangement, not a mere informal understanding, and not a future framework.\\n\\nThe defense’s contrary evidence is important, but it points mainly to performance. DX-4 and DX-5 show continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. We should not ignore that. But both exhibits also preserve the formation facts: Trump announced the ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. A breached ceasefire is still a ceasefire agreement. The proposition turns on whether the agreement was reached, not whether it was perfectly obeyed.\\n\\nThe defense says the prisoner exchange and Victory Day context make the pause non-general. The better reading is that they explain why the parties accepted a temporary general pause. A prisoner exchange can occur during a broad ceasefire; it does not make the ceasefire humanitarian-only when the announced scope is suspension of all kinetic activity. Red Square non-targeting was an additional concrete operational condition, not the whole agreement. The record contains separate broader language: ceasefire in the war, ceasefire regime on May 9-11, suspension of kinetic activity, and both sides confirmed.\\n\\nThere are source-chain gaps: direct X, Truth Social, and some official pages were hard to capture. But the market rule expressly allows credible media consensus, and here the accepted sources converge with the case-packet official-source record. The defense’s own evidence does not break that convergence; it disputes execution.\\n\\nOn balance, plaintiff’s evidence proves more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed May 9-11 halt in military engagement before May 31. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case is not about whether something happened on May 8. Something did. The record supports that a short May 9-11 truce was announced and that both sides were reported as accepting it. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition: an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause, limited arrangement, or future framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not carried that burden.\\n\\nStart with the governing rule. The market-page record requires a general pause and excludes humanitarian and limited agreements. That means the council cannot stop at the word “ceasefire” or at the fact of a public announcement. It must ask what kind of ceasefire the record proves.\\n\\nThe official-source packet supplies the best answer. Russia’s official source, through Ushakov, accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.” The key agreement described there was a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during May 9-11. On the Ukrainian official side, the direct presidential decree was not captured; the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square and parade-specific. Those facts do not prove a theatre-wide general pause. They prove a prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with a concrete parade-security component.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s own merits exhibits do not eliminate that limitation. PX-4 quotes Zelenskyy in the context of the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and says a ceasefire regime must also be established. PX-5 reports the Trump announcement but also says Zelenskyy ordered no attack on Red Square and preserves the same prisoner-swap frame. Yes, those sources use broad language such as “suspension of all kinetic activity.” But broad media language must be weighed against the actual official-source detail, the missing primary captures, and what the parties did when the supposed general pause began.\\n\\nThat implementation evidence is decisive because it goes to character and scope, not merely breach. DX-4 reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day; combat intensity decreased but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most tellingly, DX-4 reports that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square. DX-5 reports no calm in front line areas, mutual violation accusations, an unclear timeline, and Russian “response in kind.”\\n\\nPlaintiff says violations are only compliance. If this were a clearly defined general ceasefire followed by isolated breaches, that would be right. But the record shows something different: undefined conditions, the one clearly public operational term being Red Square, a prisoner-exchange purpose, and continued operations across the theater from day one. That is evidence that the arrangement never rose to the general pause required by the proposition.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce caution. Direct X or Telegram, direct Truth Social or White House, and the direct Ukrainian decree remain absent. The rule allows credible media consensus, but consensus reporting does not override ambiguity in the official-source record and battlefield evidence. At most, plaintiff proved a fragile, short, U.S.-brokered truce label attached to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The market required more.\\n\\nOn a preponderance standard, if the evidence is equally consistent with a limited prisoner-exchange/parade-security pause and a qualifying general pause, plaintiff loses. Here the limiting evidence is stronger than equal. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and resolution criteria\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Official-source case-packet record\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Guardian both-sides confirmation report\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Ukrainian-side Zelensky confirmation report\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 RFE/RL Trump announcement and both-sides confirmation\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule requiring general pause and excluding limited/humanitarian pauses\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Official-source packet: Russian prisoner-exchange framing and narrow Ukrainian decree capture\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 Unresolved record gaps and known tension on scope/violations\\n# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 NV/ISW: continued offensive operations and undefined ceasefire conditions\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 CBS/AP: mutual violation accusations and no calm on front lines\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-4/DX-6 Zelenskyy report tying ceasefire regime to prisoner exchange\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-5/DX-7 RFE/RL report with Red Square and adverse violation context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Guardian broad ceasefire confirmation\\nSource: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\\\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \\\"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\\\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \\\"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \\\"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Zelenskyy confirmation of ceasefire regime\\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\\\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \\\"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\\\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 RFE/RL both-side confirmation and adverse context\\nSource: RFE/RL, \\\"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\\\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \\\"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\\\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \\\"suspension of all Kinetic activity\\\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \\\"cease-fire regime must also be established,\\\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R4 Defendant NV/ISW exhibit showing compliance dispute, not no agreement\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R5 Defendant CBS/AP exhibit showing both sides appeared to agree\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 NV/ISW: continued operations and unclear conditions as scope evidence\\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \\\"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\\\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\\n\\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\\n\\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 CBS/AP: mutual violations, unclear timeline, no calm on front line\\nSource: CBS News/AP, \\\"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\\\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\\n\\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\\n\\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \\\"even particularly trying to,\\\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\\n\\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S3 Official-source packet: prisoner-exchange and Red Square framing\\n# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S4 Market rule requiring a general pause, not limited/humanitarian arrangements\\n# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 8 2026 report: Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire (ev_236dce43c3d8_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-236dce43c3d8)\\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\\nSHA-256: `236dce43c3d8f0a768feb3c9aa5e4214f9afb219b3cc647e8679b1179e916c6c`\\nBytes: 1583\\nRelevance: Credible media report that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, suspension of kinetic activity, and prisoner swap; directly addresses public mutual agreement and scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026: Zelenskyy confirms truce with Russia on May 9-11 (ev_2c8cd49d9b00_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-2c8cd49d9b00)\\nSource: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033888/\\nSHA-256: `2c8cd49d9b0040da3a58b04496b028fae6de5fb2b66b02d1f9b68b7bb84bbcac`\\nBytes: 1248\\nRelevance: Ukrainian media report based on Zelenskyy on X/Twitter confirming Russia's agreement and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11; addresses Ukrainian-side public confirmation.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] RFE/RL May 8 2026: Trump announces three-day cease-fire; both sides confirm (ev_5d2cebff6f4b_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2cebff6f4b)\\nSource: https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-russia-victory-day-cease-fire-drone-attacks/33752482.html\\nSHA-256: `5d2cebff6f4b0f521cbfa77b06da6f8548e1352caa5fc5983a21cf59c675b46a`\\nBytes: 1405\\nRelevance: Report preserving Trump announcement, confirmation by both sides, suspension of kinetic activity, prisoner swap, and adverse context of earlier violations; addresses official public agreement and scope/compliance distinction.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] NV May 10 2026 report on ISW assessment: fighting continued during first day of ceasefire (ev_52a3277a9302_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-52a3277a9302)\\nSource: https://english.nv.ua/russian-war/isw-says-fighting-continued-despite-may-9-11-ceasefire-50606640.html\\nSHA-256: `52a3277a93024fbf92cdd1f34c2ebf0ee4a62600c40ffa7809cd520718baba32`\\nBytes: 1823\\nRelevance: Shows adverse implementation and scope evidence: offensive operations continued across the frontline, combat declined but did not stop, ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, only known condition was Red Square non-targeting, and Russian forces allegedly used the period to reinforce positions.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] CBS/AP May 10 2026: Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating ceasefire (ev_d5ef4e09892f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-d5ef4e09892f)\\nSource: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/russia-ukraine-accuse-each-other-ceasefire-violations/\\nSHA-256: `d5ef4e09892f541e4806e0e6d705f5472ab9890cf4567bf47bf3a56b73f03dd8`\\nBytes: 1606\\nRelevance: Shows contemporaneous post-agreement evidence that both sides accused each other of violations, Zelenskyy said there was no calm on front lines despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and the ceasefire timing was unclear; bears on whether the arrangement was a general pause rather than fragile/limited truce.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and capture ledger\\nPlaintiff searched official and source-specific paths for the May 8-11 ceasefire record. Successful captures submitted as evidence: Guardian May 8 report, Ukrainska Pravda May 8 Zelenskyy confirmation report, and RFE/RL May 8 Trump/both-sides confirmation report. Existing case-packet evidence supplies market criteria and a Kremlin official-source summary. Capture limits: direct X pages for Zelenskyy and WhiteHouse rendered no text in web open; PBS returned 403; Ukrinform opened without readable lines; ISW May 8/May 11 direct pages returned 403; earlier curl to the Kremlin page timed out. These failures leave some primary-source gaps, but the accepted captures preserve the material source-chain content and include adverse context on alleged violations.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\\nAt merits, defendant inspected the new plaintiff evidence and searched targeted terms for May 9-11 ceasefire scope, violations, and ISW assessments. Source targets included ISW May 9-11 assessments, accessible media captures of those assessments, and contemporaneous violation reports. Defendant submitted accepted captures from NV/ISW and CBS/AP. Direct primary social/official sources remain incompletely captured in the record, including direct Zelenskyy X/Telegram, Trump Truth Social/White House, and president.gov.ua decree text; those gaps affect weight because plaintiff relies heavily on secondary captures for scope.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff rebuttal evidence audit\\nPlaintiff inspected the two new defendant exhibits by stat/read_evidence_range. Both primarily address implementation: continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. Both also preserve or concede agreement facts: Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. No additional outside source was needed for this targeted rebuttal.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:22.654219585Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887016,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":13},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":18,\"version\":29}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C5","after_version":29,"case_id":"arb-ex07-20260630022841","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C5","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C5\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the dispute is not whether the May 2026 Russia-Ukraine war ended, whether the May 9-11 pause was perfectly honored, or whether every later market-platform statement was correct. The proposition asks a narrower question: by the May 31 deadline, had the parties officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that was general in character rather than merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or a future framework? On this record, the answer should be yes.\n\nThe case-packet evidence gives the governing lens. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d, states that an official ceasefire agreement qualifies if it is publicly announced and mutually agreed, and that a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement had been reached can suffice. It excludes informal arrangements, humanitarian pauses, energy- or Black Sea-only deals, and future frameworks without an explicit dated commitment to stop fighting. That definition matters because the proof here points to a dated May 9-May 11 ceasefire, not simply aspirational peace talks.\n\nThe strongest plaintiff proof in the existing packet is the convergence between official-source material and credible reporting. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, identifies a Kremlin source in which Yury Ushakov, speaking on instructions from President Putin, confirmed Russia’s acceptance of the U.S.-proposed ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and located the key agreement in the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. The same file records that Ukrainian-side confirmation is currently captured through Ukrinform because direct access to the Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in the packet environment. That creates a provenance gap we should fill later, but it is not a contradiction.\n\nThe secondary-reporting record, ev_cf0c77f2fe52, then supplies the market rule’s alternative path: multiple credible outlets and ISW are summarized as reporting that Russia and Ukraine confirmed or agreed to a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11, with suspension of kinetic activity and an associated 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, preserves the same source map and correctly warns that platform assertions are not independent proof. I accept that warning. Our case rests on the official and reporting source chain, not on the market’s final Yes label.\n\nThe defense will have real points to test. The Russian official framing connects the pause to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform appears narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, candidly identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s social-media confirmation, the Ukrainian presidential page, Trump’s announcement, and battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused generally. It also notes alleged violations and continuing hostilities around the period. Those issues affect weight and may affect how the council evaluates scope and implementation.\n\nBut those gaps do not change the core theory. A qualifying agreement can be temporary. It can be attached to a prisoner exchange. It can be violated after it is reached. The decisive question is whether the parties publicly and officially agreed to halt military engagement generally for a dated period, not whether the ceasefire became a lasting peace or achieved perfect compliance. The packet’s plaintiff-side evidence already points to both sides confirming a three-day suspension of kinetic activity, while the defense evidence mainly argues motive, context, and performance.\n\nIn the next evidence phase, the plaintiff should admit the strongest underlying sources: the Kremlin page, the best accessible Ukrainian official or official-adjacent confirmation, direct presidential or U.S. announcement records if obtainable, and implementation/violation assessments from ISW or similar monitors. Those materials will let the council separate three questions: agreement reached, scope of the agreed halt, and compliance in the field. For opening purposes, the record supports the plaintiff’s framing: this was not merely an informal understanding or a future framework, but an officially announced, mutually confirmed, dated ceasefire agreement broad enough to satisfy the proposition by a preponderance of the evidence.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: the plaintiff must prove the thing this market asked for, not a nearby diplomatic event. The proposition requires an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict by May 31, 2026. It expressly excludes humanitarian pauses, limited arrangements, and future or partial frameworks.\n\nThe current packet does not yet carry that burden. It contains useful leads, but the strongest record materials point to a narrower event: a brief May 9-May 11 arrangement tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and a prisoner exchange. The market-page file, ev_f841be6ff80d, gives the rule and its exclusions, but it also warns that page-context assertions are platform assertions, not independent proof. The primary-evidence overview, ev_54e94624d245, repeats that caution: platform language cannot itself establish official mutuality, theatre-wide scope, implementation, or reliable consensus.\n\nThe official-source record, ev_959b165782b3, is where the burden problem becomes concrete. The Russian official text is not framed as a general pause in the conflict; it confirms Russia’s acceptance of a U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange, with the key agreement being a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during the May 9-May 11 period. On the Ukrainian side, the packet does not preserve a direct official presidential page; direct access reportedly returned 403. The available official-adjacent capture is Ukrinform’s report about a presidential decree that appears limited to allowing the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding Red Square from Ukrainian targeting during the parade. That is a substantial provenance and scope gap.\n\nThe plaintiff will rely on ev_cf0c77f2fe52, which summarizes credible reporting that both sides confirmed a three-day ceasefire. We do not ignore that. Secondary reporting may help find the underlying record and may later corroborate a mutual announcement. But at opening, those reports sit beside the packet’s own defense leads: Victory Day timing, Red Square security, prisoner-exchange purpose, allegations of violations, and ongoing retaliatory activity around the period. Those facts matter because the market did not ask whether some pause, some prisoner-exchange deconfliction, or some symbolic holiday arrangement occurred. It asked whether the parties had reached a general pause in military engagement.\n\nNor is this merely a compliance argument. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been agreed. But if the evidence shows the arrangement was designed and announced around a prisoner swap and parade security, and if fighting materially continued, that bears on whether the agreement was general in character at all. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56, identifies the missing proof the council should want before finding for plaintiff: direct Zelenskyy confirmation, the direct Ukrainian presidential decree, direct Trump or White House announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence of whether hostilities generally paused, and complete official post-period violation statements.\n\nIn the evidence phase, the defense will test exactly those links: the full Kremlin text, the inaccessible Ukrainian decree or an authenticated archive, any direct Ukrainian presidential social-media confirmation, the U.S. announcement, ISW and other monitoring assessments, and post-period official violation statements. If those sources show a mutual, official, theatre-wide halt, plaintiff may have a case. If they show a short Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement amid continuing hostilities, the proposition fails.\n\nFor now, the packet supports caution, not a finding. Plaintiff’s opening treats a temporary three-day ceasefire label as enough. The market language demands more: a general pause in the conflict. On this record, the decisive proof is missing or points narrower, and the council should hold plaintiff to that burden.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, plaintiff has now supplied the missing bridge the defense asked for. The record no longer rests only on the case packet. The admitted source captures show a public, mutual, dated ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine before the May 31 deadline, and the language used was broad enough to constitute a general halt in military engagement.\n\nStart with the governing rule. PX-1, the market-page record, requires an official ceasefire agreement: a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement. It excludes informal, humanitarian-only, energy-only, Black Sea-only, or future-framework arrangements. It also allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. That is exactly what the merits evidence now shows.\n\nPX-3, the Guardian May 8 capture, reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to May 11. Its key points track the rule: Trump announced a ceasefire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine”; the ceasefire included suspension of all “kinetic activity”; and it was “confirmed by both sides.” The same capture records Ukrainian confirmation by Zelenskyy and Russian confirmation by Kremlin adviser Yury Ushakov. This is not a future framework. It is a dated ceasefire, announced before the deadline, with both parties identified.\n\nPX-4 directly answers the defense’s Ukrainian-source objection. Ukrainska Pravda, sourcing Zelenskyy on X, reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Trump’s truce with Russia for May 9-11 and quoted him saying Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement to conduct the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. That is Ukrainian-side public confirmation of Russia’s agreement and of the ceasefire regime. It is not merely a Red Square decree.\n\nPX-5 adds the U.S. announcement and the mutual-confirmation frame. RFE/RL reports Trump’s announcement of a three-day cease-fire “in the war between Russia and Ukraine,” including “suspension of all Kinetic activity,” and says both sides quickly confirmed the truce and prisoner swap. It also reports that Putin aide Yury Ushakov said Russia agreed to the three-day cease-fire and prisoner exchange. PX-2, the case-packet official-source record, independently preserves the Kremlin source path and confirms the Russian official framing.\n\nThe defense’s best point is context: Victory Day, Red Square, and prisoner exchange. But context is not the same as limitation. A ceasefire can have an occasion and still be general in scope. A prisoner exchange can be conducted during a general ceasefire; it does not convert the ceasefire into a humanitarian-only pause when the announced term is suspension of all kinetic activity in the war between the two states. Likewise, the Red Square decree may be narrow by itself, but PX-4 and PX-5 show broader Ukrainian confirmation alongside that narrow parade-security action.\n\nThe defense also points to violations and continued activity. That matters for compliance, not formation. The proposition asks whether the parties had officially reached the public mutual halt by May 31. It does not require that no shot was later fired. PX-5 candidly includes adverse context: reports of earlier violations, strikes, and retaliatory claims around the period. Those facts show why compliance was contested, but they do not erase the public mutual agreement reported and confirmed on May 8.\n\nProvenance and custody: the five case-packet files are juror-visible case-packet evidence. PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5 were submitted in this merits phase as text captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and descriptions; AAR accepted each and assigned evidence IDs. Direct X pages and some official pages were hard to capture in this environment, but the accepted evidence faithfully preserves the relevant source-chain content and is corroborated across independent outlets and the existing official-source packet.\n\nOn a preponderance standard, plaintiff need not prove a lasting peace or flawless battlefield silence. The better reading of the admitted evidence is that by May 8, before the May 31 deadline, Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire in the war, including suspension of kinetic activity. That satisfies the proposition.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has improved the record, but not enough to satisfy the proposition. The record now supports that a three-day truce was publicly discussed and confirmed around May 8. The remaining question is whether that truce constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange arrangement. On this record, the better answer remains no.\n\nStart with the rule. DX-1, the market-page record, requires more than any official ceasefire label. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited agreements and requires a general pause in the conflict. That scope requirement does real work here.\n\nPlaintiff’s own proof shows why. PX-4 says Zelenskyy framed the arrangement this way: within U.S.-mediated negotiations, Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and a ceasefire regime “must also be established” on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 likewise ties Trump’s announcement to a prisoner swap and reports Zelenskyy ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the Victory Day parade. DX-2, the official-source packet, is even narrower on the Russian side: Ushakov confirmed Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and the packet’s Ukrainian official-adjacent decree record is limited to Red Square/parade targeting. Those are not side details. They are the public shape of the deal.\n\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat “suspension of all kinetic activity” as dispositive. But the source chain remains mostly media-captured, with direct X, Truth Social, and official Ukrainian decree captures still missing. More importantly, an announced aspiration to suspend kinetic activity does not resolve whether the parties actually reached a general conflict pause, as opposed to a brief operational deconfliction attached to POW exchange and parade security. The burden is plaintiff’s, and ambiguity on scope counts against them.\n\nThe implementation evidence confirms that ambiguity. DX-4, the NV/ISW capture, reports Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It says intensity decreased but did not stop, Ukraine reported 51 combat engagements, Russian forces continued strikes in Kharkiv and Kherson Oblasts, and Russia claimed thousands of Ukrainian violations. It also reports ISW’s assessment that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions and that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square, which Kyiv upheld. That is powerful evidence that the practical, defined commitment was narrow.\n\nDX-5, CBS/AP’s May 10 report, shows the same pattern during the supposed pause. Both sides accused each other of breaking the ceasefire; Zelenskyy said Russia was not observing the truce and that there was no calm in frontline areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks; Russia accused Ukraine of more than 1,000 violations and said it responded in kind. CBS/AP also noted the three-day pause’s timeline was somewhat unclear. This is not offered to impose a perfect-compliance requirement. It is offered because widespread continued operations, undefined conditions, and mutual “response in kind” claims are probative of what kind of arrangement was actually reached.\n\nPlaintiff’s best legal point is that an agreement can be violated and still be an agreement. Correct. But the proposition is not “was there an agreement called a ceasefire?” It asks whether there was a general pause in military engagement. Formation and scope are intertwined: if the only clearly defined official condition was Red Square non-targeting, if Russia’s official acceptance described a prisoner-exchange purpose, if the exchange did not even occur as the announced 1,000-for-1,000 event during the truce period on this record, and if operations continued across the theater, then plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause by a preponderance.\n\nProvenance matters too. Plaintiff’s new exhibits are accepted text captures from reputable outlets, but they remain secondary captures of hard-to-access primary statements. The case-packet itself, DX-3, flags the same gaps: missing direct Zelenskyy social-media confirmation, missing direct Ukrainian presidential decree, missing direct Trump/White House record, and missing battlefield/monitoring evidence. Defendant filled part of that last gap with DX-4 and DX-5, and the result undercuts plaintiff’s scope theory.\n\nSearch and capture ledger: I checked targeted May 9-11 ceasefire-violation and ISW queries after reading plaintiff’s exhibits. ISW May 9-11 assessments appeared as the strongest implementation target; accessible captures were preserved through NV’s ISW summary and CBS/AP’s contemporaneous violation report. A Guardian May 9 Red Square/frontline article was opened but not submitted because DX-4 and DX-5 more directly address implementation and scope.\n\nThe council can find that a short truce was announced. It should not find that plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition. The admitted evidence shows a fragile, underdefined, prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with continued frontline operations, not a publicly agreed general pause in the Russia-Ukraine conflict.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s new evidence proves the wrong point. DX-4 and DX-5 are evidence of poor compliance, weak monitoring, and violation accusations. They are not evidence that the May 8 agreement was merely Red Square-only or that no official public mutual ceasefire agreement was reached.\n\nThat distinction matters because the proposition and PX-1 focus on whether the parties had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt by May 31. The market rule even says a qualifying agreement can resolve Yes if officially reached before the resolution date regardless of later start mechanics. Defendant’s evidence is mostly about what happened after the agreement was announced.\n\nDX-4, the NV/ISW capture, says fighting intensity decreased but did not stop completely. It reports continued operations and weak ceasefire mechanisms. But it also states President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 exchange. DX-5, the CBS/AP capture, likewise reports accusations of violations, but it also states Trump announced Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire and that both sides appeared to agree. These are concessions on formation.\n\nThe defense tries to turn noncompliance into narrow scope. That does not follow. A general ceasefire with poor monitoring can be violated. A general ceasefire can be attached to a prisoner exchange. A general ceasefire can coincide with Victory Day. None of those facts converts broad language like “ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine” and “suspension of all kinetic activity” into a Red Square-only arrangement.\n\nThe best scope evidence remains PX-3, PX-4, and PX-5. PX-3 says both sides confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire and suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-4 gives the Ukrainian-side confirmation: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement and a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 gives the U.S. announcement and both-side confirmation: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides.\n\nThe Red Square material is narrower, but it is not the whole agreement. It is an additional operational commitment about parade targeting. The prisoner exchange is likewise not disqualifying. The market excludes humanitarian pauses, but this record does not show a prisoner-exchange-only corridor or a local evacuation window. It shows a ceasefire in the war, with all kinetic activity suspended, plus a prisoner swap during that pause.\n\nDefendant also leans on missing primary captures. Those gaps affect weight, and plaintiff disclosed them. But the rule expressly permits wide credible media consensus, and the accepted captures are mutually reinforcing: Guardian, Ukrainska Pravda, RFE/RL, and the case-packet official-source record all converge on public mutual confirmation. Defendant’s own exhibits do not break that chain; they accept the announcement and agreement, then dispute implementation.\n\nSo the actual evidentiary balance is this: plaintiff has multiple accepted sources proving official public mutual agreement to a dated ceasefire with broad kinetic-activity language. Defendant has sources proving the ceasefire was fragile and violated. Under a preponderance standard, the former satisfies the proposition; the latter does not rewrite it.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal is right about one thing but draws the wrong conclusion. A ceasefire can be violated and still have been reached. If the record showed a clearly defined general pause followed by isolated breaches, defendant would lose that point.\n\nBut DX-4 and DX-5 are not just breach evidence. They are scope and character evidence. DX-4 reports that, on the first day of the supposed May 9-11 general pause, Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline; combat declined but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and ISW assessed that the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most importantly, DX-4 says the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade. That does not look like a defined, general halt in military engagement. It looks like a fragile holiday/prisoner-exchange deconfliction with one concrete parade-security condition.\n\nDX-5 is similar. Plaintiff stresses that CBS/AP says both sides appeared to agree. But the same exhibit says the timeline was somewhat unclear, both sides accused each other of breaking the truce, Zelenskyy said there was no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and Russia claimed it responded in kind. Again, defendant is not saying every violation voids formation. Defendant is saying the record as a whole does not show the qualifying thing: a general pause in the conflict.\n\nThat distinction is why plaintiff’s “formation not compliance” framing is too narrow. The proposition contains a scope element. It excludes humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. The official-source packet says Russia accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange. Plaintiff’s Ukrainian-side evidence likewise puts the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange at the center, and the direct Ukrainian decree remains missing while the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square-specific. Plaintiff’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase is powerful, but it is mostly preserved through media captures, not through the unavailable primary posts, and it must be weighed against the operational evidence that no defined general pause actually existed.\n\nPlaintiff asks the council to treat announcement language as enough and implementation as irrelevant. The market does not permit that shortcut. It asks whether the parties reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. Where the public official detail is prisoner exchange and Red Square, the conditions are undefined, and fighting continued across the theater from the first day, plaintiff has not carried that stricter burden by a preponderance.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record resolves this case on a preponderance standard.\n\nThe proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It does not ask whether the war ended, whether the ceasefire was durable, or whether neither side later accused the other of violations.\n\nThe decisive record is straightforward. PX-1 defines the qualifying event as an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and permits a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. PX-3 reports that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, that Trump announced it as a ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, that it included suspension of all kinetic activity, and that it was confirmed by both sides. PX-4 supplies Ukrainian-side confirmation: Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 truce with Russia, said Ukraine had received Russia’s agreement, and said a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. PX-5 supplies the U.S. announcement and the same mutual-confirmation frame: a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, suspension of all kinetic activity, and confirmation by both sides, including Russian agreement through Ushakov. PX-2 independently preserves the Russian official-source path.\n\nThat evidence satisfies the elements: official/public, mutual, dated before the deadline, and general in the only sense the market required: a halt in military engagement in the war, not a sector-only Black Sea or energy arrangement, not a mere informal understanding, and not a future framework.\n\nThe defense’s contrary evidence is important, but it points mainly to performance. DX-4 and DX-5 show continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. We should not ignore that. But both exhibits also preserve the formation facts: Trump announced the ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. A breached ceasefire is still a ceasefire agreement. The proposition turns on whether the agreement was reached, not whether it was perfectly obeyed.\n\nThe defense says the prisoner exchange and Victory Day context make the pause non-general. The better reading is that they explain why the parties accepted a temporary general pause. A prisoner exchange can occur during a broad ceasefire; it does not make the ceasefire humanitarian-only when the announced scope is suspension of all kinetic activity. Red Square non-targeting was an additional concrete operational condition, not the whole agreement. The record contains separate broader language: ceasefire in the war, ceasefire regime on May 9-11, suspension of kinetic activity, and both sides confirmed.\n\nThere are source-chain gaps: direct X, Truth Social, and some official pages were hard to capture. But the market rule expressly allows credible media consensus, and here the accepted sources converge with the case-packet official-source record. The defense’s own evidence does not break that convergence; it disputes execution.\n\nOn balance, plaintiff’s evidence proves more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed May 9-11 halt in military engagement before May 31. The council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, this case is not about whether something happened on May 8. Something did. The record supports that a short May 9-11 truce was announced and that both sides were reported as accepting it. The question is whether plaintiff proved the market’s stricter proposition: an official, public, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause, limited arrangement, or future framework.\n\nPlaintiff has not carried that burden.\n\nStart with the governing rule. The market-page record requires a general pause and excludes humanitarian and limited agreements. That means the council cannot stop at the word “ceasefire” or at the fact of a public announcement. It must ask what kind of ceasefire the record proves.\n\nThe official-source packet supplies the best answer. Russia’s official source, through Ushakov, accepted an initiative concerning a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.” The key agreement described there was a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange during May 9-11. On the Ukrainian official side, the direct presidential decree was not captured; the official-adjacent decree record is Red Square and parade-specific. Those facts do not prove a theatre-wide general pause. They prove a prisoner-exchange and Victory Day arrangement with a concrete parade-security component.\n\nPlaintiff’s own merits exhibits do not eliminate that limitation. PX-4 quotes Zelenskyy in the context of the 1,000-for-1,000 exchange and says a ceasefire regime must also be established. PX-5 reports the Trump announcement but also says Zelenskyy ordered no attack on Red Square and preserves the same prisoner-swap frame. Yes, those sources use broad language such as “suspension of all kinetic activity.” But broad media language must be weighed against the actual official-source detail, the missing primary captures, and what the parties did when the supposed general pause began.\n\nThat implementation evidence is decisive because it goes to character and scope, not merely breach. DX-4 reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued offensive operations across the frontline during the first day; combat intensity decreased but did not stop; Russian strikes continued in Kharkiv and Kherson; and the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions. Most tellingly, DX-4 reports that the only publicly known detail was Ukraine refraining from striking Red Square. DX-5 reports no calm in front line areas, mutual violation accusations, an unclear timeline, and Russian “response in kind.”\n\nPlaintiff says violations are only compliance. If this were a clearly defined general ceasefire followed by isolated breaches, that would be right. But the record shows something different: undefined conditions, the one clearly public operational term being Red Square, a prisoner-exchange purpose, and continued operations across the theater from day one. That is evidence that the arrangement never rose to the general pause required by the proposition.\n\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce caution. Direct X or Telegram, direct Truth Social or White House, and the direct Ukrainian decree remain absent. The rule allows credible media consensus, but consensus reporting does not override ambiguity in the official-source record and battlefield evidence. At most, plaintiff proved a fragile, short, U.S.-brokered truce label attached to Victory Day and a prisoner exchange. The market required more.\n\nOn a preponderance standard, if the evidence is equally consistent with a limited prisoner-exchange/parade-security pause and a qualifying general pause, plaintiff loses. Here the limiting evidence is stronger than equal. The council should find the proposition not proven.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and resolution criteria\n# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Official-source case-packet record\n# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Guardian both-sides confirmation report\nSource: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Ukrainian-side Zelensky confirmation report\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 RFE/RL Trump announcement and both-sides confirmation\nSource: RFE/RL, \"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \"suspension of all Kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \"cease-fire regime must also be established,\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\n\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule requiring general pause and excluding limited/humanitarian pauses\n# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-2 Official-source packet: Russian prisoner-exchange framing and narrow Ukrainian decree capture\n# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-3 Unresolved record gaps and known tension on scope/violations\n# Unresolved record gaps\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\n\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\n\nKnown record tension:\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \"general pause\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-4 NV/ISW: continued offensive operations and undefined ceasefire conditions\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\n\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\n\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n[defendant] DX-5 CBS/AP: mutual violation accusations and no calm on front lines\nSource: CBS News/AP, \"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\n\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \"even particularly trying to,\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\n\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\n\n[defendant] PX-4/DX-6 Zelenskyy report tying ceasefire regime to prisoner exchange\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\n\n[defendant] PX-5/DX-7 RFE/RL report with Red Square and adverse violation context\nSource: RFE/RL, \"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \"suspension of all Kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \"cease-fire regime must also be established,\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Guardian broad ceasefire confirmation\nSource: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May\". Published Fri 8 May 2026 21.07 EDT, first published 14.23 EDT. Captured text includes headline and article body stating: \"Both sides also confirm prisoner swap which Donald Trump announced along with suspension of all 'kinetic activity' between the warring states.\" The article reports that Donald Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from 9 to 11 May. It states that the US president said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides. The article reports that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Friday night, writing on Telegram: \"We received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\" It further reports Zelenskyy wrote that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners and that Ukraine expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements. The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap, quoting Kremlin foreign policy adviser Yuri Ushakov: \"I confirm the acceptability for the Russian side of the initiative just proposed by US president Donald Trump, concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article also notes both sides had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R2 Zelenskyy confirmation of ceasefire regime\nSource: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Zelenskyy says 1,000-for-1,000 POW swap will take place and confirms truce with Russia on 9-11 May.\" By Alona Mazurenko, 8 May 2026, 21:31. The article states that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange would take place on 9 May and confirmed an announcement by US President Donald Trump regarding a truce with Russia on 9-11 May. The article identifies its source as Zelenskyy on X (Twitter) and quotes him: \"That is why today [8 May - ed.], within the framework of the negotiating process mediated by the American side, we received Russia's agreement to conduct a prisoner exchange in the format of 1,000 for 1,000. A ceasefire regime must also be established on 9, 10 and 11 May.\" The article adds that Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare the exchange and thanked President Trump and his team for diplomatic involvement, saying Ukraine expected the United States to ensure that the Russian side fulfilled these agreements. It also quotes Zelenskyy that Red Square was less important than the lives of Ukrainian prisoners who could be brought home. The article notes in background that Trump had announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R3 RFE/RL both-side confirmation and adverse context\nSource: RFE/RL, \"Trump Announces 3-Day Cease-Fire In Russia-Ukraine War; Zelenskyy Vows No Red Square Attacks.\" By RFE/RL, May 08, 2026 08:39 CET, updated 20:55 CET. The article states that US President Donald Trump announced a three-day cease-fire in the war between Russia and Ukraine, with both sides quickly confirming they had agreed to the truce along with a major prisoner swap. It reports Trump's May 8 Truth Social post announcing a \"THREE DAY CEASEFIRE (May 9th, 10th, and 11th) in the War between Russia and Ukraine.\" The article states Trump added that the truce would include \"suspension of all Kinetic activity\" and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each side. It reports that Zelenskyy, in a Telegram post, confirmed he had agreed to a prisoner swap and said the three-day \"cease-fire regime must also be established,\" and that he ordered his military not to attack Red Square during the May 9 Victory Day military parade. It also states that Putin aide Yury Ushakov followed with a statement saying Russia had agreed to the three-day cease-fire and the exchange of prisoners. Adverse/context language: the article says it earlier appeared that a Kremlin-proposed Victory Day cease-fire had collapsed within hours, with Ukraine and Russia reporting hundreds of violations a day before the parade; it also reports drone/artillery/missile strikes and retaliatory-strike claims around the period.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R4 Defendant NV/ISW exhibit showing compliance dispute, not no agreement\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\n\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\n\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R5 Defendant CBS/AP exhibit showing both sides appeared to agree\nSource: CBS News/AP, \"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\n\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \"even particularly trying to,\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\n\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 NV/ISW: continued operations and unclear conditions as scope evidence\nSource: The New Voice of Ukraine, \"ISW says Russia used ceasefire to reinforce positions,\" 10 May 2026, 09:30 AM. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: NV reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued conducting offensive operations across the frontline during the first day of the May 9-11 ceasefire, although fighting intensity decreased, citing the Institute for the Study of War's May 9 assessment. NV states Ukraine's General Staff reported 51 combat engagements along the frontline on May 9 and that Russian forces continued strikes against Kharkiv Oblast and Kherson Oblast. NV also reports Russia's Defense Ministry claimed Ukrainian forces committed 8,970 ceasefire violations.\n\nNV further reports that Ukraine/Russia reports and NASA monitoring data indicated combat activity on May 9, especially in northern Ukraine, declined but did not stop completely. It says ISW noted the ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, and that the only publicly known detail was that Ukraine would refrain from striking Red Square during the Victory Day parade, a condition Kyiv upheld. NV states ISW concluded mutual accusations and continued localized fighting on May 9 showed that a ceasefire lacking clear mechanisms, reliable third-party monitoring, dispute resolution, and troop withdrawals was unlikely to be sustainable.\n\nNV also reports ISW found Russian forces used the ceasefire period for rotations, reinforcements, redeployment, and logistics improvements across the frontline in preparation for future offensives, and expected Russian forces to continue regrouping on May 10 and 11. The article notes President Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire on May 8 and that President Zelenskyy later confirmed the agreement and planned 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 CBS/AP: mutual violations, unclear timeline, no calm on front line\nSource: CBS News/AP, \"Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating U.S.-brokered ceasefire,\" May 10, 2026, 1:44 PM EDT. Accessible page capture via web.run on 2026-06-30.\n\nRelevant captured content: CBS/AP reports that Russia and Ukraine swapped accusations of breaking a U.S.-brokered ceasefire on Sunday, with both sides claiming casualties in drone and artillery strikes over the prior 24 hours. It states President Trump had announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine would swap 1,000 prisoners as part of a three-day ceasefire coinciding with Russia's Victory Day observance.\n\nCBS/AP reports President Zelenskyy said Russia was neither observing the truce nor \"even particularly trying to,\" and that there had been no calm in front line areas despite a lull in large-scale attacks. CBS/AP further reports Ukrainian regional officials said one person was killed and others injured by Russian artillery and drone attacks in the prior 24 hours.\n\nThe article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense accused Kyiv of more than 1,000 ceasefire violations, claimed Ukrainian forces attacked civilian targets in Russian regions and Russian military positions on the front line, and said Russian forces responded in kind. CBS/AP states the timeline of the three-day pause was somewhat unclear, while Trump had said fighting would be suspended from Saturday through Monday and both sides appeared to agree. The article also reports that Ushakov said Moscow remained fixed on its demand that Kyiv withdraw from eastern Donbas and that previous ceasefires had failed to produce tangible results amid deep mistrust.\n\n[defendant] DX-S3 Official-source packet: prisoner-exchange and Red Square framing\n# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-S4 Market rule requiring a general pause, not limited/humanitarian arrangements\n# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Guardian May 8 2026 report: Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire (ev_236dce43c3d8_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-236dce43c3d8)\nSource: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\nSHA-256: `236dce43c3d8f0a768feb3c9aa5e4214f9afb219b3cc647e8679b1179e916c6c`\nBytes: 1583\nRelevance: Credible media report that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-11 ceasefire, suspension of kinetic activity, and prisoner swap; directly addresses public mutual agreement and scope.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026: Zelenskyy confirms truce with Russia on May 9-11 (ev_2c8cd49d9b00_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-2c8cd49d9b00)\nSource: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033888/\nSHA-256: `2c8cd49d9b0040da3a58b04496b028fae6de5fb2b66b02d1f9b68b7bb84bbcac`\nBytes: 1248\nRelevance: Ukrainian media report based on Zelenskyy on X/Twitter confirming Russia's agreement and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11; addresses Ukrainian-side public confirmation.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] RFE/RL May 8 2026: Trump announces three-day cease-fire; both sides confirm (ev_5d2cebff6f4b_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2cebff6f4b)\nSource: https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-russia-victory-day-cease-fire-drone-attacks/33752482.html\nSHA-256: `5d2cebff6f4b0f521cbfa77b06da6f8548e1352caa5fc5983a21cf59c675b46a`\nBytes: 1405\nRelevance: Report preserving Trump announcement, confirmation by both sides, suspension of kinetic activity, prisoner swap, and adverse context of earlier violations; addresses official public agreement and scope/compliance distinction.\n\n[defendant arguments] NV May 10 2026 report on ISW assessment: fighting continued during first day of ceasefire (ev_52a3277a9302_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-52a3277a9302)\nSource: https://english.nv.ua/russian-war/isw-says-fighting-continued-despite-may-9-11-ceasefire-50606640.html\nSHA-256: `52a3277a93024fbf92cdd1f34c2ebf0ee4a62600c40ffa7809cd520718baba32`\nBytes: 1823\nRelevance: Shows adverse implementation and scope evidence: offensive operations continued across the frontline, combat declined but did not stop, ceasefire lacked clearly defined conditions, only known condition was Red Square non-targeting, and Russian forces allegedly used the period to reinforce positions.\n\n[defendant arguments] CBS/AP May 10 2026: Russia and Ukraine accuse each other of violating ceasefire (ev_d5ef4e09892f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-d5ef4e09892f)\nSource: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/russia-ukraine-accuse-each-other-ceasefire-violations/\nSHA-256: `d5ef4e09892f541e4806e0e6d705f5472ab9890cf4567bf47bf3a56b73f03dd8`\nBytes: 1606\nRelevance: Shows contemporaneous post-agreement evidence that both sides accused each other of violations, Zelenskyy said there was no calm on front lines despite a lull in large-scale attacks, and the ceasefire timing was unclear; bears on whether the arrangement was a general pause rather than fragile/limited truce.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and capture ledger\nPlaintiff searched official and source-specific paths for the May 8-11 ceasefire record. Successful captures submitted as evidence: Guardian May 8 report, Ukrainska Pravda May 8 Zelenskyy confirmation report, and RFE/RL May 8 Trump/both-sides confirmation report. Existing case-packet evidence supplies market criteria and a Kremlin official-source summary. Capture limits: direct X pages for Zelenskyy and WhiteHouse rendered no text in web open; PBS returned 403; Ukrinform opened without readable lines; ISW May 8/May 11 direct pages returned 403; earlier curl to the Kremlin page timed out. These failures leave some primary-source gaps, but the accepted captures preserve the material source-chain content and include adverse context on alleged violations.\n\n[defendant] Defendant source-search and capture ledger\nAt merits, defendant inspected the new plaintiff evidence and searched targeted terms for May 9-11 ceasefire scope, violations, and ISW assessments. Source targets included ISW May 9-11 assessments, accessible media captures of those assessments, and contemporaneous violation reports. Defendant submitted accepted captures from NV/ISW and CBS/AP. Direct primary social/official sources remain incompletely captured in the record, including direct Zelenskyy X/Telegram, Trump Truth Social/White House, and president.gov.ua decree text; those gaps affect weight because plaintiff relies heavily on secondary captures for scope.\n\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff rebuttal evidence audit\nPlaintiff inspected the two new defendant exhibits by stat/read_evidence_range. Both primarily address implementation: continued operations, violation accusations, unclear mechanisms, and weak monitoring. Both also preserve or concede agreement facts: Trump announced the May 9-11 ceasefire, Zelenskyy confirmed, and both sides appeared to agree. No additional outside source was needed for this targeted rebuttal.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T03:06:22.654219585Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C5","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C5","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":887016,"role_id":"council","turn_number":13},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":18,"version":29}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782787895642}]}
