tivity suspension.\n\nMilitary operations persisted, with both sides continuing combat engagements. The absence of a clear, defined mechanism for the ceasefire further undermines the plaintiff's claim of a broad military halt. The evidence points to a limited, fragile arrangement rather than a comprehensive cessation of hostilities.\n\nISW's assessment reveals a lack of precise conditions, with the single concrete requirement being the avoidance of striking Red Square. This suggests a narrow, carefully negotiated agreement rather than a widespread military pause. The prisoner exchange framing and narrow official decree reinforce the interpretation of a targeted, limited arrangement.\n\nThe evidence indicates a temporary tactical deconfliction, not a substantive halt to the broader conflict. The preponderance of information supports a conclusion that this was a constrained ceasefire with specific, limited objectives.\n\nThe council should find the proposition was not demonstrated.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"functions.mcp:1","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted evidence shows a publicly announced May 9-11 truce, but the preponderance of the record demonstrates it was a limited arrangement, not a general pause. Russian official framing tied the ceasefire to a prisoner exchange purpose; the Ukrainian presidential decree was limited to Red Square targeting; and implementation evidence shows continued operations across the front"},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\": \"aar_submit_council_vote\", \"args\": \"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"not_demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"The admitted evidence shows a publicly announced May 9-11 truce, but the preponderance of the record demonstrates it was a limited arrangement, not a general pause. Russian official framing tied the ceasefire to a prisoner exchange purpose; the Ukrainian presidential decree was limited to Red Square 